@Node "Words" "Some words from the editor"

@{B} Welcome to the 8th issue of The Demo.Guide!@{UB}

 As usual strange things have happened since the previous guide,
 fortunately (hopefully) all of these changes have lead to something good.
 To begin with I'll mention the new rating system that replaces the old
 one. Why? Because the old one got quite complicated after a while with all
 those half points, and the fact that no demo seemed to reach a
 ******-rating (which is the absolute maximum). The new rating system is
 more simple, but still I believe it to be at least as good as the old one.
 The rules are simple too: It ranges from non (-) to four (****) points, no
 half points are present. No *'s means, of course, that the demo is
 absolutely crap! Crazy demos and fast productions are the most common
 demos in this category. One star means that the demo may have some good
 elements, but the general quality is not the best possible (however, even
 a bad demo may have a huge entertainment value). ** mean an okay demo,
 some good some bad, usually worth watching. *** mean a good, or even very
 good demo, watch it! **** is the real state of the art demos, those you
 can watch over and over, enjoy the music, graphics, design, code, etc. for
 a looong time.

 The number of screenshots have suddenly increased dramatically, meaning
 (in short terms) that when you don't understand what we write in the
 review, just look at the pictures... Currently there's only screenshots
 from about 80 of the demos, but it's still increasing. Look out for
 Demo.Guide- and picture-archive updates at Aminet (demo/mag)!

 This time my dear co-editor DareDevil haven't written any reviews,
 therefore only about 35 reviews are added. Instead you get a bunch of
 screenshots as described above.

 The hardware requirements has grown lately. It's not long ago 4 MB
 fast-RAM was adequate for almost all demos, the really wild ones even
 needed 6 or 8. Now it seems as if you need at least a block of 16 MB to
 run the newest demos. Some parties keep raising the requirements limit,
 and why shouldn't the coders use the oppertunity?
 If you have a block of 16 MB or more that you want to give away, then
 don't hesitate to send it to me! In that way I'll also be able to review
 the newest demos!

 As always we are pleased to receive any kind of response, suggestions,
 ideas, bug reports, inside information, etc., or just an e-mail to let us
 know if you like The Guide. New hardware, demos and loads of money are,
 however, things that we prefer the most. A postcard is fine too! :-)

 Finally: A new guy is about to support The Guide with a lot of party
 results. That means that (if everything work out well) the next issue will
 contain lists of party results, of course with links to the reviews.
 His name is Jani Kannisto, he's Finnish and freak. Welcome!

 But for now you have to settle with this 8th issue. Enjoy!

                                                   On behalf of TDG,
                                                       @{" Dreyer " link "DRD"}

 And remember: Spread the word... And the Guide!

                         @{" Return to MAIN MENU " link "MAIN"}
@EndNode


@Node "Editors" "Info on the editors"

A little info on the editor:

@{" Dreyer " link "DRD"}
---------

@{B}Name:@{UB} Dreyer (!)
@{B}Handle:@{UB} Dreyer (!!)
@{B}Age:@{UB} 20
@{B}Birthday:@{UB} 13th February, 1978
@{B}Hobbies:@{UB} Scene, music, drawing, my aquarium (!)

@{B}Groups:@{UB} .sPOOn., Blasphemy (PeeCee), sUBSCURe
@{B}Ex-groups:@{UB} .sPOOn.
@{B}Task:@{UB} Musician, main-editor of The Demo.Guide
@{B}Famous productions:@{UB} The Demo.Guide
@{B}Biggest succes:@{UB} No. 3 in the music compo at The Summer Party '96
                (12 competed...)

 @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Dreyer.Gif"} Click here to see me (don't really look like me, but it is!)

@{B}Biography:@{UB}
Born in Copenhagen in 1978, moved to Ĺrhus three years later, the place
where I still live. I went to public school for ten years, joined the
highschool 1994 (I guess) and graduated three years later. For a couple of
month afterwards I was unemployed (lots of time for the Scene!), but I was
low on cash, so I got a job in a printing house (I was the one doing the
dirty work...). Returning from a vacation II found out that I was fired
which was a goood thing (TM) as my boss was a mean bastard who didn't
really gave a shit about the employees, only thinking about money.
Currently I haven't really got a job, just a couple of hours in a video
shop.
Also, I'm writing for Denmark's biggest, best (and only) Amiga Magazine
(both Scene stuff and other articles).

@{B}Scene story:@{UB}
In 1988 or '89 I bought an A500 with some programs, games and a joystick
(and of course a TV-modulator), and a couple of years later I made my first
ugly tunes, I remember I used Sonix for a short period of time, but as so
many others I ended up with Noisetracker, then Startrekker (amazing - eight
channels!), then ProTracker, and finally the great DigiBooster Pro which I
use currently.
In 1995 (more or less) I joined Blasphemy. Some guys I met at highschool
was about to make a group, they needed a musician. Unfortunately a PeeCee
group, but... I joined .sPOOn. sometimes afterwards (as double-member), but
they died shortly after. In late 1997 .sPOOn. was reborn and I'm a member
there once again. Also I'm a member of sUBSCURe who concentrates on making
wilddemos.
In 1996 I bought an A1230 with some extra RAM and a HD, which was the
ideal computer for the Scene which had gone AGA a long time ago.

@{B}The Demo.Guide:@{UB}
Early 1997 (as far as I remember) The Demo.Guide was born. I started
reviewing the demos found on my HD, then trying to get hold of as many
other demos as possible. NoName/Sector 7^Haujobb was at the same time about
to make a @{" demo CD " link "DemoCD"}, and as he liked The Guide he wanted to include it on the
CD. I travelled to Germany to visit him (back then he was a complete
stranger) and there I got @{B}a lot@{UB} of demos! I haven't made my way through
them yet, far from I'm afraid. But I'm working on it...

                                                                @{B}Dreyer@{UB}


@{" DareDevil " link "DRD"}
------------

@{B}Name:@{UB} Gaetano Campagna
@{B}Handle:@{UB} DareDevil
@{B}Age:@{UB} 26
@{B}Birthday:@{UB} 13th May, 1972 (luckily it was a Saturday!)

@{B}Group:@{UB} Amiga Group Italy
@{B}Task:@{UB} Co-editor of The Demo.Guide
@{B}Famous productions:@{UB} The Demo.Guide (from issue 5)

@{B}Biography:@{UB}
Born in Bari, Italy, in 1972, I never moved from here. I went to public
school for thirteen year, and I take a diploma as Industrial Technician in
Computer Science. This mean that I should be a programmer :).
I worked as technician at a cash registers retailer, but I no longer has
this job. I might start working in a computershop.

 @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Gaetano.Gif"} Click here to see the Devil himself!

@{B}Scene story:@{UB}
In 1986 I had my first computer, a Commodore 64, on which I started to
collecting some strange and wonderful programs completely useless, full of
colour effects on border, with a scrolltext full of crap, bouncing sprites
and in most cases cool musics ripped from various games and made by peoples
like Rob Hubbard, Martin Galway, Maniacs of Noise, Chris Huelsback, Ben
Daglish, Fred and Matt Gray and so on.
Some of you do remember "Hubbard the barbar", "Thrust concert" or "Can't
be"? Ah, good old times! In 1991 I sold my C64 (and all my demo-collection,
:~~~( sigh!) to buy an A500 on which... I started to collect the same
useless programs, but with fantastic musics and incredible effects (it was
1991 and I came from C64!!!) on which I amuse myself in ripping musics. I'm
speaking of things like Vision Megademo, The Bass Megademo 2, Quadlite Demo
and many others, most of than I've scratched from my disks when a friend
gave me "WOOOW" and especially "Cube-o-matic" by Spreadpoint. That was a
revelation for me about what is a REAL demo!
In 1994 I bought my A1200 and harddisk (20MB!) and I started a new
collection with AGA demos. Later my @{" equipment " link "equipment"} has been upgraded
drastically.

                                        Gaetano @{B}"DareDevil"@{UB} Campagna


                         @{" Return to MAIN MENU " link "MAIN"}
@Endnode



