@Node "cont" "How to help us"

You can contribute in many ways: Sending demos, reviews of demos and a copy
of the demo, error reports, your opinion about the guide, the comments
and/or the ratings, etc. Feel free to spread this guide as much as you
like! If you have any suggestions for changes please @{" contact us! " link "DRD"}
We could use some helping hands, eyes and ears (we're a couple of years
behind schedule...), so please send some test reviews of some demos, and
you might be the next top editor :)!
Also, if you have information that we haven't (often marked with a ?) about
release place and year and placing, who made it, etc., then tell us!
"Inside information" is very welcome too (good gossip everone likes!)!

How to send us demos: 1) By @{" snail-mail " link "DRD"}
                      2) By @{" E-mail: " link "DRD"} Attach the file(s) to an E-mail. The
                         max. filesize must not exceed more than 710 KB!
                         Use LHA, LZX or ZIP.
                      3) Tell @{" us " link "DRD"} where on The Net I can find the demo,
                         still the filesize must be under 710 KB!
                      4) Visit @{" us " link "DRD"}! Bring your complete demo collection
                         right to my door!

Now some guidelines for you who want to start reviewing demos:

1) You have to have seen the demo yourself! I want your opinion from you,
   and others' opinion from themselves! Not the other way around :-)!
2) Don't judge a demo by the name of the demo or by the group who made
   it! An unknown group can also be able to make a great production!
3) Don't judge the demo on one or two categories only, there's a lot to
   think about: The code, graphic, music, design, timing, length, variation
   etc. Consider the entertainment value.
4) Is the machine that is running the demo a wild animal or is it just an
   "ordinary" Amiga? Of course the routines look fastest on the fast
   machines, please consider this when rating (especially concerning the
   code).
5) Don't be blinded by the good effects, graphic or music. Rate the demo as
   an overall of the demo. Are you entertained?
6) Be neutral.

Note: Do NOT edit this guide yourself! Contact @{" me " link "DRD"} to become editor.


                   @{" Addresses & E-mail " link "DRD"}  @{" Return to MAIN MENU" link "main"}


@EndNode


@Node "GeneralInfo" "General information on topics"

The editor that reviews a demo is the one that rates it. If other editors
disagree with the rating (s)he can either discuss it with the first editor,
or (s)he can put up a veto-box with his/hers opinion in it.
The main-editor is the supreme judge and therefore able to change any
rating as he pleases :-)

All reviews that has no signature as the last line is written by
@{" main-editor Dreyer " link "DRD"}, while all reviews that have a signature is written by
that person, of course. Typically that is @{" co-editor DareDevil " link "DRD"}.

We don't want to hurt or offend anyone, so don't take it personally if we
say that your demo sucks - that's just the way it is :-). We guess that
most of the demo makers out there agree that they can actually get better.
It has nothing to do with the crew behind the demo.
Also, we don't dislike Polish people - only their crazy demos...

Now for the explanation of the @{B}topics in the reviews@{UB}:

@{B}Name:@{UB} The name of the demo!
@{B}Group:@{UB} The name(s) of the group(s) that created the demo!

@{B}Year:@{UB} The year the demo was released
@{B}Event:@{UB} At which event or happening was the demo released
@{B}Placing:@{UB} If the demo took part in a compo, which placing did it get

@{B}Size:@{UB} The demo's size (approximately) measured in megabytes.
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} What you need to run the demo!
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} What equipment is recommended to make the demo run well.
@{B}Note:@{UB} Special remarks that doesn't fit the three above mentioned
 categories.

@{B}Code:@{UB} The coder(s) who have coded the demo!
@{B}Graphic:@{UB} The graphician(s) who've drawn the graphic for the demo!
@{B}Music:@{UB} The musician(s) who've composed the music for the demo! (etc.)...
@{B}Objects:@{UB} The 3D-modellers creating the 3D-objects and 3D-scenes
@{B}Design:@{UB} The people who've designed the demo (usually this is the coder(s)
 and/or the graphician(s)

A few other categories can be found, they are rarely used and are (also)
self-explaning.

@{B}Rating:@{UB} The demos rating!

The @{B}ratings@{UB} go like this:

---- Crap! Avoid this!
*--- A quite bad demo!
**-- An average production, some good, some bad.
***- A good demo, worth watching more than once.
**** A magnificient demo! One you can watch over and over and over and...

Be aware that a demo that scores a low rating actually can be good! An
example is Depth's @{" Vi Elsker Darkhawk " link "Darkhawk"}! The code and design
suck, but still it's great!

@{B}+:@{UB} Good things about the demo!
@{B}-:@{UB} Bad things about the demo!

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Comments and description of the demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Conclusion... If you don't want to read the rest to find out if
  a demo is worth watching read this!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} Rumors, facts and the like about the demo and/or the
  crew behind it.

@{B}Note:@{UB} Thing you should be aware of

                         @{" Return to MAIN MENU " link "MAIN"}

@Endnode


