@Node "Brainstate" "Brain-State-in-a-Box / Cryptoburners"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Brain-State-in-a-Box
@{B}Group:@{UB} Cryptoburners

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 11

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.71 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM. To install on HD you'll
 probably need a patch

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nice routines
- Strange colors, few routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I guess this is one of the demos that the true techno freaks love,
 while the ones that dislike techno also dislikes this demo. It consists of
 no more than two or three routines, a quite fast color zoomer with a mess
 of various colors that are zoomed towards you or away from you, a fast
 fog voxel landscape (the part of it that are far away from you are either
 hidden in fog or in the dark), and a zooming rotator routine that might be
 a part of the color zoomer, they are combined, anyway. As mentioned the
 colors aren't exactly the best combination ever seen (everything from red
 to blue, from white to black are included), but when a blur routine is
 added to the zoomer, which happens now and then, it actually is quite
 nice. The demo changes between the two or three above mentioned routines,
 most of the time it is the color zoomer that is on, tends to get quite
 boring unless you've gone into some kind of trance before it starts to get
 dull. The music surely helps you getting into trance, for that's what it
 is, while the short flashes with pictures in between the routines probably
 convince your sub consciousness of something (for example: Vote for
 Cryptoburners! :)). The demo never ends (I guess), it just keeps looping
 the same routine and music again and again. Be careful not to fall into a
 trance when you're home alone, you might not be found again!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth having a look at. Is like LSD for some people, others
 just might get bored.

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/BrainstateInABox01.jpg"} "Interesting" title picture
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/BrainstateInABox02.jpg"} Psychedelic color zoomer effect
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/BrainstateInABox03.jpg"} The voxel landscape is very nice
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/BrainstateInABox04.jpg"} The voxel is zoomed away

@EndNode


@Node "Exile" "Exile / Desire"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Exile
@{B}Group:@{UB} Desire

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} For the HD-installer (which is needed to install the demo on
 HD) it requires: 0.5-1 MB chip-RAM, 1.5 MB fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Riox, Sacha
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Zoef, Dwel, Giz, Solid/Cryptoburners
@{B}Music:@{UB} Fabian, Antibody

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nothing special as it is an old, quite traditional demo
- Simple effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This is an old, quite traditional demo with everything that
 follows, good and bad. All the routines are quite simple seen with
 nowadays eyes, but still there are some of them that are quite nice.
 It begins with title pictures and the like that are shown according to the
 music, including the first effect: A fast line drawer routine. A quite
 nice transition leads us to the next routine, which is a blurred
 black/white rotator in a little box in the middle of the screen. A picture
 is shown afterwards, leading us to the next moving things, small three-
 colored cubes (about 10-12) flying randomly around with small pixel tails
 behind them. Another picture is on, again a pretty average one which goes
 for most of the graphic in the demo, and then there's a different scroll
 text, different because it's wrapped around an invisible ball. It's a bit
 difficult to read the colorful letters for the untrained scroll-reader,
 and also the ball is quite small, but the idea is good enough. Pixel
 effects are almost always nice, and the one in this demo is no exception.
 Quite traditional it draws different kinds of simple, symmetrical patterns
 and shapes, with a Desire logo shown next to it. Another picture, not too
 good, is on, then a fine little triangle-effect where a blurred triangle
 enters the screen, flies around for a short while, while it leaves a long
 tail behind it, a tail that doesn't disappear causing nice shapes made
 from small triangles to appear. The routine is on for a little too long to
 keep you attention, though. Finally we've reached the endscroller with a
 simple 3D-starfield in the background. Unlike many other demos (even
 though it is traditional) I only remember few black backgrounds, different
 kinds of colors (or what appear to be colors) are used instead.
 The music is a strange mixture of hiphop, heavy and techno, but it works.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a must see.

@EndNode


@Node "KurvaAnyad" "Kurva Anyad / Crimson Jihad"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Kurva Anyad
@{B}Group:@{UB} Crimson Jihad

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} AntIQ
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ? (Competed in the Lamer Demo Compo)

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?

@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Unreal
@{B}Music:@{UB} Lord
@{B}Design:@{UB} Crimson Jihad

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ The thoughts (?) behind the demo are good, multitasking
- Noisy sound, ugly graphic and animation

@{B}Comment:@{UB} One of those very ugly "demos" that contain no code, but small,
 crappy animations, for example a hand holding a glass of beer, something
 that could look like Bill Gates and a PeeCee getting smashed by a big
 shoe. The music is heavy metal, just some samples put together.
 No wonder why they call it a lamer demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Avoid!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} Was made in 7 hours at the party place.

@EndNode


@Node "Bebetotefofu" "Bebetotefofu? / Depth & Efreet"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Bebetotefofu?
@{B}Group:@{UB} Depth & Efreet

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Copenhagen Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 7 (but no. 1 in the "sponsor-compo")

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.56 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, '020 or better (don't know if it runs on '040 and '060)

@{B}Code:@{UB} Cytron/Depth, Blueberry/Efreet
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} hund./Depth, Cytron/Depth
@{B}Music:@{UB} Cytron/Depth

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nothing
- Advertising

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The demo is a so called Sponsor Demo, which means that it contains
 a lot of advertising for random companies, in this case Danish ones.
 While a lot of text is written on the screen a simple effect is shown, for
 example a zoomer, scroller or what looks like to be a bumpy window. The
 most complicated one is a picture that curls. All the effects are quite
 fast, but only few colors are used in the demo.
 The music is a melodic piece of jazz, quite good, fits the demo okay.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not really worth wasting time on.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} The idea with this demo was to make fun of TCP's
 main sponsor Betafon (Danish Amiga/PeeCee dealer). The point is that they
 (Depth) forget what they are to advertise for. Kind of an advanced kind of
 mud throwing demo creator Cytron says.
 At the prize giving Depth handed over the prize (which was much bigger
 than in the real Amiga demo compo) for this demo to the winner of the real
 compo that was won by IRIS with the demo @{" Kilkenny " link "Kilkenny"}.

@EndNode


@Node "Zif" "Zif / Parallax"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Zif
@{B}Group:@{UB} Parallax

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 15!

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.5 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} A4040/40 MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Simply, Debug
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mistral, Tukan
@{B}Music:@{UB} Legend

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some nice routines, pretty good design
- Better transitions would have been nice

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I guess it's really a matter of taste if this demo should have won
 the Assembly, personally I like a couple of other demos from that party,
 but the bottom line is that it did win the party with about 1/3 more votes
 than the second place. Still, it's a good demo, no question about that,
 and actually it contains two quite impressive routines, plus a lot of
 other good stuff. There are no of the routines that are directly bad, but
 some of them are a bit slow, that's why a '040 is recommended. Also the
 graphic is pretty good, so is the ambient techno music. All in all
 everything (more or less) seem to fit
 quite okay into the demo which starts with a title picture, which is
 shortly after used in a plasma. Unfortunately it's a bit slow, and so are
 the "fire"-letters that enter the screen afterwards. They spell the group
 name while rotating and zooming with a tale of what looks like a tail of
 fire after them. Basically it's just some vector letters that are put on
 fire, looks nice. The credits are up next, not just boring text screens,
 but two effects: The task is shown with rotating phong letters, while the
 names are shown with standard letters, then stretched away. The next
 effect is very cool, one of the best of its kind I've seen! It's a party
 twister build from what looks mostly like voxel, in fact it looks pretty
 much like a voxel landscape wrapped around a stick (just to give you an
 idea). Great. It's even better when colored lightsources start to pass by
 causing it to slowly change its color where the lightsources are. Both
 the resolution and speed are good, even on a '030/40 MHz. The same can't
 be said about the next routine, which is a texture mapped mask. The
 resolution is good, but the speed is unfortunate on less than an '040.
 A picture of an octopus is shown afterwards, and soon after an env-
 mapped glass slowly rotates in front of it. In opposite to the previous
 phong the resolution is now a bit low, while the speed is quite good.
 More phong is on next, a texture mapped blob, followed by a nice tunnel
 with hills coming out of its sides. It sometimes twists and the colors
 change creating a shadow effect. Another blob is shown next, this time
 it isn't phong, it rather looks as if it's build from the same routine
 that the party twister is build from. A little strange (but atmospheric)
 picture is shown afterwards, then more phong is presented, this time a
 very original object is used: A WV-bobble! The really exciting about this
 isn't the object itself, but its movement. It skids into the screen from
 the left, just like the cars in a good American action movie and exits
 only driving on its rear wheels... Finally we've reach the last routine,
 a good one too. At first it's what you'd believe to be a simple bumpmap
 routine, but shortly after it has started the map zooms away from the
 screen, and you discover that it's just one side of a column. And there
 are many columns in the wall-less "room". Very nice indeed.
 It all ends with a picture with the group's name written across it.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Recommended.

@EndNode


@Node "AlphaOmega" "Alpha Omega / Pure Metal Coders"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Alpha Omega
@{B}Group:@{UB} Pure Metal Coders

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1991
@{B}Event:@{UB} Amega Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 6

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.9 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Needs a fix to install on HD, my fix needs 0.5 MB chip-RAM,
 1.5 MB fast-RAM. Doesn't run on OS'es higher than 1.3 if it isn't patched,
 needs 1 MB RAM
@{B}Note:@{UB} There are some timing problems with this HD-fix

@{B}Code:@{UB} Cocy, Vanguard
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Ramjet
@{B}Music:@{UB} Peter
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Cocy, Vanguard

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice routines, beautiful trace
- The music doesn't fit the demo, no quit

@{B}Comment:@{UB} As mentioned above there are some timing problems with this demo
 when you run it on a A1200 and the like. Originally it's made for the good
 old Amigas (no AGA), but I haven't had the chance to test it on such.
 Anyway, it's not that bad and of course it will not affect the review or
 rating. One of the first thing you notice about this demo is the
 scrolltext in the bottom of the screen, and the CNN news line right above
 it. It's present almost all the time.
 The first routine is a vector doom routine (or animation?), no textures on
 the walls or anything, but with some colorful colors (?). After having
 spend some time walking around in those hallways you take off and discover
 that the walls are the letters PMC. Nice! Afterwards there are a lot of
 different vector objects of every kind, and then (after some depacking I
 guess) a beautiful raytraced animation appears, reminds me a lot of the
 one in Phenomena's Enigma, for those of you who haven't seen that one
 (you really should do yourself that favor to watch it) I can inform you
 that it's some transparent glass balls that reflect the fractal image
 beneath it. Simple, but great! And we stick to the fractal and animation,
 afterwards a little fractal zoomer is shown, it's quite smooth, but
 doesn't last for long before it is played backwards.
 I guess the people behind this demo are Star Wars fans (who aren't?), the
 3D vector objects and scenes shown as one of the last things in this demo
 are heavily inspired by the spacecrafts and the Death Star in Star Wars.
 Especially a sequence where you fly in a tunnel, then reaching a big room
 with some kind of pedestal in the middle reminds me of the scene in Return
 of the Jedi where the Death Star is blown up. Still no textures or fancy
 shadows are used, but what the hell, that was 1991!
 The demo ends with zooming letters that consist of letters that are
 zoomed that consist of letters that are zoomed that consist of letters
 that are zoomed that consist of letters that are zoomed, etc. :-)
 The graphic is difficult to judge, the timing problems do that the few
 logos in the demo are skipped, and the music doesn't fit the demo very
 well. It's way too happy and are unable to maintain the atmosphere that
 the visual part of the demo invites to. Too bad, but not a disaster.
 Anyway, as music used only for listening it's fine.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch it!

@EndNode


@Node "Q" "Q / Newage & Subspace"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Q
@{B}Group:@{UB} Newage & Subspace

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.14 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Coinfidence, Origo, Spite
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Spot.
@{B}Music:@{UB} Deelite
@{B}Ideas:@{UB} Gorg

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Original
- Short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is very different from almost all demos ever made, the
 reason is that it uses only two (2) colors: Dark green and black. All the
 effects are therefore dithered. Unfortunately there aren't many of them,
 but the ones that are present run very smooth. After some fast credits
 and texts the first routine is shown, it's a torus. Sounds simple (and is
 simple), but it's something completely different watching those raster
 effects instead of effects with hundred of colors, etc. Next routine is a
 zooming rotator and the last one is a fractal routine that is  difficult
 to see clearly because of the display. Also, a little naive "comic" is
 included. The music is a down-to-earth piece of rock, technically good,
 but nothing special.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Gets a little rating-point extra for its originality

@EndNode


@Node "Duel" "Duel / Genocide"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Duel
@{B}Group:@{UB} Genocide

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1993
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.47 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Smooth animation
- Short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} One of the shortest demos I have seen, and it isn't even a real
 demo. It's rather a short movie, actually a very famous movie: The
 fighting scene in Star Wars when Obiwan is "killed" by Vader. The
 animation consists of silhouettes of the fighters, accompanied by the
 real light sabre sound also taken directly from the movies. Only few
 colors are used and the movie takes place in a frameless square covering
 about 70% of the screen, but on the other hand everything moves smoothly
 and the resolution is quite acceptable. Too bad it's so short...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} I'd rather watch the real movie scene, but still try have a
 look, especially if you're a Star Wars freak

@EndNode


@Node "Episode" "Episode / Nah-Kolor"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Episode
@{B}Group:@{UB} Nah-Kolor

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Gravity
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 4...

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.62 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM. 4 MB fast-RAM, HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Kloo
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Fame, Lazur
@{B}Music:@{UB} Scorpik

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This production is one of those that takes most Amigas beyond what
 is possible to do. Unfortunately this isn't meant as anything positive, in
 fact this means that only Amigas equipped with a fast '040 processor or
 better will be able to enjoy the demo (if it works on those processors at
 all). The reason for all this complaining is the frame rate throughout
 most of the show, often it's below ten frames per second on a 1230-40MHz
 (which was used for this test), but then again I believe that it might
 have been made for the powerful MC's. Often two different routines are on
 at the same time (for example a phong object with a tunnel in the
 background), and the resolution is 1x1 throughout the whole demo (or maybe
 there are one effect which aren't in this resolution). To try to boost the
 speed a little Kloo has cut of the left and right edge of the display
 area, so that everything is shown in a square box. There are some effects
 that run at an acceptable speed, but without ever being really fast,
 though. The demo contains many different routines, most of them aren't
 shown for very long, so you're somewhat entertained all the time. However,
 nobody seems to have taken care of the design, so the constant stream of
 effects never really "catches" you, non of visual impressions you get from
 the demo relate to other of the demo's parts, luckily the techno/house
 music is there to hold the pieces together, even though it's a difficult
 job. It doesn't succeed completely, but somewhat saves it from being a
 total mess. Just to mention some of the effects (I will only mention the
 most interesting ones) I could describe the very first routine: A nice
 combination of four or five different effects, that is rotating,
 stretching, zooming, bumpmapped plasma! In front of this the credits are
 shown, or more correctly most of them are shown, because the rightmost
 letters seem to have disappeared beyond the display area's border. If this
 is so called design or if it's an error is an unanswered question, but I
 tend to believe in the last of the two possibilities. The reason why is
 that some of the later effects have also gone over the border, but instead
 of just disappearing they appear on the other side of the screen...
 Anyway, the effect is good, but lasts to short I guess. The title is shown
 afterwards using a colored bumpmap, almost looking like a piece of
 tinfoil. One of the best routines in the demo (maybe except for the start
 effect) is a view over the ocean. Nah-Kolor have made a quite realistic
 water effect, looks just like if you're standing on a dune near the beach
 looking over the ocean. Another interesting effect is a voxel vulcan where
 lava slowly appears from the top of it running down its sides. This
 routine is slow though, the colors few and would probably have looked
 better if some small pixel explosions could be added, we want a real
 eruption (waiting for the PPC to come!)! The last effect in the demo is
 some kind of Doom routine where you're flying around in a wall-less room
 filled with square columns with different pictures or animations on them.
 On the texts that are presented in the bottom of each effect it says
 something about some bumpmap and mirrors, but to be honest this is
 difficult to see, maybe if you look very closely, but... The speed is
 surprisingly good (still it's not more than acceptable, though).
 The demo is generally rather colorful, but somehow the palette doesn't
 seem to have been used to its full extend, sometimes causing bad color
 fades. This combined with the "design" and the bugs leave a not too
 positive impression of this demo, but the music pulls it up a little. Also
 the pictures presented drags it up a little, unfortunately non of them
 fits the demo very well (or else they both do because it's such a mess
 already!), but seen as single pictures there are mostly positive things to
 say about them. Especially Lazur's contribution (I believe it took part at
 one of The Party's GFX compos) is a beauty.
 Despite the lack of design and the messy look many of the effects are
 actually worth having a look at, especially on fast machines. A standard
 A1200 is totally out of the question though, but then again isn't it
 always nowadays?

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch once...

@EndNode


@Node "InAWorldofAscii" "In a World of Ascii"

@{B}Name:@{UB} In a World of Ascii
@{B}Group:@{UB} Impact DK

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 13 of 22

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.62 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} The Priest, Zip, Fazion
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Morph
@{B}Music:@{UB} Unison
@{B}Animation:@{UB} The Priest
@{B}Ideas:@{UB} The Priest, Fazion, Unison

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ The idea is great
- The effects are very old and common

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A very unusual demo. It is a demonstration where the effects that
 are usually shown with "normal" graphic, are converted so that they use
 characters instead, and all run in a Cli-window!
 After a little introduction text the demo starts with some '*' stars that
 are formed as a 3D "wireframed" cube in rotation on all of its axis and a
 dot circular tunnel made with 'O' letters. Then a full window zooming
 mandelbrot fractal picture, made with ANSI chars that explode in a big ANSI
 star, is shown. After the credits and a picture (everything is the work of
 the ASCII artist Morph) a strange partial scrolltext rotates and zooms
 an "IMPACT DK" logo, afterwards it explodes resulting in hundred of *.
 Then, after some "shading chars", a great ANSI animation realized with
 Scenery Animator and converted to chars fills the window. Now the most
 "difficult" effects made (they say) is on using system routines: Seven
 ANSI vectorballs zooms and rotates into the window, and a cool ANSI filled
 and ligthsourced 3D cube appears. At last an "endcli" command stops the
 demo and starts the greetings-part this time in normal bitmap on some
 dotted fractal backgrounds (hey... and the ASCII?).
 The first piece music is a normal piece in demo style well synchronized
 with effects, and the greetings music is a quite good remake of Martin
 Galways's Parallax highscore tune from the C64.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Do you work on a BBS screen every day? You'll love it!
 Others you won't appreciate it too much. Worth watching only ones.

  - Daredevil

@EndNode


@Node "DrugVanillaSyndrome" "Drug Vanille Syndrome / Darkage"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Drug Vanille Syndrome
@{B}Group:@{UB} Darkage

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Italian Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 2

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.02 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50MHz or '040/25MHz (if it runs on such thing)

@{B}Code:@{UB} Modem, Washburn
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Decibel, KaosMaster
@{B}Music:@{UB} FBY
@{B}Design:@{UB} Modem

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nothing, everything is pretty average
- Strange (non-existing?) design, some routines are a bit slow, pictures
  are below average

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I must admit that I wasn't very entertained when watching this
 demo. First of all the "design" is, to be nice, different (to be honest:
 non-existing), and also the routines have all been seen better before.
 Every single effect is using colors that don't match anything else in
 rest of the demo, which results in a big color mess. Only if the effects
 are watched separately you might think it's nice, but watched one by one
 as in a typical demo (like this one) there's nothing to hold it together.
 The many different logos and pictures, different especially concerning
 style and quality, only make the design worse. The graphic isn't exactly
 state of the art, to be positive one could say that it's different. Also
 the pretty well timed music, won't be remembered in the next century, but
 has its bright moments. It's a piece that consists of both an atmospheric
 tune and a techno tune, it changes to the appropriate kind of music when
 needed according to the demo. More or less successful.
 The routines are a simple tunnel with ugly textures, a nice "old-glass"
 effect, some kind of plasma that looks like watching a picture through
 old-fashioned glass, traditional phong and simple 2D-metaballs.
 The effect that really saves this demo is a transparent phong object (a
 bend torus) that morphs into a blob and back again a couple of times,
 while the background zooms and rotates. The speed is quite good which is
 rather impressive, especially concerning that it runs in 1x1. Still I
 wonder about the choice of colors. Also worth mentioning is a very short
 looping 3D-animation where you are walking up a stair, not that it is so
 very good, but at least you don't see that every day in a demo...
 All in all a demo where nothing really seems to fit, anyway the parts that
 works are worth watching.

                                                                Dreyer


@{B}Comment:@{UB} This is the first real demo released by Darkage, after many
 intros, and it is nothing exceptional. Yes, it is well coded, it has good
 graphics with some woman faces pictures by Decibel made in an attractive
 and sober style, it conatins good music by FBY that mix atmosphere and
 techno in a pleasant way, but that's all, and is not enough.
 In this demo you can see - after the intro pictures - a very colourful
 tunnel, smeared bump mapping on a picture, a really cool 3D env-mapped
 object rotating on a rotozooming base, a 3D gouraud shaded Darkage logo,
 a raytraced animation of a winding stair, some blobs (bobs with a good
 effect of cross light sum), and the final scrolltext.
 No new effects, and a below average design too.
 What a pity! Maybe better synchronized music (but not with that music),
 would be very useful to make this demo more attractive.
                                                                DareDevil

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A common demo. There are better demos out there for sure!

@EndNode


@Node "EspenBredesen" "Espen bredesen / Dual Crew Shining"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Espen Bredesen
@{B}Group:@{UB} Dual Crew Shining

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1997

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.42 MB

@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, '020 or better (don't know if it runs on '040 and '060)
@{B}Code:@{UB} Deetsan
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} B., Blank, Boost
@{B}Music:@{UB} Carebear

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Hmmm...
- Monotone

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A strange little demo that only contains (more or less) one
 effect, phong in yellow and pink colors, butterflies (!?) and backgrounds
 from beneath the surface of the sea (scans).
 The show starts with a zooming and slowly rotating DCS logo which is
 shortly after taken over by a phong routine with different transparent
 shapes flying around, and thanks to the few colors used in the demo they
 look a bit strange, the colors don't fade right. Butterflies are on next,
 lots of them with fast moving wings. And it continues like this a couple
 of minutes, phong and butterflies... And then, after the credits, it ends.
 The music is believed to be some kind of hiphop variation, not a success
 (hiphop rarely is), but has the same quality level as rest of the demo...
 I still wonder about the title...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For people that tends to like strange demos, insects and
 scooping!

@EndNode


@Node "3Seconds" "3 Seconds of Delight / Movement"

@{B}Name:@{UB} 3 Seconds of Delight
@{B}Group:@{UB} Movement

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ----

+ "Interesting" reset function
- This is not a real demo, just advertising or similar, no quit

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The name of this short demo is more or less well chosen. More
 because it really is short, more than 3 seconds, still not much more than
 10-15 seconds, less because of the "Delight" word. It sure is not a
 delight watching this production that is to short to be called a demo,
 and it does not have any routines in it. The only that happens is that
 three different mostly brown screens with some text on them are shown,
 then it starts all over again. The music is a very distorted piece of
 electric church music, strange.
 You can't quit the demo by pressing the mouse or ESC, but when you reset
 another part starts, also just some text, but with a slightly different
 design, and the music in this part is techno. When you reset again you
 really reset!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Forget it, I guess it is a 3 second production!

@EndNode


@Node "StrangeDays" "Strange Days / Venture"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Strange Days
@{B}Group:@{UB} Venture

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Intel Outside 3
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 19

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.37 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} Noster, Pippen
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Korbatz, Majkel
@{B}Music:@{UB} Wierza

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ There's a message in the demo!
- The demo doesn't seem to be a perfect work of art, the code is a bit
  slow, the music a class or two below the "professional" demo music
  (but is atmospheric)

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The demo starts with a black/white movie with a pretty low frame
 rate and poor picture quality, while an atmospheric piece of music that
 could need some polishing, plays in the background. A quite violent movie,
 and that's what the demo is about: Violence, death and destruction.
 After the moviepart some more "normal" demo effects are shown, spiced up
 with lots of pictures presenting war, famine, death, etc. The effects are
 slow phongs, traditional bumpmap, a tunnel with mountains coming out of
 its sides and the like, pretty much the usual stuff, seen faster before!
 The music isn't state of the art, but still it's good for creating some
 kind of gloomy atmosphere that somewhat saves the demo a little.
 And by the way, this demo really has got a (sensible) message!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For people with fast processors!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB}
 - The pictures in the demo were leeched from CNN's homepage, then
   processed
 - Venture thought about releasing this demo on Somewhere in Holland, but
   decided not to, as most of the crew was going to IO3 anyway.
 - They started working on this demo about two weeks before the party.

@EndNode


@Node "GetTough" "Get Tough / Apathy (UK)"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Get Tough
@{B}Group:@{UB} Apathy (UK)

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Was supposed to be released at Kindergarten, but due to personal
       problems it wasn't
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.31 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Runs on all AGA machines

@{B}Code:@{UB} Wizzball
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Lazur, Sunscream, various PD libraries
@{B}Music:@{UB} Christian Alfs, Maze

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Fast routines
- Mostly simple routines, graphics from PD libraries

@{B}Comment:@{UB} If somebody asked me when this demo was released and I didn't
 know, I would have guessed it was in the early '90s, but as written
 above it's from 1997. The reason of this mis-judgement is that the
 routines are all quite simple, and the only thing that could indicate that
 this is not a non-AGA demo, is, of course, the colors used, even though I
 guess it's hard to see that it actually uses a full 256 color palette.
 The show starts with the demo's name and title fading in, followed by a
 nice picture exposed to a plasma working only on the y-axis. The next
 routine is a simple grid cube with a couple of blurry lines after it. This
 part is on for a long time, unfortunately, because it is so simple and is
 unable to keep even a hardcore old-Scener interested for very long. After
 a while it starts flashing from the current effect to one where the cube
 is checked (transparent/purple) and back again, it does this a couple of
 times. A very nice picture by Lazur is on, and like the other pictures in
 the demo it seems to have been chosen randomly, it has nothing to do with
 anything else in the demo. A simple, low-res "wrap-around-a-ball" routine
 is the next moving thing, that is, the ball doesn't move, the picture
 does. After a while small balls start appearing in front of the big ball,
 quite uninteresting as long as it's just a copy of the big ball instead of
 mirroring it or similar. Two 3D vector objects (so it seems) are on next,
 but actually there are more, as one of them starts to fall apart into
 several spinning fragments. For a demo from 1997 this isn't too fancy, it
 would have been 5-6 years ago I guess... A scanned B/W picture is on
 before a fast, low-res rotator takes over. Doesn't look too nice because
 it is quite "grumsy", but the speed somewhat saves it. Finally we have
 reached the endscroller, a simple 3D-starfield zoom towards you in the
 background in this part.
 The music in the main part is techno that tends to be quite monotone. In
 the endpart it's a nice little chiptune.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not really worth watching

@EndNode


@Node "Ritual" "Ritual / Limited Edition"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Ritual
@{B}Group:@{UB} Limited Edition

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Non, was supposed to be released at Assembly '97, but it wasn't
       finished in time...
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.56 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 4 MB RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} PG, Dew
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Pad, MRK, Skize
@{B}Music:@{UB} Lord Epithal
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Skize
@{B}Design:@{UB} Skize, PG

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice ideas, some good routines, atmospheric music
- Needs a lot of CPU power

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is far from the usual LED productions, both concerning
 speed and concept. For those who don't know LED's normal style I'll tell
 you that it's fast, colorful and quite entertaining demos. This demo is
 almost the opposite, that is slow, few colors and, in my opinion, not too
 entertaining. But scary! Pentagrams, a ghost and an atmospheric, gloomy
 soundtrack makes this demo one of the most scary ones yet!
 The show starts with some kind of lightsourced plasma (pretty nice)
 followed by the group's name, credits (shown with a smooth blur morph
 routine) and the title. A lightspot effect in fog, one of those that
 points towards the viewer, so that you can follow the rays that appear
 around the invisible pentagram. Not the best I've seen, but there's
 something interesting about it anyway, hard to say exactly what it is.
 A picture of an eye is on afterwards, and shortly after a slow moving
 animation is shown in the eye, including a clock that lead us to the next
 effect: A 3D-scene including an old clock, but more important a
 transparent ghost that looks furious. Everything moves pretty slow on a
 '030 and '040 I guess, but on the other hand the resolution is quite good.
 Also, in this scene the very atmospheric, scary music (as taken from a
 horror movie!) changes to mostly sound effects, rain and thunder.
 More 3D is on afterwards, a fast tunnel where we're moving around studying
 the nice texture on its wall. Too bad that you're unable to see very far
 into the tunnel, but Dew must have given the speed the highest priority,
 bad for '060 owners, good for mortals :). A texture mapped 3D object in
 water has been seen before, but anyway it's also present in this demo.
 Unfortunately this one is not as good as the ones I've seen before, for
 example it doesn't affect the green fluid it's in, and it just rotates,
 it doesn't move around. Still worth having a look at. Another 3D-scene is
 on afterwards, one where you're walking down some stairs, then entering a
 room with a pentagram (surprise!) on the floor. Suddenly light and things
 start coming out of this pentagram, followed by lightballs. The speed and
 resolution is pretty much the same as the previous scene, still I like
 this the best, maybe because I find the ghost in the previous scene a bit
 to comic to be scary...? Shortly after the demo ends with a scrolltext and
 a new piece of music, a bit more "modern" than the other piece, still
 quite atmospheric.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth watching ones, mostly for people with fast CPUs.

@EndNode


@Node "AngerIsAGift" "Anger is a Gift / Kiki Productions"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Anger is a Gift
@{B}Group:@{UB} Kiki Productions

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Belgian Scene Event
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.18 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM

@{B}By:@{UB} Momo

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nice animation
- No routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A production that could not really be called a demo, nor an intro
 as the author calls it (you might have noticed the size, which is a little
 big for an intro...). The number of routines can be counted on one finger,
 most of the show consists of pictures and text, added with some heavy
 rock. Only one thing raises it above the masses of lousy crap productions:
 It has some excellent, but short, animated, cartoonish sequences, where
 you see a hand waving a gun around in a hallway - a really alternative
 Doom-routine!? Still, that really isn't enough to save the whole show.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch it for the animations, then get rid of it!

@EndNode


@Node "Atmosphere" "Atmosphere / Frame 18"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Atmosphere
@{B}Group:@{UB} Frame 18

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} AntIQ
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.45 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more...
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '040 or better (if it runs on such processors)

@{B}Code:@{UB} Darklon, Dundee, EFT/Impulse (c2p)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Flex, Nat, Beast/Impulse, Rack/Majic 12
@{B}Music:@{UB} Pat

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some good routines, high quality graphics
- Some routines need lots of CPU power, a little short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A nonstop five days production the Frame 18 members claim, and
 even though I like this production, I guess it's true. The five days have
 been spend rather well, but has also resulted in few routines (about five)
 and some small (but not significant) bugs. Also, the techno/dance music
 isn't timed, and could have been performed better in my opinion, and the
 pictures/textures, which are great, seems to have been chosen randomly,
 but this is somewhat saved partly because of their high quality, and
 because the colors are all clear, and therefore nothing is conspicuous.
 The routines are roughly speaking divided into to kinds: The ones that
 run near perfect on a '030/50, and the ones that eat up lots of CPU power.
 Luckily the '030-friendly routines outnumber the hungry ones, but these
 are typically the ones that run in low resolution (of course).
 The show starts with a zooming flash, followed by group name, and title.
 An airplane spinning around is the first moving object, a phong that is,
 it's slow, a little buggy, but the resolution is good. A picture exposed
 to a moving lightsource is on next, like bumpmap without the bumps...
 Also this effect is slow on '030, and again the resolution is good. The
 credits part is on next, and this is terrific, so good that I suspect it
 to be an animation!? You see to spotlights, a red and a yellow, lightening
 towards you, one moving from left to right, and the other one the other
 direction, with the names and job in front of them. Looks really great as
 long as it lasts, this part is quite short. A cool plasma is on next,
 fast too, but the resolution is a little low, still acceptable, though.
 It's one of those plasmas that appears from one point of the screen and
 disappears at the same point while it's moving around. Hard to explain,
 cool to watch. The next effect is great too, a pretty traditional "rings
 in water" effect, actually one of the better ones. The speed is good,
 maybe because the effect is copied, so that the same thing happens twice
 at the same time, but under normal circumstances you might not notice
 that. Phong torusses have been seen (too) many times before, but I
 forgive Frame 18 for using one in the next part of the demo, not so much
 because of the object, more because they've succeeded in running a jelly
 torus and a moving background in 1x1 near smoothly on a '030/50. That's
 not a thing you see every day on a medium class MC-chip. A great picture
 by Beast is shown afterwards, then the demo ends with another plasma,
 similar to the one earlier in the demo, and a scrolltext.
 If Frame 18 have chosen to spend a couple of weeks or month on demo making
 they could really make demo that kicked some ass!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Have a look!

@EndNode


@Node "VoyageInStorm" "Voyage in Storm / Impulse"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Voyage in Storm
@{B}Group:@{UB} Impulse

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Supposed to be released at The Party 1995, but was five minutes late
       for the deadline... Was released a couple of days after The Party.
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 4.9 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 2 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '040 or '060 (if it runs on such processors)

@{B}Code:@{UB} EFT
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Rendall, Thomas, SLO
@{B}Music:@{UB} Mr. Pixel

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Nice graphic, entertaining, some nice routines
- Some routines need lots of CPU power

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A beautiful fantasy picture appears. The synth-music fades in.
 In other words: The voyage has begun. A texture mapped logo enters the
 screen from the left to right, shortly after it appears really close to
 the viewer moving from the right to left. Pretty slow, though, not all
 routines in the demo run superfast, this is one of them. On the other
 hand the resolution is good throughout the whole show, making it ideal for
 people with fast processors (however, I don't know if it takes advantage
 of those processors). The title is on next, using not less than three
 pictures, one for each word, all of them interesting. Talking about
 pictures and graphic in general this demo is an example of good graphic
 all the way through. Pictures, textures and backgrounds never get boring!
 Next routine is great: A spinning, rotating and zooming cube with an
 wave animation on its sides, looks like it's mapped with moving bumps.
 And it gets even better (or at least just as good): After the cube exists
 another cube, this one with three different rotating pictures on the
 sides, enters. Runs fast too, unlike the gouraud shaded torus that is
 the next moving object. It's a bit slow, but then there's the logo in the
 background... For a short time afterwards four balls that dither the
 background appear, and then some kind of Doom-routine is on. Actually it
 has not really anything to do with a real Doom-routine, but it looks a bit
 like, mostly because of the textures on the walls. Imagine that you're
 driving down a tunnel that waves from side to side, and has no floor or
 ceiling. That's how it looks, unfortunately that's a little simple and it
 doesn't give you a "speed-rush" which would most likely have saved the
 effect. More gouraud is on next, this time a big blob with about 1000
 faces resulting in a speed that isn't exactly impressive. A beautiful
 picture appears afterwards, then a short traced sequence, which lead us
 to the so called "Mars"-routine, which shows to be voxel landscape that
 after a while starts to wave up and down. It really needs a fast processor
 to run smoothly, and still it doesn't fill the entire screen at all. A
 Chinese scrolltext scrolls to the left of the voxelscape (difficult to
 read :)). Another picture is on, and then the demo ends with an
 informative scroller, with the same waving animation as used on the first
 cube (nice). The music in this part is a remix of a Mike Oldfield score,
 which is heavily inspired by Irish folk music. The music in the demo is,
 as mentioned earlier, synth, but also techno elements, sometimes mixed
 with some blues I guess is heard (strange mixture by the way).
 All in all a fine presentation by the Impulse crew.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Recommended, should be in your collection!

@EndNode


@Node "Karaoke" "Karaoke / Depth"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Karaoke
@{B}Group:@{UB} Depth

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Copenhagen Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} Didn't compete in any of the compos

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.54 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Cytron
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cytron
@{B}Music:@{UB} Cytron

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Funny for Danes and other Danish speaking people
- Not funny for anybody else

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A little short "demo" (or intro as Cytron calls it, a half meg
 intro, Cytron?) that contains no routines, besides a textwriter that
 writes the text that is sung, or rather growled, in the heavy metal
 "music". The text is all in Danish, so only those who understand this
 strange language will find the "demo" funny. It's about how much the
 growling person wants DGC to die (I believe Cytron is referring to
 "Dansk Gruppe af Computerfreaks" ("Danish Group of Computer freaks"),
 the people behind The Copenhagen Party, which was quite a failure.
 Depth, who is said to be the most noisy group, has specialized in getting
 as much attention as possible, really did a good job at TCP...!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A cult demo (?) for Danes only!

@EndNode


@Node "Fairytale" "Fairytale / Floppy"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Fairytale
@{B}Group:@{UB} Floppy

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Gravity and/or Belgian Scene Event
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 3 (at BSE)

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.05 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, PAL. 2 MB chip-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040/40MHz or '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} Zig
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Fame
@{B}Music:@{UB} Revisq
@{B}Something:@{UB} Yasi, Def

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice objects and design, the music fits well
- Needs lots of CPU power, (too) much 3D

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A quite nice demo that is telling, and showing, us about the
 alien visitors from outer space. In it is a lot of 3D, actually too much
 3D for my taste, but it is all nicely done, and there are different kinds
 of 3D. For example texture mapping, phong and bumpmapping (or what looks
 like it).
 The show starts with a nice Floppy logo, which is followed by the first
 routine and the credits. It's an orange 3D landscape with some balls of
 some kind (UFOs I suppose) flying around above it. The frame rate isn't
 impressive on a '030, but I guess when running on '040/40MHz (as Floppy
 recommend) or better it looks good. On the other hand it runs in 1x1
 resolution, which is also the case for rest of the demo. Another thing
 that is present throughout the entire demo is shaking texts telling the
 UFO story (that can also be found in the readme file - scary reading!).
 After the landscape scene there's all this different kind of 3D objects
 flying around here and there. Later another 3D scene is on picturing the
 ocean, but instead of just using plain and sharp pictures Floppy has
 messed it up a little so that it looks a bit like a painting, interesting.
 Also worth mentioning is a cave/hallway scene where we follow to UFOs
 flying down a hallway. The walls and water look nice, the UFOs a bit
 simple, but that isn't necessarily a bad thing. The last effect is a
 colored bumpmap with a single lightsource.
 The music is a fitting piece of ambient/jungle techno, and I must say that
 Floppy is successful in forming a synthesis with this production. Still,
 too much 3D, too few other effects!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Especially recommended for people with fast processors!

@EndNode


@Node "MegademoB" "Megademo $B / Gunnars Farvebio"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Megademo $B
@{B}Group:@{UB} Gunnars Farvebio

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Copenhagen Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 7

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.43 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} (Tested version) 4 MB fast-RAM, HD, (also available) floppy
 (requires 8 MB fast-RAM)
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030 or '040 (if it runs on such thing)

@{B}Code:@{UB} MZ1453
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Johnny Hash, Gandy/IRIS
@{B}Music:@{UB} Boris Bahnhof, Daddy Kool

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nothing really, it's pretty average
- Low resolution

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Another one of GFB's many crazy productions, this one pieced
 together from a bunch of routines of different quality. You have to
 execute a little script too see all of the demo's four parts (more or
 less), and every time it changes from one part to another you'll see the
 Workbench or CLI (depending on how you run it...). But that's not a big
 loss as some of them are quite funny (actually most of the demo is funny,
 especially if you understand Danish), and most of the demo doesn't look
 very professional, both concerning design and optimizing.
 The show starts with a little animation (first part), followed by the real
 demo part, the one containing all the real routines. A lot of pictures
 presenting model's faces are scrolled across the screen, while the demo's
 title is flying around. Then a low-res Doom routine is on, actually more
 like a real 3D-routine, as you fly freely around having a look at the
 nice textures (that, unfortunately, are ruined by the resolution). Like
 most of the rest of the demo this routine is shown in widescreen, the top
 and bottom has been cut off. Instead a logo is placed in the top, and a
 silly scrolltext is shown below the routine. Next routine is a 3D-logo
 with three light sources behind it, causing rays of light to appear from
 the letters, a quite nice routine, and like the previous and the next
 routines it uses a low resolution display. A env-mapped torus is on next,
 then a tasteless 3D-scene is shown (four bending "columns" standing in a
 circle with a spotlight in the middle), followed by another torus, mapped
 with pictures of those model faces... The next thing that happens is that
 we fly through a 3D-tunnel, probably made from the same engine as the Doom
 scene is build upon, and with the same textures, but with a fast '030 it
 looks pretty nice I guess. Also, a couple of lightballs (that don't seem
 to give away any light to their surroundings) is present. Back to the 3D
 routines, same routine new scene. Luckily this one is a bit more
 interesting than the first one, for example a spinning, texturemapped cube
 is present. A plasma routine is on as the next, a transparent one where
 two plasmas is shown above each other. Nice. A rather slow morphing
 routine is on as the next, I've seen many better morphers than this one.
 Also the pictures that it morphs aren't big. Back to the Doom routine,
 now with some fancy "gimmicks" added, a spinning env-mapped torus and a
 texture mapped box hovering above a mirror. But that is far from enough
 to justify that it is on for a very long time, maybe GFB didn't want to
 cut down the length of the scrolltext in order to make it fit a proper
 demo duration, at least they could have made it scroll faster then.
 Third part is a Win'95 (we _hate_ it) look-a-like "shutdown" message, just
 a lot more funny than the original (in Danish...). Also a scrolltext is
 present, and later a quite smooth bumpmapped 3D-object appears. For ones
 the resolution is good. 4th part is a screenshot from EuroChart's 4K
 chart... GFB wonder why their 4092 is placed where it is...
 The music in the demo is a piece of synth music, average, and in the last
 part a techno piece, nothing special.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For GFB fans

@EndNode


@Node "Arte" "Arte / Sanity"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Arte
@{B}Group:@{UB} @{" Sanity " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/ArteLogo2.gif"}

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1993
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 3
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 28

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.91 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} OCS/ECS, 1 MB RAM, needs a patch to install on HD and to use
 AGA

@{B}Code:@{UB} Mr. Pet, Chaos, McDeal
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Ra
@{B}Music:@{UB} Moby

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Everything
- Is not AGA, is a trackmo

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I admit that this is the ECS demo that I prefer. It could be
 because of the fantastic music by Moby, the wonderful pictures by Ra or
 the great code by Mr. Pet and the precise vector engine by Chaos and
 McDeal, but this demo is a masterpiece. If you watch it on an A500 or on
 an A1200 the feeling is the same: A perfect work of art where everything
 seems to dance together to the funky rhythm!
 The graphic style of Ra is incredible: With so few colors he succeeded in
 painting some surreal @{" picture" system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Arte3.gif"}s ironical and fascinating, and the whole
 demo adapt his flow to this style. A series of strange and absurd messages
 introduce a very worthy texturized tunnel that ends in the title picture.
 After that a blue chicken without head (?!) turn around an Arte logo that
 after a while follows the chicken! The effect changes: A scrolltext is
 wrapped around a big moon, a strange text. Then come an incredible
 Einstein picture that fades to introduce some rotating starfields. A
 strange rubber rotator tunnel appears, and when the music changes a
 deformed chunky copper picture enters, zooming and rotating. This is the
 last effect of the first part. Some absurd messages terminate the music
 and introduce the second part. A new funky tune introduces a 3D dots
 landscape with a message that scrolls and wraps over these dot mountains.
 When a Hammond organ starts to play, a wonderful sine plasma starts to
 dance. And a vector bouncing ball, lightsourced, follows the rhythm.
 Now is time for the distorted electric guitar, and a strange texture
 rotator wrapped around a sphere. And then a beautiful picture of some of
 the most beautiful girls ever seen in the Demo Scene appear: Miss
 @{" Monroe-Shiffer-Crawford " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Arte4.gif"}, who introduce a color tunnel, a kaleidoscopic
 flow of colors in chunky copper. After some square columns (the lousy
 effect in the whole demo) is a wonderful picture, fantasy style, that
 after a defragmented tunnel, is being explained concerning the @{" anti-digit " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Arte1.gif"}
 mode. Time to end, and some incredible vector object animations, well
 synchronized to the third piece of music in the demo, and a final
 scrolltext, conclude the show. This routine is very cool if you see on a
 A1200 + fast mem, but also on a A500 + fast mem is not so slow as you
 could expect.
 What a pity that all this goods is only one disk!
 What a pity that Arte is not AGA!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} What is a demo? Arte!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB}
 Mr Pet wrote many messages in German hidden into the code of the demo.
 If I understood one of these: His girlfriend gone away when he was coding
 Arte. What is coding a demo? Sacrifice for Arte!
 In the final scrolltext Ra say that Anti-digits mode shows what R.W.O.
 can't show. One year later R.W.O. replied with a picture shown in the
 same mode in Balance's @{" Syndrome " link "Syndrome"}.
 Moby says that the music in this production is some of his work that he's
 the most proud of.

 @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Arte2.gif"} Ra's style is unique!
 @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Arte3.gif"} Talks for itself
 @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Arte4.gif"} Top model?
 @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Arte1.gif"} The anti-digit mode ends with this picture


                                                        Daredevil

@EndNode


@Node "Riverhorse" "Riverhorse / Ambrosia"

@{B}Name:@{UB} RiverHorse
@{B}Group:@{UB} Ambrosia

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} South Sealand
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 12

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.49 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 4 MB fastmem
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} 68030/50Mhz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Powdihacker
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cain, Access, Powdihacker, Shadow Walker
@{B}Music:@{UB} Unison/Impact

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ The intro idea is funny, maybe a bit vulgar, but great
- It's short, many effects are in 1x2 pixels resolution

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Imagine a country: Blue sky, green grass, some trees, a sweet
 piece of flute music and a cow (?!), and you are flying free as a bird
 in this little calm paradise. But... What happens??? Hey you! Where are
 you going??? No! Not into the cow! Not in THAT hole! AAAAAAAAAAAARGH!!!
 Great! Simply great! This demo has one of the funniest intro I've ever
 seen and it isn't an animation: is totally in 1x1 pixels resolution!!!
 Congratulation to Ambrosia for this piece of humor!
 Let's talk about the rest of the demo. Now you are voyaging in a "brown
 morphing tunnel" (imagine by yourself in what part of the cow you are!)
 as you can see at the "cow-display" (which is actually a hippo-
 display?!?), and at the end of tunnel you find a blue puddle, water drops
 fill it with waves, and a moving light causing a bumpmap effect to the
 puddle. Then a rotozooming platform shows colorful shade bobs textures
 and also show the greetings in sync with music. Afterwards some credits
 in bump mapping mode are shown, interleaved by a multicolor tunnel in
 which a star moves around changing the illumination (Looks quite odd and
 tasteless - DRD). A picture of an Ambrosia logo with a circle moving as a
 twisting lens on the picture is on afterwards. The next effect is two half
 part of a 3d brown, blurred, twisting object on half placed in the left
 edges of the screen, the other in the opposite side. A well-made effect.
 A commercial spot picture of the Ambrosia game Genetic Species with the
 same circle lens seen before (lasts too long - DRD). The last effect is
 a morphing blue bump mapped tunnel, where also the last credits are shown.
 And finally picture ends the demo.
 The graphics are nothing special, except for the intro part, but the music
 is worthy of some words. When I listened the first time it was a simple
 demo tune, very pleasant, but not exceptional. From the second time I feel
 that the refrain begins to turn in my mind, and from the third time I
 found myself to whistle it very often and without needs! It's worthy!

Comment from Dreyer: You may wonder about the title, I guess that has a
 lot to do with the hippo-radar (the one that's on when you enter the cow).
 In Danish a hippo is called a (directly translated) riverhorse, that might
 explain the strange title...
 Worth noticing is that not all the effects are too smooth, some last a
 little too long, and there's no really fancy transitions or the like
 (well, except for the journey into the cow...).

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A good demo with many ideas, worthy but short and with a great
 intro to see.
                                                        Daredevil

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Riverhorse01.jpg"} The 3D scene and the cow
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Riverhorse02.jpg"} Inside the cow/hippo (?)
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Riverhorse03.jpg"} A little twirl routine is loose on this picture
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Riverhorse04.jpg"} Two blury party twisters, nice!
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Riverhorse05.jpg"} Some kind of plasma


@EndNode


@Node "Roots" "Roots v. 1.0 / Sanity"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Roots
@{B}Group:@{UB} Sanity

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 4
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 8 of 22

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.91 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, needs a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Chaos, Mr. Pet, Tron (animation player)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cougar, Cthulhu, Sire/Lego (dots objects), Oliver R. Wilke
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jester

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Many good ideas...
- ... But the deadline ruined all the work

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Roots is a strange demo. It is incomplete and you notice that
 something is lost on the way. But it isn't a complete disaster.
 The effects are very well coordinated to the music (a Jester techno piece,
 very impressive, but a bit monotone) and also well coded. A very
 interesting experiment are the Cthulhu pictures in German Expressionism
 style, scanned by Chaos directly from Cthulhu paints! But also the Cougar
 pictures are of very high quality. There are many good effects from dot
 3D objects manipulation and morphing, to an impressive lens morphing on a
 scrolling texture that changes into a tunnel and into a human face. Also
 worth mentioning is great 3D rotation and zooming of some textures that
 morph. The mountains voyage effect I'm sure to have seen it in another
 demo (maybe Odyssey by Alcatraz), but this is not good. The voxelscape
 that follows is OK, though, maybe a bit slow. And now the bad impressions
 starts. The dots human face that morph into a hand is a bit imperfect
 however, it is optimized in @{" Roots 2 " link "Roots2"}).
 The plasma is good, but the 3D double scrolltext on it is incomplete.
 As final effect there's a raytraced anim with giant pixels. It fills some
 empty diskspace (as said in the final scrolltext)... And with the
 scrolltext appears some realtime morphing faces that originally are the
 author's faces (you'll see in @{" Roots 2 " link "Roots2"}).
 I want to be clear: all these are not bug, but missing things that ruin a
 demo potentially cool demo.
 
@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} What a pity! If you want to see how Roots is good, look at
 @{" Roots 2 " link "Roots2"}. This version is worthy to see only once.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} What goes wrong? Mr. Pet didn't arrive at The Party
 and he had much graphics and code to complete Roots, so Chaos, near the
 deadline, used test gfx and partially effects to complete the demo.
 The animation was taken from a game in development (as I know was never
 released) called Jive.

Click @{" here " link "Roots2"} to go to Roots 2.
                                                        Daredevil

@EndNode


@Node "Roots2" "Roots 2 / Sanity"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Roots 2
@{B}Group:@{UB} Sanity

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.91 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} 1st part of the demo is AGA, need a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Chaos, Mr. Pet
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cougar, Cthulhu
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jester

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ 19 effects, two pieces of music, nine pictures, one AGA-part and one
  part ECS, are that enough?
- Too many effects result in a demo or in a mess?

@{B}Comment:@{UB} @{" Roots " link "Roots"} is a strange demo. It was incomplete, you noticed that
 something was lost on the way! This demo is a remixed and optimized
 version of @{"Roots" link "Roots"}.
 Many effects are the same but a bit corrected. Technically the evolution
 is the same: Very well coded routines coordinated to the music (the same
 Jester's techno piece in the first part, and a rage tune in the second
 part), very impressive, Sanity's style.
 Also to find in the demo is some of Cthulhu's pictures, always in German
 expressionistic style, and the excellent Cougar graphics give Roots 2 the
 right touch.
 The demo is divided in two parts. The first, in AGA, presents the same
 effects as in @{" Roots " link "Roots"}: Dots 3D objects manipulation and
 morphing, lens morphing on a scrolling texture that changes into a tunnel
 and into a human face, 3D rotation and zooming of some textures that morph
 into others, a kaleidoscopic tunnel, a sine rotozooming texture
 (rotozooming is a trademark of Sanity!), an AGA plasma, and (new effect!)
 a 3D world that morphs into a Sanity logo.
 The second part, in ECS, starts with some new effects. A little animated
 logo appears zooming, a sinus texturized tunnel and a little Wolfenstein
 3D labyrinth is on afterwards. Then follow the dots human face that
 morphs into a hand, and the hi-res mountains voyage effect that I'm sure
 to have seen somewhere else is also to find. A rotozoomer (they made in
 AGA, now they demonstrate it in ECS!), a dots spiral galaxy object, a dual
 plasma and a fantastic (considering it is in ECS) voxelscape in half of
 screen (under A500 is a bit slow but flows okay). With the final
 scrolltext the author's faces appear  morphing in realtime.
 OK, what's wrong with all these goods? That this is a demo, not a compo
 about "who-fit-most-effects-on-a-disk"! The effects aren't linked by
 anything and the music isn't timed above the usual. I call this lack of
 design. And for the authors of @{" Arte " link "Arte"} this is very
 strange. Well. Now there are two different points of view to consider. If
 you watch Roots 2 for the first time the effects are impressive and you'll
 ask yourself how these guys managed to put so many things in only one
 disk? If you see Roots 2 after seeing @{" Roots " link "Roots"} you'll ask
 yourself the same thing, but with a clear déjŕ vu.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A big production, is worthy to be seen more than once.

Click @{" here " link "Roots"} to go to Roots.

                                                        Daredevil

@EndNode


@Node "Smart" "Smart / Elven 11"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Smart
@{B}Group:@{UB} Elven 11

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Symposium-Mekka 97
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 5 of 14

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.88 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} 68030/50Mhz, works on faster processors too

@{B}Code:@{UB} Manta, Slat, Dip
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mat/Vajrayana, Rio, Manta, Slat, Vision-X/Degeneration
@{B}Music:@{UB} Parsec
@{B}Design:@{UB} Manta, Mat/Vajrayana, Slat, Parsec

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Innovative ideas and effects
- A big lack of design, needs a fast processor

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo technically is one of the most interesting I've ever
 seen. Many effects are in interlace and truecolor. The graphics is nice,
 but the soundtrack (a techno style tune) is only functional to introduce
 the effects. But you feel that something is missing, and that's the links
 from one effect to the next. So, the demo is a show of effects without
 soul, and the music alone cannot fill this hole, at least not that tune
 in my opinion.
 The demo starts with some interlaced text, and the credits flow on a
 motion blurred starfield that ends in a big interlace bumpmapped logo.
 Other effects in the demo are: A cool Egyptian styled triangular
 bumpmapped tunnel, a 2x1 24-bit truecolor motionblurring cross fade
 between two interlaced pictures, an incredible 2x2 24-bit truecolor
 blurred plasma rotator which at the same time cross fades into a picture,
 some old style copper effects on a picture, an impressive 1x1 18-bit
 truecolor bumpmap in interlace, a worthy env-mapped torus in a broken
 glass, an innovative wide-angle distortion on some textures, a bump mapped
 circular tunnel, and finally a scrolltext. On the truecolor effects appear
 parts of a message that continues on the next. A try to link the demo a
 bit better? Maybe, but however, it's not enough!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} An incredible demo from a technical point of view, but too
 "cold" to be very impressive. However, if you like new effects and
 interlace, you must give a try.
                                                        Daredevil

@EndNode


@Node "World of Commodore" "World of Commodore / Sanity"

@{B}Name:@{UB} World of Commodore
@{B}Group:@{UB} Sanity

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1992
@{B}Event:@{UB} World of Commodore
@{B}Placing:@{UB} Didn't compete

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.91 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Need a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Chaos, Mr.Pet
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cruiser, Cougar, Olof
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jester, Bit Arts

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Nice design, good coding, good music
- The effects too common nowadays, but that isn't necessarily bad, is it?

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo has historical value. It contains in my opinion the base
 for complex effects, now so common. There's a full screen "Amiga rules" in
 realtime zooming and rotating with a persistence effect all in chunky
 copper, really well introduced thanks to the very good Jesterday's tune.
 Very impressive is the so called "Escher distorter": A platform in
 sine-zooming with morphed graphics inspired by Escher pictures, and the
 Jesterday tunnel: A tunnel of concentric circles in deformation.
 Very cool are the credits: A simple, but very good 3D texture map made
 with copper.
 In the second part the effects are more common. 3D dots sine field, a
 picture in rotozooming, some shadebobs, a dot tunnel. The best effect is
 the three twisting bars on which a ball bounces and deforms itself like a
 soap bubble. The music by Bit Arts in this part is good.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Such an old trackmo that runs without complication on any Amiga
 is something special. Recommended!
                                                        Daredevil

@EndNode


@Node "Trailway" "Trailway (Assault 2)/ Capsule"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Trailway (Assault 2)
@{B}Group:@{UB} Capsule

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Euskal 5
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 5

@{B}Size:@{UB} 4.4 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020 (minimum), 68030/50 (standard)

@{B}Code:@{UB} Kustom
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} .Judas & Zaac
@{B}Music:@{UB} Pink

+ Adequate routines
- Unfinished

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **-- (recalculated from Generation ratings)

@{B}Comment:@{UB} When thinking of recent Capsule demos being uploaded on the
 Aminet, one gets the fatal impression that downloading the releases from
 the Spanish based group around Eystrak might be a waste of time. In fact,
 before the release of Trailway, they concentrated on "low budget"
 productions which carried no guarantee for quality standards. Things
 change, time changes - so why shouldn't Capsule releases change?
 Released at the Euskal Party 1997 in Spain, it certainly has a difficult
 way to the wider attention of the Amiga Scene, as Spain isn't known as
 the most influential Scene country, to put it politely. Maybe with this
 review, Trailway might make its way into more demo collections.
 The demo starts traditionally. A Capsule logo by Zaac scrolls in from the
 bottom to the top, followed by the names of the people involved. These
 shrink on a gray background as negative zoom into the screen and get
 exchanged by a futuristic fullscreen picture by .Judas. Disturbing in this
 intro sequence is only that the soundtrack - a spacefunk module by Pink -
 doesn't fit what is shown as it just crashes into the scene for the
 beginning without any kind of spherical appeal; like the upsetting would
 have demanded. Maybe we here see the first traces of the unfinished state
 of the demo... The first effect is some kind of "computer" texture
 running over a centered ball, so that the texture gets deformed and
 stretched in the middle. The resolution here is low, but the effect itself
 cores the eye. Additionally, after a flash, three gouraud shaded
 vector circles start to run over the described background. A highly
 fashionable effect which only misses shading of the objects on the
 background.
 Usually when demo designers let a lightsource scroll behind static logos
 for a movietrailer impression, Kustom - who according to our sources
 (Generation's) shortly after the release joined Abyss - lets his letters
 scroll up to bottom. The background is light gray, while the letters are
 held in black. The words throw out their negative shades (dark to light)
 towards the viewer. In the shades themselves, dark particles as individual
 sources stress the effect even more. Two sets of words saying "are you
 prepared" get shown this way. An interesting linking effect follows, but
 runs too slow to gain more than an uncertain impression at the viewer.
 Much like the next effect. For a very short amount of time - and I mean
 very short - a star object comes into sight. It seems to be environmental
 mapped and gets mirrored in a "fuzzy" way, but more information cannot be
 given as the whole thing remains on screen for less than five seconds. A
 timing mistake?
 The following face-out-of-a-box effect which we all know from @{" The Gate " link "TheGate"}
 by Artwork stays longer on screen. For quite a long time to be exact. It
 runs in a standard resolution and uses environment mapping. For some
 seconds it also seems like it uses bump mapping like in @{" Megademo IV " link "MegademoIV"},
 but this is just a vague impression. The effect runs on a gray background
 including a static Trailway-logo. Vector worlds have become an often seen
 part of 1997 demos after the success of Bomb's The Party 6 winning demo
 by Ben @{" Shaft 7 " link "Shaft7"}, who used the first Lightwave scene converter
 on Amiga ever. The vector world shown in Trailway afterwards looks a
 little like a clone in design and as it is only shown for a short time
 before disappearing, one can say with a good consciousness that it also is
 generated using Lightwave. Why not? Another futuristic fullscreen by
 .Judas is followed by a second vector world including a Capsule logo in
 much the same design as the first one. Also this one is shown only for a
 short period of time.
 The end lowers the overall impression of the demo. A fullscreen picture by
 Zaac of an aggressively looking nude girl in front of a Union Jack is
 shown for a short time and then it all goes away. The music - which
 restarted just short before - cuts in the middle of the pattern and the
 Workbench screen grins at the surprised viewer. Unfinished they said? Now
 we know what they mean: The demo has no end.
 Who expects brilliant programming from a demo might be disappointed after
 watching Trailway. The code seems to be of standard quality, and even the
 most "easy-to-impress-watcher" gets in troubles when being asked to find
 innovation. Trailway, however, is a good demo for the way the show is
 composed. The way the effects are displayed is nice, the composition of
 the main palette is suiting and consequently used, although it is not very
 original. The music doesn't entirely fit the layout, but is refreshing to
 listen to after all the industrial stuff in 1996 and 1997. There should
 have been worked more on the intro and outro.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} All in all Trailway is a production that features all common
 requests for a demo in 1997.

 Click @{" here " link "Assault"} to go to Assualt

                                                           RockDaZone

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Trailway01.jpg"} A very nice title picture
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Trailway02.jpg"} Phong in the front, bumped texture behind it
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Trailway03.jpg"} A cool color zoomer routine
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Trailway04.jpg"} A simple object is mirrored
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Trailway05.jpg"} The traditional face in plate routine
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Trailway06.jpg"} The graphics are quite okay

@EndNode


@Node "Dose" "Dose / Mellow Chips of TRSi"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Dose
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mellow Chips of TRSi

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Demolition
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 9 (mixed Amiga and PeeCee compo)

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.0 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020 or better, PAL, AGA, 4 or 8 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040/40
@{B}Note:@{UB} The music's mixing rate (it's an eight channel mod) can be adjusted
 by entering a number after the start command.

@{B}Code:@{UB} Aivo
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Ola, Lich
@{B}Music:@{UB} Kalsu/Artificial People, Jogi
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Aivo, Ola, Tequila

+ Magnificent overall impression
- Needs quite some power

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **** (recalculated from Generation ratings)

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Once upon a time there was a bunch of sorcerers, combined under
 the cryptic name of Mellow Chips. With their witty illusionist tricks they
 became favorable and applauded in all of the Scene countries. Still, not
 only fame but also critics came their way for rather concentrating on the
 appearance than on hardcore coding - the coders guard was embarrassed.
 This must have been blasphemy! The commoners, however, honored and
 applauded the Finnish magicians and voted them high in every chart. Then
 came the breakdown. Almost one year of silence from the Mellow Chippers
 made the people insecure first; then secure that another comet had hit the
 earth and glowed out. Then in a pixelstorm they came back and brought the
 right "Dose" with them!
 The intro picture makes it quite clear: Mellow Chips has become a subgroup
 of TRSI; like the simple black/white group logo expresses. This seems to
 be the only real change from their state of independancy, however, as the
 next part including the credits, expresses: All the known faces are back.
 The credits part itself convinces by its splendid composition. A storm of
 animated clouds wobble through the screen and from its inner dust, the
 names zoom in, one after another. The resolution here like in the rest of
 the demo is quite low, which for a change doesn't disturb too much: The
 show itself excuses this disturbing factor. Another factor being same for
 all effects are the aftershading of the objects. This effect looks
 brilliant on fast processors, as the edgy movement gets overlaid, but
 confuses the eye on slower machines ('020/'030) as the aftershades stay
 too long on screen.
 The music is a sensitive piece of (Goa-)Trance which fits the effects and
 is well timed as well. It's a multichannel module which also cuts
 processor time so that on smaller configurations, the mixing rate has to
 be set down from the standard rate of the optional 20000. This can easily
 be done by simply adding the desired rate behind the filename in the
 Shell. 10000 is quite enough so we can recommend that on '030/25 and
 below. Next we find a rendered Mellow Chips logo in Gray-Green, which
 looks much like the rest of the drawn graphics in this demo, below
 standard. It is always strange to see that people with a good sense of
 composing palettes for effects and to create valuable textures are in need
 of weak fullscreen pictures. The first "real" effect is a 3D-object
 rotating over a dark blue background. Here the low resolution and the
 aftershading only partly enable the watcher to fully understand what he
 sees. Still it looks well displayed. The next effect is more of a crasher
 as a polished golden female body (sister of C3PO) rotates and zooms over
 another bluish background, environmental mapped and illuminated by four
 separate lightsources. Although we have seen similar effects before, this
 one simply has its own touch and strongly reminds of well placed PeeCee
 Demos. On a bigscreen and with a 68060 in the back, certain PC-braggers
 would leave their mouthes opened wide. The next vector world looks much
 like the highly fashionable scenes we are used to latest since The Party
 6. In the middle of the room we find a transparent object which deforms
 the background in its shape. Only strange that even MC finds nothing more
 interesting than the Quake-corridors design for their worlds. Looks good,
 but nothing particularly special here. Now back to the fullscreens. As
 said before: They ain't so gorgeous, to stay polite. The next picture
 appearing now is highly inspired by Pam Anderson, but only parts of the
 picture and its surrounding are drawn well somehow. Especially the facial
 expression of "Pam" makes it obvious that she suffers from multiple
 sclerosis. Another world appears: We bet that it's a Lightwave-scene, but
 nothing against this as the strange objects are displayed nicely and the
 overall impression is well. Next follow a female torso walking in
 3D-robot motion over the screen, which itself consists of a huge
 zoom-rotating eye in the background. Quite impressive sight although also
 here the 030/25 isn't able to enable full beauty. Another rotating
 env-mapped world enters afterwards and give the background for a
 transparent MC logo. Another chance for certain demo groups for some
 design studies.
 What would be a demo without the head behind it? Factually nothing. The
 MC's enable us to get to know their mastermind in the next part and
 - ouch! - what a strange guy. A bumpmapped head with a strong-red texture
 comes in and is effected by three or four lightsources. The texture in the
 background makes it obvious: Yes, this is a colorful effect. What seems
 to be an amorphe texture mass turns out to be a huge bumpmapped morphing
 ball effect, zooming in and closing off the viewer. Interesting views
 here surely, but the effect itself is not so impressive despite for its
 speed.
 That's it. They could have left out and the endpart - just a scroller up
 with another naked Pam-monster in the background - even tackles and
 crackles for unknown reasons, before the viewer virtually gets kicked out
 off the demo. Why can't Amiga coders perform a smooth end like they do on
 other systems?
 MC stay faithful to their pathes and deliver a highly fashionable
 video-like demo which leaves not many wishes for design and appearance.
 It's a stunning trip into a world of demo; like Tasslehoff Burrfoot would
 put it, "The Journey was fantastic!"
 This demo doesn't come up entirely with the biggest and most important
 releases of 1997 technically, but pushes away much what we have seen so
 far this year. Why did they only get second placed at the Demolition I
 wonder, not having seen the first rank yet. One surely can make better
 demos, but - damn! - it would be a hard task. TRSI can only be gratulated
 to have found a compact subgroup of these abilities.

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Highly recommended!
                                                        RockDaZone

@{B}Inside information:@{UB}
 - The demo is pretty much a remix of @{" Divine " link "Divine"}, Aivo was in the army at the
 time the demo was made, so he had too little time to produce new effects.
 The demo was made in three days (using old routines)
 - The music was made in one day
 - The demo ought to have won the compo (it is said...)

Source: SeenPoint 7

@EndNode


@Node "GhostInTheMachine" "Ghost in the Machine / Venus Art"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Ghost in the Machine
@{B}Group:@{UB} Venus Art

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Gravity Party 2 (the review is based on the bugfixed version)
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.88 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, '020 or better, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} CyberGFX, 68060, 2 MB Graphics board

@{B}Code:@{UB} NOE & BJSebo
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Lazur
@{B}Music:@{UB} Wierza/Venture

+ Support for graphicsboard
- Needs lots of CPU power

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **-- (recalculated from Generation)

@{B}Comment:@{UB} "And if they lay us down to rest, tells our moms we done the
 best." If we can fullfill their grammatically important last wish in the
 demo without lying to the old ladies, this review shall sort out.
 Important here that I am biased towards the demo as it supports CyberGFX
 and may therefore be awarded as one step nearer to a Amiga Scene, using
 real graphics. Thanks to the Gravity organizers, who seemingly understood
 the sign of the times and allowed 68060/50 and CyberGFX support in the
 demo competition. Interesting here that the demo is written using SasC &
 DevPac. So at least partly done in C++. Maybe there could be patches for
 PowerPC later on?
 After setting the appropriate screenmode, when being in the lucky position
 of CyberGFX, you wait relaxed for the things to come... Just to get the
 shock of your life for a very shrill beginning with slightly overdone
 pompous brasses blasting away your senses. A cinematesque starting with a
 marmorised female torso (env-mapped) and red letters forming the group's
 name over a static blue sky. The sounds fade, so does the screen and a
 darkblue background gets visible as well as the demo's title. A gourauded
 "triple spoon" object starts to rotate. What first appears as
 unidentifiable object mass in the first moment turns towards the viewer
 next and one comes to understand: It's a female comic-character's face in
 grayscales. The engine features environment shading, movements and one
 static lightsource. A surely nice object, but already on AGA/320X240,
 68030/25 by far too slow to be really enjoyable. This demo uses given
 resources to the extreme, so much is true. Next follow a very impressive
 Quake-engine in which a soldier is hunted by a large doberman dog through
 the corridors until shooting the animal in a final showdown. Especially
 the textures are very nice here. The 3D-engine features bumpmapping and
 transparent surfaces and is most probably a Lightwave 3.5 scene.
 After the screen faded blood red a very nicely designed screen filling
 bumpmap object gets visible with a large hole in the middle under which a
 green water surface gets visible. Another object flies through this hole
 and returns for no particular reason. The subsequently following
 fullscreen by Lazur is - as hard this may be to believe - rather poor!
 The polish graphician surely is a brilliant talent, but why does he still
 release his older and surely weaker pictures? And why does he paint faces
 all the time, when he has an obvious weakness just there? Even here the
 author is wrong from the technical aspect, but the picture simply doesn't
 look good. Especially not under AGA 320X240 as it gets totally scrambled
 by the viewing routine. At least on the test-configuration (A4030/25, 8 MB
 fast-RAM, 2 MB Spectrum 24/28 Gfxboard). Under CyberGFX 640X512 everything
 appears to be normal. Then a roller coaster pops on the screen. Quite
 complex, but slowly and quality seems doubtful as it surely is a Lightwave
 scene and as such not a well designed one.
 In contrast to the now following flying saurus. A texture of eye dazzling
 beauty shapes the Pteranodous on his majestical flight over a blue summer
 sky. A beauty really. Then the credits in huge blue and white object
 letters scrolling scrolls screen. Nothing specific to report here. The
 next fullscreen by Lazur reveals the same weaknesses as the in the one
 discussed earlier and is replaced by a final Virtual 3D logo formed of
 single bumpmapped objects, before the cryptic request from the start
 appears.
 The demo exits cleanly to system only leaving a window with "Alles in
 Ordnung!" (Everything's in Order!) in it. Does this mean they used the
 system specific catalog as indicator for a final 'Good Bye' in the
 appropriate language or did they simply use the German sentence for
 strange purposes (I've seen the demo crash after giving this message...
 - DRD)? Anyway, it is over.
 The demo seems to consist mainly of Lightwave scenes, thus they ought
 to have found a well converting solution. The design ranges from weak to
 very nice and gives a sober average impression in the end. The spherical
 score supports the release well. The best fact of this demo surely is
 when first displaying it under AGA 320X240 and then again, switching to
 CyberGFX 640X512 or higher. Of course the demo runs very slow on our
 test configuration, but it simply looks gorgeous in such a high resolution.
 This especially goes for the comic girl, the Quake scene and the flying
 saurus.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Recommended for people with fast CPUs and graphic boards!

                                                        RockDaZone

 Click @{" here " link "GhostInTheMachinePPC"} to go to the PPC-version.

@EndNode


@Node "Odorless" "Odorless / EMS Design"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Odorless
@{B}Group:@{UB} EMS Design

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.2 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} 68020/14MHz, ExSys.library (included)
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/25MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Hellrazor & Stan
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Stan
@{B}Music:@{UB} Trump

+ Some nice routines
- Pretty average

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **-- (recalculated from Generation)

@{B}Comment:@{UB} After installing the ExSys-library which is part of the archive,
 one is able to start the demo by running the executable file. Apart from
 this library, Odorless comes without any external datafiles.
 The Norwegian EMS Design presents a quite short demo when it comes to
 duration. With 1.2 MB on harddisk, however, it isn't the shortest of its
 kind. After watching the demo, doubts appear in the watcher, where they
 actually have put all the data in? There are two fullscreen pictures of
 rather low resolution and a drums'n'bass module called "Soothe me to
 Sleep" by Trump which takes 201140 bytes of the memory. Although they
 surely used new textures on each effect, it remains a riddle for what
 they needed so much space.
 The demo starts with an EMS Design logo followed by the demo's title held
 in brown, blurring and fading out one after another on a black screen.
 The blurring is smooth and ensures the audience that a fashionable demo is
 to be started now. The first main-effect is a low-resolution (320X240)
 tunnel in the same color palette as before. In its center the credits
 appear and fade out, well timed to the score. Then a hi-resolution bumpmap
 over an interesting texture fills the screen, followed by yet another
 low-res tunnel. This time with a pulsating lightsource in the middle and a
 textured vectorcube rotating and zooming in the middle. All six faces of
 the cube features the same texture of a fractal. The next effect is
 another, this time more extreme lightened blue, bumpmap, which somehow
 gives a transparent impression. Next, an interesting picture by Stan fills
 the screen, which appears to be a collage of scanned and reworked
 material, shows a man being pulled into his computer by a hand coming out
 of the monitor (often happens to me - DRD :) ). A short greetings list
 tosses off afterwards in letters blurring out much the same like in the
 start. Then the final and most impressive effect already starts. A
 deformed tunnel with a bumpmap running from the outside to the center -
 therefore against the main movement of the tunnel itself - with a donut
 in the middle. Again running in low-res, but surely a nice one here.
 Basically that's it for the whole demo. The music calms and a final screen
 with some lighteffects under a simple and white EMS Design logo is shown.
 The demo exits to system on mouseclick.
 With Odorless, EMS Design present a compact demo with a fitting appearance
 due a dense plot and overall nice display. The production is to be
 classified far off the top of 1997 demos, but proves a solid basement for
 coming future releases, which will follow next with a slideshow by their
 member Maze. The score gives a lot of mood to the release and saves the
 solid picture. Somehow we miss a real highlight in it, which leaves a
 trace in our memory and which causes us to run it more often than maybe
 twice or thrice. Some graphical surprise would have helped a lot, but
 maybe it could also have interfered the already mentioned compact
 impression.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth having a look at.
                                                        RockDaZone
@Endnode


@Node "Paradisio" "Paradisio / Drifters"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Paradiso
@{B}Group:@{UB} Drifters

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Symposium
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.5 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Zinko, Vention
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Clary, Třf
@{B}Music:@{UB} Zinko

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Funny, nice graphics
- Doesn't last for long

@{B}Comment:@{UB} If you've seen some of Drifters' earlier works you will probably
 have no problem pointing out that they made this little production, even
 if they didn't write their name in the demo. Actually it's more an
 animated slideshow than a demo, there are no effects in it. Instead it's
 filled with cartoon style animations - three or four different ones
 shown again and again until the end of the show. The animations are
 short, but funny (I love the one with (among others) Calvin and Hobbes
 dancing on the beach), the music is a mod-ification of a pop hit from the
 "real world", somehow it fits the show. Unfortunately the demo is too
 long, you get bored when the same animations are looped over and over.
 The title fits the demo well with the paradise atmosphere present from
 start to end, lots of tropical palms and the blue ocean in the background.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch once!

@EndNode


@Node "ASCIIJunkie" "ASCII Junkie / Juice"

@{B}Name:@{UB} ASCII Junkie
@{B}Group:@{UB} Juice

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Scene Strike 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.95 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Kozmo
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Loco, Pain, Jamon, Marry-Anna
@{B}Music:@{UB} AlmanActive, Marry-Anna (vocal)

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Good idea, well-timed music
- Quite monotone, gets boring in the long run

@{B}Comment:@{UB} As the title suggests this demo consists of ASCII chars,
 everything is made from these chars, except for the start and the end of
 the show that are real graphics. The show starts with some shaking
 letters, then the show starts. And for people that have followed the Scene
 productions for the last five years would think of (at least) two demos
 that are similar to this one: @{" In a World of ASCII " link "InAWorldofAscii"} by Impact DK
 and @{" State of the Art " link "StateOfTheArt"} by Spaceballs, the first one of course
 because of the use of ASCII chars, the second because of the (mostly)
 dancing people present. Yes, Juice managed to make a music video of
 ASCII chars, a long one too. In fact too long. After a while it gets
 boring to watch the constantly changing, but very similar, dance scenes.
 On the other hand, the technical side of the demo is excellent with
 smooth movement, and blurred edges on the dancers, looks nice.
 The music is all right if you like techno combined with triphop drums
 (drum'n'bass), but maybe more important it's well timed to the visuals.
 The show ends with the credits, pictures with the names and a screenshot
 of the program used for their task. Nice.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} This product is of a high quality, but it's too monotone to
 keep you in front of the screen for long.

@EndNode


@Node "Severed" "Severed (fixed version)/ Mellow Chips"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Severed (fixed version)
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mellow Chips

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Abduction
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 10

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Braindead
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Lick, Ola, Tequila
@{B}Music:@{UB} DJ Weckro

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nice routines
- Strange design, bad music, monotone

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I guess this one of Mellow Chips first demos. Compared to their
 later productions it's quite lousy, but still you see the first signs of
 talent, especially concerning the code and the graphics (Lich's pictures
 that is). But the demo itself isn't exactly state of the art. It contains
 some quite good (but a bit buggy) texturemapped phong objects running at
 an acceptable frame rate, but in a low, but acceptable, resolution. The
 objects shown in first part of the demo are medieval items, for example a
 helmet, a sword and a shield. The background in this parts are a bit ugly,
 partly because of the resolution, but also because the images used in
 general are not too successful. This phong part gets quite monotone as the
 objects are on for quite a while each, and even though the objects are
 different the code is more or less the same all the times. That changes,
 luckily, when the demo changes to the next effect, a combined plasma and
 credits part. The plasma is the kind that looks like rings in water
 (mostly) with primitive letters in front of them using acid colors.
 Next effect is a nice one. A couple of spotlights, blue and red, lights up
 a wall, and suddenly a face morphs out of the wall, so that it is a
 bumpmap. The next part is more or less a little slideshow as the only
 thing that happens is that three pictures by Lich are shown in a row.
 Looks a bit painted and are pretty nice. A texturemapped map (!) is on
 next waving around in the wind (this part is also long), followed by a
 texturemapped head that has been cut of the body, a bit disgusting!
 After that the demo ends.
 The music is not very good most of the time, and doesn't fit the demo's
 mostly medieval theme. It stretches from techno to synth and heavy rock,
 non of the genres are very successful. The music could somehow have
 compensated for the monotone visual, but it doesn't, and the many genres
 are "unnecessary", one would have been preferred.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not recommended

@EndNode


@Node "Depthcharge" "Depthcharge / Corrosion"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Depthcharge
@{B}Group:@{UB} Corrosion

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Scene Strike 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.21 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, runs on '020 and better
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030, 2 MB fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Suffocator, Griffin
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Asarhad
@{B}Music:@{UB} Dominator

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Simple, but nice routines, fitting music
- Few routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is in many ways a nice little thing, a quality product
 with rather traditional, simple, but nice routines. Seems as if Corrosion
 has used the good, oldschool routines mostly, but the way they are
 performed raises the demo's overall impression a lot.
 The show starts with logo, while the ambient techno brings you in the
 right mood. The first routine is a tunnel made out of a square dragging a
 long tail after it, one that zooms towards you giving the impression of a
 tunnel. The title is shown afterwards (seems as if it was made rather
 fast), and the tunnel routine is shown again, colorcycling. The next
 routine is very nice, and at the same time rather simple. It's a pixel
 routine with pixels (!) that fly around in different patterns with a short
 tale after them. Looks great! This is followed by some kind of shadebob
 routine, a quite okay one too, which again is followed by a nice picture
 of an eye, the style reminds me a lot of Cyclone's drawings. A (rather
 slow) texture plasma is on next, first shown as four small screens, then
 as close to fullscreen plasma running in a nice resolution. There are two
 versions of this, a slow one, and one not quite as slow, I can't see the
 difference between those two. Anyway, it's nice. The combined greetings
 and credits part is the next thing on, an original designed as small TV-
screens with the author's faces shown. Finally a slow, rotating cube with a
 smiley on its sides is on. Doesn't fit the rest of the demo, but maybe
 there is a deeper meaning about it?

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Recommended

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Depthcharge01.jpg"} A pretty nice Corrosion logo
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Depthcharge02.jpg"} It may be hard to see it, but this an awesome looking bunch of particles
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Depthcharge03.jpg"} Good, old shadebobs
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Depthcharge04.jpg"} Texture mapped plasma, nice, but slow
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Depthcharge05.jpg"} The special credits part

@EndNode


@Node "SuperPimpero" "SuperPimpero / Spedes"

@{B}Name:@{UB} SuperPimpero
@{B}Group:@{UB} Spedes

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Scenario
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ A few nice routines
- Strange mixture of good and bad

@{B}Comment:@{UB} On one side some parts of this demo are some entertaining stuff,
 while other parts are as taken from lamer-demo, or at least a low-fi
 production. The demo looks almost promising when started: To the left is
 a transparent rotating head (an animation), and to the left is a text
 analysis. Much a'la for example Blade Runner, the Scene where Bryant
 introduces Deckard to the replicants. The font used somewhat ruins the
 illusion, though. The group name and title are shown afterwards and removed
 using a simple stretch routine. Later there's a very nice plasma, the
 display is quite strange though, every second line show something
 displaced, and after that a simple 16 colors partly transparent vector
 object is on. Finally a little joke, a Bond intro, is shown, while a loud
 chiptune plays an improvised version of the well known Bond-theme.
 The music in the rest of the demo is mostly a hardcore piece of techno,
 not the best choice, but that's quite typical for low-fi demos.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Strange mix of good and bad, judge it yourself! Not really
 recommended

@EndNode


@Node "ArtByCoincidence" "Art by Coincidence / Spaceballs"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Art by Coincidence
@{B}Group:@{UB} Spaceballs

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Convention
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.11 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 4 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040 (if it runs on such thing)

@{B}Code:@{UB} Slummy
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Boo, Zack
@{B}Music:@{UB} Duckhunter

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Nice and original effects, good transitions and design
- Long breaks

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Nice to see that Spaceballs after a while in silence are heading
 back to the top. This production proves that they both have the ideas and
 the talent to conquer the Scene once again, and Slummy even claims that it
 just took a week for it to be finished!? The demo contains some rather
 original effects, and some nice transitions, good design and well timed
 ambient music with triphop drums. But unfortunately there are a couple of
 way too long breaks here and there in the demo, maybe because of decrunch
 time or whatever, it's quite annoying.
 It starts with a text telling you where it was released, followed by the
 first effect, a Spaceballs logo is somehow zoomed away from the screen.
 The upper part of the logo is zoomed first, then the lower parts are
 zoomed. The frame rate is low, though. This logo is on for a long time,
 but finally the demo starts for real: Two zooming, transparent, texture
 mapped balls appear, moving around. In one corner the letters ABC are
 shown one by one and exposed to a strange effect (that I won't try to
 explain here). It's the only routine in the demo that haven't got a
 colorful background, it's pretty fast, but the resolution is a little low,
 still quite acceptable. Next on is a gouraud shaded diamond object that is
 exposed to a smoke/fractal effect, looks really cool. The smoke whirls
 around making beautiful patterns around the object - very nice, however
 I'd recommend at least a fast '030 for this particular routine.
 Spotlight balls that blinds the viewer has been seen before, but I guess
 that no one has ever made the spot gouraud shaded? Spaceballs now have.
 The effect is that these spots twist and turn, and when the light beam
 points directly towards the viewer (s)he is blinded by it. This routine
 is on for too long, a bit slow, but nice anyway. Also the picture that is
 on next is shown for too long, but if you have the patience to wait for
 the rest of the demo you are awarded with a nice picture displace routine.
 Again a 3D diamond object is present in the middle of the screen, and
 around is a picture, not behind it. When the diamond spins around it
 simply pushes the picture! Nice. Afterwards a strange voxel-like,
 pulsating, big blob appears (this one is on for to little time), and the
 background shows up to be some kind of color tunnel/zoomer, a nice one
 two. The diamond object appears in the upper left corner, while all these
 colors fly by. When the object disappears the many colors are formed into
 a tunnel that is exposed to a "drunken-view"-effect, or said in other
 words it's like when you try to get your eyes out of focus, so that you
 see the object you're looking at twice. In this case you see the tunnel
 four times, and you don't have to de-focus yourself, Slummy has already
 done that for you! Great. This very nice effect is the last one. The demo
 ends with a picture and some credits.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Original, colorful and nice! Watch it!

@EndNode


@Node "Hate2" "Hate 2 / Fanatic"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Hate 2
@{B}Group:@{UB} Fanatic

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 7 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.29 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} SHD, Duster
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Doc, Brainlock (trace)
@{B}Music:@{UB} Speck

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Colorful, fast routines
- Low resolution

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I ask my self, after having watched this demo, why it's called
 Hate 2. I see no indications of hate in this pretty nice demo, what I see
 are some stylish traced pictures, fast, but low resolution "standard"
 routines, and a mixture of different colors here and there.
 It begins with some stylish raytraced pictures that introduce the demo,
 which are followed by a low-res, pulsating texture mapped plasma. After
 that we are flying between two flat and endless red planes, unfortunately
 Fanatic has chosen not to make a horizon, the two planes simply end up
 in one big mess. That combined with the low resolution ruins this effect a
 little, but still it's nice. Even nicer is that a flat object and a light
 ball suddenly appear making it all a bit more interesting. Next routine is
 some strange kind of tunnel, one that zooms a lot of colors towards the
 viewer, making it look like a tunnel. After a short 2D pulsating "thing",
 something with some waves to make a long routine short, another tunnel
 appears, this time a real 3D tunnel with plasma tendencies. Fast and nice,
 but it uses, like most of the other routines in the demo, low resolution.
 Two boring torusses are up next, gouraud shaded (but in 1x1 resolution),
 and then we have another tunnel once again. This time it's a hexagon-
 shaped one with a picture of a model's face (original...) as wall texture.
 Finally the end is near. The demo ends with some texture mapped 3D letters
 flying through a cow...
 The music changes from being techno, synth or/and traditional demo music.
 Not a module that will be remembered after the demo has ended, but it fits
 the demo all right.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth having a look at

@EndNode


@Node "WasteOfSpace" "Waste of Space / Tulou"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Waste of Space
@{B}Group:@{UB} Tulou

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Hackernight IX
@{B}Placing:@{UB} Probably didn't compete

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Dr. Strangelove
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Razorback
@{B}Music:@{UB} Fossil

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ A pretty fast rotator routine
- Some slow routines, monotone

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Usually a demo's title doesn't tell much about the demo, but this
 is an exception, because all in all this demo is a waste of space. It does
 have some nice routines in it though, but only few, and the last part is
 way too long. There are about five routines in the demo, these are some
 kind of plasma that looks like rings in water, a quite fast zoomer/rotator
 with the letters TULOU flying towards you (this one is actually nice!),
 another kind of rotator, a strecher with tunnel tendencies, a very slow
 and not very nice phong torus with a tail behind it, and finally a blurred
 morph routine that lasts way too long. What it does is to form some black/
 white pictures or letters, then morph them into something new, always
 primitive drawings.
 The music is an ambient piece of techno with quite some atmosphere in it,
 but still I don't think that it is the perfect choice for the demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Waste of space...

@EndNode


@Node "Remix" "Remix / Limited Edition"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Remix
@{B}Group:@{UB} Limited Edition

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.83 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, and probably more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} PG, Hence
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Skize, Skutt, MRK, Dvize
@{B}Music:@{UB} Steffo
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Skize
@{B}Japanese translation:@{UB} Nicke

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Nice and fast routines
- Small design problems, cartoonish sound now and then

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Limited Edition has always been able to make some interesting
 demos, this one is no exception, actually I guess this is one of their
 best. As in many others of their demos the style is fast, but the colors
 aren't the usual clear ones. The demo is full of nice backgrounds,
 routines and ideas, making it interesting to watch.
 The demo starts with some industrial techno that are synchronized with the
 letters that pops up spelling the group's name. Soon after the letters
 disappear and some simple phong objects enter the screen, wrapped into
 some kind of design, looks quite cool. Also, one of the objects explodes,
 and is assembled afterwards, but it all happens so fast that you don't
 really see it. After the title picture a scrolling texture appears in a
 funny way (something about the screen being flipped), which shows to be a
 fast 3D tunnel with a phong object and a lot of bright lightballs flying
 around in it. Also the next effect is impressive, it's a voxelscape where
 you are flying freely above, spin around and enjoy the ride, there really
 is something to enjoy during this effect. Next up is the greetings-part,
 a 3D-scene where you're flying through some octagon-shaped rings with
 flashing lights in their corners. Next to them are signs with the
 different group names on them. Nice and fast. Until now the design has
 been successful, but suddenly there's a picture of a cow!?... I like cows,
 but that's just not the right time or place to insert such a picture
 there! Anyway, it's a nice picture. The credits are on afterwards in front
 of a "rings in water"-routine with some nice background colors, and
 finally we have reach what really makes this demo stand out from so many
 others: The battle scene. Two texture mapped 3D robots are fighting,
 hitting and kicking each other until one of them dies! Future war? The
 movements aren't very realistic, but still it's a cute little scene.
 The last effect is a nice texture mapped phong object. It's a little slow,
 but the resolution is good, so it's just a matter of possessing the right
 processor. Light suddenly starts to shine from the object, small beams
 start to appear from the inner of the blob - nice, but it's on for too
 long, gets monotone quite fast. Afterwards the demo ends with a little
 message.
 The music is, as mentioned earlier, techno - with some sounds that are
 a bit too cartoonish (one particular one!). Also, it's quite simple, but
 on the other hand effective, it generally fits the show well.
 I wish LED had used a little more time polishing this demo, there are
 small things here and there that could have been better, but then again
 there's no important things to critizise - maybe except for the cow...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Should be in your LED directory for sure!

@EndNode


@Node "ElectroboyInside" "Electroboy Inside / Smoke"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Electroboy Inside
@{B}Group:@{UB} Smoke

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.21 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, runs on '020-'060
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040

@{B}By:@{UB} Thor, Devotion, Spite
@{B}Music:@{UB} Fndr

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Original routines, nice graphics, good atmosphere
- Some slow routines, a bit short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} After Smoke's successful intro at last year's The Party it's nice
 to see that they are still able to deliver a quality product, even though
 it can be discussed if it actually deserved the 3rd place.
 The design is different from most other Amiga demos, let's call it fancy
 fashion, and often there are more than one effect shown at the same time.
 The show starts with a spinning, texture mapped star, a "Telia"-effect is
 shown in the upper right corner (letters are blurred away in a special
 way), and two kinds of equalizers are present too. The title is shown
 afterwards with a nice colorful logo, while a quite unexplainable effect
 acts like background, a nice one. Next routine is a slow plasma-like
 "pulsating rings" effect, which is followed by a motion blurred phong
 blob that seems to spread some kind of smoke now and then. Also this
 routine is a little slow, and the colorfades aren't to smooth on the
 object, but still it's pretty. Up next is a pulsating texture mapped
 plate, and in the background black/white pictures slowly and smoothly
 fades directly from one two another. Nice touch that they run more effects
 simultaneous. A well-drawn picture with the group name on it is shown
 afterwards, followed by a near unexplainable routine, or rather three,
 again running at the same time. This part of the demo consists of a
 wireframe tube with grey moving silhouettes where it covers the screen,
 while some white, floating streams silently appears here and there in
 front of everything else. Something really happens here, almost too
 much some would maybe say? We have reach the last effect, the credits,
 a phong blob and a rotating tube of toothpaste (?). The show ends with
 another nice picture.
 The music is ambient, fits the show quite well. Technically it's well
 done, but it only works combined with the demo in my opinion, alone it
 won't really work. But that doesn't matter anyway, as I guess most demo
 freaks both watch and listen to the demo!...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Different, nice and recommended

@EndNode


@Node "MellowYellow" "Mellow Yellow / Factor"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Mellow Yellow
@{B}Group:@{UB} Factor

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 5 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, some fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Booger
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Booger, Jeanluc, Iceman
@{B}Music:@{UB} Opio
@{B}Design:@{UB} Booger

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nothing really
- Simple routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} There's no doubt that there was some cheating with the voting at
 The Party 7, but who did it not completely cleared up. Let's just say that
 Factor have a motive...
 This piece of banana crap should have been the loser, that would reflect
 the quality much better. The demo is nothing but simple routines, for
 example jumping scrolltexts and flying bananas. The most advanced routine
 is a mosaic effect, not too nice.
 The music is rock, not bad, but nothing special either.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Stay away, the authors have smoked too many bananas!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} Supposed to be an intro, but because of a problem with
 the size it's a demo... This could explain some of the lack of quality,
 but...

@EndNode


@Node "Idoru" "Idoru / Depth"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Idoru
@{B}Group:@{UB} Depth

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 7 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.4 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Optima
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Ib
@{B}Music:@{UB} Curt Cool

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Lots of routines
- Low resolution, lacks design, some simple routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo could might as well be several small demos put together
 to one long show, actually it is. The different parts don't fit each
 other too well concerning the choice of colors, but on the other hand
 there's plenty of different routines, some interesting pictures and a
 little funky piece of music. First one is a plasma routine using low
 resolution, which unfortunately goes through the rest of the demo as well.
 It is followed by a 3D vector scene, no texture mapping, light sources or
 anything, it's just plain vector - not exactly the most interesting thing
 to watch, especially not compared to demos like Haujobb/Scoopex's
 @{" My Kingdom " link "MyKingdom"} with some awesome 3D scenes in it, or last year's Party
 winner @{" Shaft 7 " link "Shaft7"} by Bomb. Optima must have taken all his routines and put
 them all into one file - this demo (just a theory)? After an interesting
 picture the next effect is on: About four glass balls (in very low
 resolution) flies around in front of a background texture, and through
 each other too. The background is naturally disturbed when seen through
 the balls, but I guess the resolution should have been better to make this
 routine work. Like most other routines in the demo it's on for only a
 couple of seconds. It prevents you from getting bored watching the show,
 because most of the effects really are old school, for example the two-
 colored rotating bumpmap, different kinds of plasma (including a twirler),
 zooming letters in the greetings part, and a quite simple kind of plasma
 that like the bumpmap is exposed to a rotator making it a little more
 interesting. The end is most likely inspired by the end in @{" Nexus 7 " link "Nexus7"} by
 Andromeda, you probably remember the effect where it looks like laser
 beams are pointing in your direction, Andromeda's effect is better though. 

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Lots of effects, both good and bad, worth having a look at

@EndNode


@Node "LopsKakki" "Lops Kakki / Da Jormas"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Lops Kakki
@{B}Group:@{UB} Da Jormas

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 9 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.33 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Innovative
- Way too long

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A rather innovative demo that are very different from all other of
 The Party 7-demos, and for most, if not any, demo released. Basically it's
 a video recording (from a rave I believe) mixed with a lot of different
 effects, acid colors, strange display and a repeating piece of techno.
 One would think that that s/he has eaten a lot of ecstasy or similar
 drugs when watching it. The real problem is that it's way too long.
 At least five minutes with more or less the same effects can make the most
 hardcore demo viewer sleep I guess, but as pure music video it'll probably
 work all right shown at a rave party - but not at The Party or any other
 places.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For ravers only

@EndNode


@Node "MyKingdom" "My Kingdom / Haujobb & Scoopex"

@{B}Name:@{UB} @{" My Kingdom " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/MyKingdomTitle.GIF"}
@{B}Group:@{UB} Haujobb & Scoopex

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 17!

@{B}Size:@{UB} 7.31 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, Runs on '020-'060
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030

@{B}Code:@{UB} Boogeyman, Fastjack, Speedo, Kenny
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Visualize, Kid Love, Leumann, Bay Tremore, Jazz, Dice
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jazz, Muffler
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Nomad, Boogeyman
@{B}Design:@{UB} Owl

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ****

+ Very fast routines, lots of variation, nice graphic and sound
- Better transitions would be nice

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A fully deserved winner of The Party 7, it got more than twice as
 many votes as the nearest competitor @{" Killer " link "Killer"} by CNCD.
 This is a real quality production from start to end, nice and fast
 routines, well-drawn pictures (I don't like the intro-logos too much
 though), and some rather fitting music that at one point in the demo even
 changes to the better, unlike so many others of those ambient/techno/
 triphop modules out there. The design can be discussed concerning the
 colors, it changes from some dark/gloomy ones, in the groovy 3D-scenes, to
 very happy ones in some tunnel and plasma routines, but I like the way
 that it is made; Lot's of colors for the non-3D effects, the other way
 around concerning the 3D-scenes.
 After you have executed the little script the demo starts, and you are
 quickly made aware of that this is a cooperation between Haujobb and
 Scoopex - their logos, fast 3D phong objects, fly towards you, and is
 shortly after followed by two fullscreen logos that I dislike, they don't
 seem to keep up with the standard in rest of the show, and also I think
 they are too cartoonish. But all that is forgotten when the next effect
 starts: A fast 3D scene, looks a bit like a torus seen from the inside,
 but with hands sticking out of the center-pole holding televisions that
 shows the same as your monitor. It's running in 1x1 resolution, but even
 though it's fast, and you '030-owners probably wonder if it really is a
 '030 under the "helmet", or if it's an '040! Also the credits are shown
 here (as you can see above there's a lot!). The title is shown afterwards
 (nice picture), then the fast routines continue with a bouncing, jelly,
 bumpmapped, texture mapped phong ball. Unfortunately the resolution is
 not quite as good as in the 3D-scene, but the frame rate is (as the other
 effects in the demo) good. A really colorful 3D-tunnel is on as the next,
 lightsourced I guess, a bright light in the end of the tunnel (that are
 not very far away from the viewer) seems to illuminate the part of the
 flower shaped tunnel that is near the middle. After all these positive
 words and phrases about almost everything in this demo I'm sorry to say
 that the wallwrap look-a-like shown afterwards is a bit ugly. The texture
 used reminds me of a combination of old 1970s wallpaper and symmetric
 fractals. The pink color is frightening! But I believe that's the only
 mistake made, and that's not many for a demo with so many routines in it.
 Well, maybe not the only mistake: A second file is now loaded from the
 script, and that's maybe why there seems to be a small error. The sound is
 more or less cut, and the screen goes black for a little while. Maybe it's
 just my computer that makes the mistake? The show goes on with a nice
 picture, followed by a great pulsating blob made of what looks like voxel.
 A blue spotlight hidden behind the object, pointing towards you takes care
 of the background. In a hurry we enter the next 3D-"show off", this time
 not quite as advanced as the credits part, but still as fast. What happens
 is that a rather tasteless (?) object - The two group's logos combined
 with a rocket - flies through a row of rings, all of it is texture mapped
 I guess. I can't help thinking about those Zero Gravity intros from
 Scoopex when watching this, the phong routine is (more or less) the same
 as in those ones. A color confusion plasma/tunnel routine is on next
 (great if you fancy strong colors), then a new 3D-scene is ready to be
 watched. What makes it interesting is the little "fountain" in the middle
 of it that instead of spraying water up into the air uses small
 lightballs. The scene is in other ways quite traditional, but is somewhat
 saved by these balls (and of course the great speed and resolution).
 After a really great plasma, the final effect is on - also a 3D-scene:
 Small hills surround a black hole, and four rings fly around down into
 the hole, find a nice little phong blob which follows them up to the
 sky. The demo ends with one of Visualize's interesting artworks, I wonder
 what those Chinese kanjis mean.
 As you should know by now I'm rather enthusiastic about this demo,
 especially because of those fast routines everywhere, even when the Party
 crew decided to use an '060 Amiga instead of the "traditional" '030/50 MHz
 machine. That only proves that you're able to make good productions on
 limited systems. Those 3D-scenes really are fast! You might get the
 impression that there are too much 3D, but that's not the case. The
 routines are balanced so that they are never on too long, merely the
 opposite is the case keeping you hungry, give you the need to watch it
 just once more. The cooperation is really successful, but how can it
 avoid to be with so much talent put into just one production?
 Both Haujobb and Scoopex are talented groups, but together they reach a
 higher state (and placing :))!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} One of the absolut best demos in 1997!

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/MyKingdomTitle.GIF"} The Title
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/MyKingdom1.GIF"} Interesting 3D-logo combination
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/MyKingdom2.GIF"} Maybe the fastest 3D engine ever!?
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/MyKingdom3.GIF"} And there was light...
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/MyKingdomPic1.GIF"} One of the excellent pictures
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/MyKingdomPic2.GIF"} And another (called Kingdom). This got the 2nd place at The Party 7

@EndNode


@Node "Turbotronic" "Turbotronic / Instinct"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Turbotronic
@{B}Group:@{UB} Instinct

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 17 of 17...

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, maybe more. Runs on '020-'060
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} Nuclear Ninja, Dr. Who/Gunnars Farvebio
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Squid, Angeldust, Nuclear Ninja, TNT, Receiver
@{B}Music:@{UB} Turbocop
@{B}Moral support:@{UB}: Receiver

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Some nice 3D scenes
- Rather slow 3D, monotone

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Strange title for this production, it is quite far from the truth
 (which is out there). The demo is nor turbo, neither tronic (whatever that
 means, but it sounds fancy), and 90% of it is 3D-scenes that need quite
 some CPU-power to raise the frame rate to an acceptable level. Well, there
 are both HAM6 3D-scenes and ordinary 8-bit, but an '060 is what you need
 watch the heaviest of these scenes running smoothly (if possible). Also,
 sometimes the perspective correction isn't working (or is non-existing),
 which result in oblique rendering.
 The show starts with (yes, you guessed it) a 3D-scene, followed by a 3D-
 scene, followed by a 3D-scene, interrupted by a mismatching picture that
 is followed by a 3D-scene, where a woman is walking on something that
 looks like a bridge, followed by a 3D-scene - you're flying from a room
 to the sky, where you see some 3D-letters (this routine even uses a
 smaller display area to gain speed, not too successful). And then it's
 time for the endscroller, and a beautiful and fast bumpmap routine, one of
 the best I've seen actually, running in the background.
 I could explain how the scenes look, but I find it unnecessary to do so,
 however, most of them are nice.
 The music reminds me of Jean-Michel Jarre (the greatest!), the floating
 tunes is as taken from one of his silent pieces, but unfortunately
 Turbocop has chosen to add some drums, which works fine in the beginning,
 but as the demo progresses they get wilder and wilder, the visual side
 don't, though. Technically it's not too impressive either, but it does its
 job.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Reminds me of those 3D-PeeCee demos, 3D gets boring!

@EndNode


@Node "Repugnance" "Repugnance / Powerline"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Repugnance
@{B}Group:@{UB} Powerline

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Icing Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 5!

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.97 MB
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030

@{B}Code:@{UB} Chip, Raylight, Scout/C-lous (C2P)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Orhan, Mattias Hellstedt
@{B}Music:@{UB} Wasp
@{B}Additional work:@{UB} Gunrider, Mad Druid

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Fast, colorful, well-timed music
- Could need a little more work here and there

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This must be called Powerline's breakthrough - from just being a
 little unknown group they've, with this demo, proven worthy to enter the
 charts around the globe. And that is not without reason: The entire crew
 has done a good job with this demo, from code to music, even though some
 more originality and professionalism are wanted concerning the 3D objects,
 but that isn't a too big problem, as there is only little 3D in the demo.
 Everything in the second part of the demo - that is after the intro part -
 runs very fast, both concerning frame rate and the amount of time it's on.
 One nice effect after another is smashed into your face with 120 km/h.
 But let's start at the beginning: The credits, group name and title are
 shown using an "out of focus on the X-axis"-effect, some kind of blur. The
 music is timed perfectly, some atmospheric synth sounds are heard every
 time a new word gets shown, or a choir is singing (well performed by the
 way, but with a sample rate that is a bit low). And then the second part,
 the main part, starts. The music changes to heavy rock that later changes
 to techno. The effects shown are some kind of 3D-tunnel, different kinds
 of plasma (including a cool bumpmapped one), a color zoomer that looks
 like a burning piece of material flying against the wind seen from behind,
 a texture tunnel zoomer (or what looks like it) that suddenly splits up
 into three tunnels, a texture mapped 3D object with a pulsating background
 - this one is really great! After this stunning fast show the tempo is
 lowered to a more moderate speed. A picture is shown (beautiful!), the
 music gets more ambient and a flatscape routine with both floor and
 ceiling is on. After a while (maybe a bit too long) the "camera" find a
 hole in one of the planes, and what is more natural than to enter a hole?!
 Soon after you a flying through a 3D tunnel (a bit fake, but it looks
 good!)! That's how to make a great transition! Also the music is timed,
 so that when you enter the tunnel it changes to a more fitting speed.
 Afterwards a quite ugly picture with 3D letters and a lensflare on it is
 shown, and now we have entered the demo's 3rd part, which start with a
 little wide-screen plasma and some text. After that Powerline feels like
 showing us more text, actually quoting some wise (?) words, while showing
 a variation of their bumpmapped plasma. Next effect is a blur routine that
 blurs and un-blurs everything present on the screen, also the 3D object
 that flies around (the same as before). Next up is a water effect, where
 you see a texture (some bricks) below the water's surface, while small
 waves wave... The last effect is both indescribable and also a little
 slow, but on the other hand the resolution is better than in the rest of
 the demo I guess. I think it's a colored bumpmap with multiple
 lightsources, but I'm not too sure, look for yourself! The whole show ends
 with an endscroller.
 All in all a demo that really is worth spending time watching. It could
 need a little polishing here and there, maybe the resolution is a little
 low now and then (to achieve speed, it's designed for '030/50MHz), but
 that really isn't the point I think. The point is to entertain people, and
 it sure does!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Should be in your collection!

@EndNode


@Node "Session" "Session / Oops!"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Session
@{B}Group:@{UB} Oops!

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Bizarre
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Mentat
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Shag
@{B}Music:@{UB} Prodigy

+ Pretty nice routines
- Few routines

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A little short production made at the party place, Bizarre, if you
 are to believe the readme-file. Three contributions was needed for the
 demo compo, so the Oops! guys decided to put this demo together,
 impressive that they won. Then again the competition can't have been very
 hard... Only four effects find their way to the screen, but they are all
 pretty nice. After a short presentation of the crew behind the show, the
 first of those effects appears: A nice water drip effect with a spotlight
 shining on it. The resolution is 2x2, but the frame rate is quite good
 which goes for the rest of the routines as well. Next one is kind of a
 colorful tunnel (slightly buggy), followed by another water effect, this
 one with bigger waves, and with the lightsource placed somewhere away from
 the screen. Finally there is a pixel effect where the pixels are locked in
 a pattern that slowly moves around with a fading tail behind them. After
 this the demo ends and also causes a minor crash (maybe I was just
 unlucky?). The music is somehow laid-back ambient with triphop drums, fits
 the show okay, but is nothing special.
 All in all I wouldn't really recommend this demo, simply because it's so
 short. Its contents are fine, but the duration stops you from wanna watch
 it again (much like reading a dictionary, except that is to looong!?)...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Can be watched once

@EndNode


@Node "Prey" "Prey, The / Polka Brothers"

@{B}Name:@{UB} The Prey
@{B}Group:@{UB} Polka Brothers

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 4
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 6 of 22

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.66 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Airwalk, Merge
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Colin, Pixie, Devilstar, Vandrup
@{B}Music:@{UB} Slide, Merge

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Fast routines, well-timed music
- Low resolution now and then, some simple routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The Polka Brothers are infamous for their fast demos, and this
 demo is no exception. Most of the effects are thrown right into your face
 at great speed, while the atmospheric, hard beating Prodigy style techno
 music gets your loudspeakers on the edge of being blown away (that is if
 you play at a high volume...). Speaking about the music, it's strange, but
 by some reason it starts half a minute into this rather long demo, not at
 the beginning. But then again the title is on as one of the last things...
 Better late than never. Instead of starting like most other demos, with
 the indifferent title, The Prey starts with some wise words (disguised in
 satanic design). The first effect is a simple, but fast voxel landscape
 that zooms towards you at great speed, but in rather low resolution. It's
 followed by a nice picture, and first at this point the music starts.
 Some kind of plasma appears afterwards, also a bit of text is made out of
 it. The next routine is also a kind of plasma, one of those "rings in
 water"-ones, but the rings doesn't move (must be frosen :)), instead a
 texture is placed beneath it, and is of course affected by the rings that
 moves according to the bass drum. This effect, plus a simple oscilloscope
 line with a circuit board in the background, is shown for a while changing
 now and then. A colorful flatscape is the next effect on, followed by a
 simple, colorcycling tunnel that is made from vector graphics - it isn't
 3D though, it's made from a lot of plates with holes in the middle that
 zoom towards you. A low-res color zoomer (including tasteless colors) is
 on as the next effect, followed by a rather fine plasma. It's fast, still
 the resolution is good (or maybe you just don't notice that it isn't
 because of the frequent flashes and changes). Another kind of tunnel is
 shown next, unfortunately the display is quite messy, every second line
 is displaced compared to the ones above and below, thus making it
 difficult to get a good look at the tunnel- maybe that's the point?
 A double plasma is on afterwards, double because two different colored
 plasmas are floating side by side, and also through each other. A fine
 idea, however, the choice of colors could have been better. After a simple
 wireframe box that moves with a tremendous speed, is a very nice picture
 by Devilstar, followed by a tunnel-animation, low-res, but in other
 aspects okay. And then we have the title, followed by the end.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A fast demo that must be watched at least once

@EndNode



@Node "Kinematic" "Kinematic / Alien Projects & The Interceptors"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Kinematic
@{B}Group:@{UB} Alien Projects & The Interceptors

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Astrosyn
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 6.77 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Caustic
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Def
@{B}Music:@{UB} Revisq

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Fast 3D-scenes
- Nothing but 3D-scenes

@{B}Comment:@{UB} 3D-scenes. There are both fast and slow 3D-engines to create such,
 and fortunately we have one here that belongs to the first mentioned
 category. It's very fast actually, the resolution is quite good too, and
 the scenes used are some interesting ones. The negative part about this is
 that the only thing there is in this demo are 3D-scenes. Mostly gray-scale
 ones too, but also some that are a bit more colorful, not much, though.
 Caustic has made some exciting camera movements/angles, and also the
 little detail that transparent faces are put in front of the scenes is a
 plus. But it doesn't change the fact that it's only 3D-scenes, nothing but
 3D-scenes. One with a smoke effect in it, some with transparent faces in
 front of them, and some with moving objects - still too much 3D! However,
 the demo is rather short, so you haven't got the time to get bored, but
 variation can't be found here. It has some kind of "wow"-effect when you
 watch it the first time (I personally thought if it really was only my old
 '030 in my machine), but it doesn't last forever this feeling.
 The music is ambient and atmospheric with a bit of noise in it, fits the
 demo well.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Have a look

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Kinematic01.jpg"} A 3D scene with transparent figures in the foreground
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Kinematic02.jpg"} Big pumping cylinders, and very fast 3D too

@EndNode


@Node "DreamscapeDisorder" "Dreamscape Disorder / Logic Probe"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Dreamscape Disorder
@{B}Group:@{UB} Logic Probe

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 13 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.71 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Takes advantage of CyberGraphics- and compatible GFX-boards,
 able to use native VGA.
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040

@{B}Code:@{UB} Bolt
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Virulent, Diztinct
@{B}Music:@{UB} Pulse

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some nice effects
- Lack transitions, the music could be better

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I don't think that the low placing at The Party was completely
 fair, but it's not a production that makes you wake up saying: "Hey!
 That's brilliant". Because it isn't. Yet, it isn't a bad production
 either. More or less all the effects have been seen before, so has the
 design, the lack of transitions and the triphop-style techno-music that
 sounds as if it needs a couple of extra kilobytes to sound acceptable.
 The show starts with a colorful phong object and jumping texts here and
 there, which is followed by another (exciting) object, at least there is
 some originality to find: Some of the objects. Next effect is also phong,
 but not just phong, in the background is a wallwrap-routine running (looks
 different from others of its kind, as you can see that it somehow is
 magnified through a lot of squares). In the bottom and the top of the
 screen is some technological frames to create some kind of atmosphere.
 After a picture a plasmated wallwrap and some ditto letters appear (hard
 to read what it says), I guess this is the most original effect in the
 demo, but it is something. The contrast to this rather original effect
 must be the torusses that fly around in formation, together with small
 blobs that flies through the torusse's holes. The only people that aren't
 tired of torusses are obviously the ones that design the demos?! A Logic
 Probe-logo designed as the (almighty?) Coca Cola logo is on next, as a
 colored bumpmap effect, funny that red isn't one of the colors...
 An environment mapped (that is transparent) blob in front of a little
 picture is on next, then a fullscreen picture (by the way a quite good
 one) followed by a cow, it's phong with an invisible lightsource flying
 around it. The cow itself doesn't move (cows rarely do...).
 The show ends with a Logic Probe logo, traced.
 The effects are all in a good resolution, most of the routines require
 a fast '030 or better to be smooth, though.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a demo that'll go into the Scene history books

@EndNode


@Node "Power" "Power / SkyTech"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Power
@{B}Group:@{UB} SkyTech

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 12 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Sniper, Shadow
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} X-cell
@{B}Music:@{UB} Orange

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Erh...
- Unfinished? Slow routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Strange one. Seems to have no end, or rather it just ends half a
 minute after running out of effects?! Might be an error in my copy.
 Anyway, the effects that did run weren't too impressive, nor fast: A big,
 slow, gouraud-shaded triangular torus, followed by another strange, buggy
 object. A traditional grayscale bumpmap with the credits shown on it. And
 finally an effect that blurs away the letters that are written, slowly,
 very slowly. Actually this is an extremely monotone part. And then it
 happens - the techno music (not very impressive by the way) continues, but
 no effects, nor graphics are shown, and a bit later it exists. Just like
 that. I wonder what's going on.
 This review will be updated if I get my hands on a better version.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Avoid!

@EndNode


@Node "IfThereWasNoGravity" "If there was no Gravity / Da Jormas"

@{B}Name:@{UB} If there was no Gravity
@{B}Group:@{UB} Da Jormas

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Scenario Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.6 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, may not run on '040 and better

@{B}Code:@{UB} Pekka Pou, RaatoMestari, Vesuri
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Piirakka Munalla
@{B}Music:@{UB} Piirakka Munalla
@{B}Design:@{UB} Da Jormas

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Some simple, but nice effects
- Short, few effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A short little demo with pretty nice design, fast routines,
 and atmospheric and ambient industrial music. Unfortunately there are only
 three routines in the demo: Wireframe glenz letters, that is, transparent
 letters, where you are able to see the wires that they are build around.
 A weird plasma that uses a strange kind of blitterscreen display (or
 similar), it's a circular one and the colors are subdued, but kind of
 tasteless anyway in my humble opinion. The last routine, one that is on
 when the end texts are on, is a simple. but nice equalizer-style effect
 that moves according to the music.
 Unfortunately no more routines are included, a shame, this demo could have
 been something.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch another

@EndNode


@Node "HighAnxiety" "High Anxiety / Abyss"

@{B}Name:@{UB} High Anxiety
@{B}Group:@{UB} Abyss

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 11 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.39 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Moon, Dexter
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Toxic
@{B}Music:@{UB} Pink

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Mostly fast routines, a very nice intro
- Low resolution, unoriginal objects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A demo that contains mostly "seen before"-effects, heard before
 techno/demo-music and technically nice, but old-style space-pictures.
 All effects are show one after another, except for the start there are
 only few smart transitions, and the resolution ranges from low to very
 low, but on the other hand the frame rate is good during most routines.
 The demo starts by using its best effect by far, and that is even an
 animation, where you are spinning around something that looks like random
 placed walls, while the credits are shown with a water-effect in front of
 the animation (looks great except for the low resolution). The most
 brilliant about this is that when there are no more credits you suddenly
 fly above the walls, and you discover that they are actually letters that,
 of course, spells Abyss. In a flash everything but the letters (which are
 now white) disappears, then we enter the more ordinary part of the demo.
 First a pretty nice tunnel is on. It doesn't look like most other tunnels
 as it seems to be made using six small pieces of graphics that are drawn
 repeatedly, so that it looks like a tunnel. Gouraud shaded boxes have been
 seen before, Abyss shows us one again, this one with the advantage that it
 morphs; From being an ordinary box it changes to a box with depressions
 and/or spikes coming in/out to/of it (lots of or/or's...). Afterwards the
 title picture is shown (it's the face of an astronaut), the same picture
 is used in the plasma/rotator routine that appears as the next effect.
 Also motion blur is added after a little while, but the (too) low
 resolution does that it is difficult to see what is actually going on.
 After a gouraud shaded torus (how original... :() another picture is on,
 followed by an odd little tunnel/zoomer routine that draws a road, and
 later adds a grid roof. Doesn't look exceptionally nice, but at least it's
 more original than the torus... More gouraud is on, some pretty boring
 objects are used, one of them seems to be made of jelly - those stretching
 moves are easy to recognize. Two slow objects that looks as if they are
 texture mapped with a black/white grid texture appears next (one of them
 a torus), and then the demo ends with a scrolltext with a dark,
 flower-shaped plasma in the background.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch the intro, forget the rest. The low resolution prevents
 the nicest of the effects from being nice...

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/HighAnx_1.GIF"} Screenshot from the fine intro
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/HighAnx_2.GIF"} A strange looking effect
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/HighAnx_3.GIF"} An astronuat
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/HighAnx_4.GIF"} The morphing box
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/HighAnx_5.GIF"} The end with the plasma

@EndNode


@Node "Breathtaker" "Breathtaker / Virtual Dreams of Fairlight"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Breathtaker
@{B}Group:@{UB} Virtual Dreams of Fairlight

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 12

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.83 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 6 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Accelerator-board, fast HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Alien
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Jaco
@{B}Music:@{UB} Alien

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Great 3D-scenes and other effects
- Lack transitions

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A really nice demo that really is able to take your breath away!
 Unlike most other demos (except wild demos) there is only a minimal amount
 of code in this one. All of the effects are "just" animations (I strongly
 suppose) which causes even the most advanced of them to run at a quite
 good framerate. The resolution is acceptable too, but the animations are
 made so that they just use one color scale (red, green or blue), some
 would maybe say that this looks boring, but it doesn't. In my opinion it
 just adds some atmosphere (same old story: What is best - color photos or
 black/white ones...). Additionally this saves a lot of HD space :).
 The animations last for about 8-10 seconds each, and a little presentation
 text that informs you about the next effect is shown in between. Some nice
 transitions would have been very nice, but of course this would also
 require that it all was one long animation. Most of the effects are
 3D-scenes where you're flying above the ocean around an island, watch the
 birth of a 3D object and similar, but also tunnels, gouraud shaded masks
 and transparent effects are present. All of a high quality.
 The music is techno, a fast tune that somehow fits the demo, even though
 I guess a more quiet tune would have been more sensible to use.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch this one, it's stunning!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} With this demo Virtual Dreams introduced the
 "graphics only" demo, demos based on graphic and animation rather than
 code.

@EndNode


@Node "Mortality" "Mortality / Tulou"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Mortality
@{B}Group:@{UB} Tulou

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 8 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.22 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} 4 MB fast-RAM, AGA, works on '020-'060
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040 or better

@{B}Code:@{UB} Dr. Strangelove
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} Barksten, Temal

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Atmospheric, different, nice design
- Slow routines, a bit monotone, often quite dark

 @{B}Comment:@{UB} This production is different from most other demos. It's very
 atmospheric and is constantly circling around the themes mortality, life
 and death. So how do you show that kind of thing in a demo - well, watch
 this one and you'll find out! Or else just read on and I'll try to create
 a little of the atmosphere that is present in the demo.
 The show starts with a ticking, analog watch. A little poem appears and
 the watch blurs away in the background, while a choir is heard.
 Next thing is that you're driving on a straight road for a while, and
 suddenly you hit a man (probably a member of Tulou...). The title is shown
 afterwards using a "spotlight behind letters" routine, an effect where you
 see the letters in front of a spotlight that causes beams of light to
 appear around the letters. Unfortunately the routine is slow, and that
 goes for many of the other routines as well. But then again, it's made for
 The Party 7 where all productions were shown on a '060. Another thing that
 goes for many of the routines is that they are using only the grayscale,
 no other colors. This helps creating a quite gloomy atmosphere, and also
 the music does its best to keep the atmosphere this way - choir, church
 bells and big, floating synth-sounds are mixed together more or less
 successful. Technically not the best, but it surely has some qualities at
 other points and it fits the demo well.
 A picture is shown afterwards, this one, like the others shown later in
 the demo, dark and scary.
 One of those machines that you find on a hospital that tells you if you're
 alive or not is shown next, and I would have preferred if this part wasn't
 in the demo at all. The sound is irritating, the graphic a bit simple and
 actually it's very little interesting watching it, but then again it's a
 way to illustrate the life/death-theme so everyone understands what this
 is about. Another spotlight effect is on as the next routine, this one
 without anything in front of it. In fact it looks mostly as if it is a
 normal picture slowly moved around the screen, but there are small changes
 in it that reveals that it actually is a piece of code. Another picture
 is shown, then exposed to a zoom routine where you're zooming closer and
 closer towards the laughing, gloomy man at the picture - could be Death. 
 A quite slow and not too nice routine with a flat face that transforms to
 a 3D-face is the next living picture, reminds me of those "faces growing
 out of a box"-routine, except for the missing box. After a picture and
 yet another spotlight routine - including a pentagram - we reach a tunnel
 with hills on its sides. Except for the rather slow speed this one is
 nice, and the resolution is good. A quite original credits-part is on
 afterwards, gravestones with the some names and info written on them. At
 this point the music changes a bit, a deep lead tune is added, creating
 a perfect atmosphere for the final part, the end/greetings-part. At first
 it's a dark, red voxel landscape, but suddenly it fades to become a nice
 bright ocean landscape with small islands here and there, and with a
 beautiful cloudy background. The greetings appear in the horizon.
 I couldn't have thought of a better way to end this demo, it seems very
 thought through, and the demo's theme really has a central placing all the
 way through demo. A speciality that only few master. Unfortunately Tulou
 haven't quite been able to make the demo varied enough, still it's worth
 having a look at.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Tale of life, a thing you shouldn't miss!

@EndNode


@Node "ECintro32" "Eurochart 32 Intro / Depth"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Eurochart 32 Intro
@{B}Group:@{UB} Depth

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 16 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} ?
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, some Fast-RAM (A version for standard A1200 is also
 available)
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Cytron, Blueberry/Efreet, Scout/C-lous
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} hund., Ib
@{B}Music:@{UB} Cytron

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Some nice routines
- Terrible design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} As you probably know the Depth's are the ones that have chosen to
 carry on creating the infamous Eurochart, originally made by Crusaders,
 then taken over by Static Bytes, and Depth decided to give it a try too.
 But they also have to "sell" the mag to the hungry, confused Sceners, and
 I guess that they've heard that any publicity is good publicity. The fact
 is that this intro is a demo, and also it's quite ugly - completely lack
 design and good taste - I guess that's the wellknown Depth style :).
 And not to forget it: It's a commercial demo where the name Eurochart is
 shown a lot.
 But it does contain some nice routines, including some transparent ones
 that are really nice, they don't even loose speed when transparently
 fading from one effect to another. The routines are texturemapped tunnels,
 env-mapped phong objects (also a jelly one), a texture-zoom rotator and
 finally an effect that looks as if you take a bumpy piece of glass and
 look through it. The music is a little melody that fits the show allright,
 technically it lacks some work... The textures are all old pictures that
 seems to be more or less randomly chosen for this commercial demo It
 really is a mistake to do so, they don't fit in anywhere! Does the demo?
 Anyway, the mag is quite okay!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Any publicity is good publicity???

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} After hours of desperate work Depth finally got
 Eurochart 32 put together at The Party 7, but unfortunately they only
 handed out a few copies, as the party was nearly over...

@EndNode


@Node "Psychedelic" "Psychedelic / Virtual Dreams of Fairlight"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Psychedelic
@{B}Group:@{UB} Virtual Dreams of Fairlight

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 4
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 22

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.38 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Dr. Skull
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Ra, Alien
@{B}Music:@{UB} Probe, Julius/Polka Brothers, Excellate

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ****

+ Lots of nice and fast routines, graphics and sound, nice transitions
- Strange music cut off, needs the final touch

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is incredible in many ways. The routines and graphics
 are amazing, the sound fits the show well, and there are lots of it.
 Still, the size is kept down, so that it fits on only three disks.
 It's almost scary to see how much the good Dr. Skull has put in this demo.
 I've rarely seen a show with so many different effects ranging from
 tunnels to texture mapped 3D-objects, from starfields to wireframe
 figures, from voxel to plasma... The list is long. When starting the demo
 from the little start-script that assigns it to the right location I was
 impressed from the first moment, not so much because of the routines, but
 because of the transitions between them - the first part really just
 floats. Unfortunately the demo - like many others - suffers from the
 "deadline-syndrome", that is in the beginning everything is near perfect,
 but when the time is about to run out at party-place the demo-people has
 no choice but to hurry finishing the demo, which often results in
 unfortunate design in the demo's last parts. It's not a big problem in
 Psychedelic, still you can't avoid noticing it. For example at one point
 in the show the music is suddenly abruptly cut off instead of smoothly
 faded away (or maybe better: Timed to end). Well, let me introduce you to
 a little selection of the many routines: The show starts with a texture
 mapped globe (yes, it's the Earth I believe, home of The Scene). In the
 background you see a lot of stars which shows to be a slightly motion
 blurred 3D starfield, suddenly we land on a green surface, a sun (looks
 strange, but cool) appears for a short while, before it sets. The green
 surface shows to be capable of presenting a nice voxel landscape, fast
 too and in a quite good resolution. And now to something completely
 different: A great 3D scene. The scene itself is nicely build, interesting
 modeling work, and the engine runs okay as well, including motion blur.
 To gain speed (and add atmosphere?) it's all kept in blue colors, and the
 display looks as if only every second line is in use - but it sure is an
 experience anyway. After this little journey through the 3D world we're
 back with a box. A box that reflects the background it is placed in front
 of, it probably is just transparent, but it's nice. Lightsourced 3D is
 up next. Big, advanced objects are used for this purpose which means that
 they don't move, only the lightsources - there are two of them with
 different colors - move. A shame that objects don't move, but then again
 I'm not sure I want to see them move, as the lightsources are slow enough
 already. On next is a simple Doom-routine. Back then it was a rather new
 thing with those 3D-tours around a stranger's basement, and you can
 clearly see that on this routine: The walls are thin as papers, and the
 perspective correction is bad or non-existing, but it's pretty fast.
 After a simple tunnel flight, made from black/white motion blurred
 vectors, an infinity box routine is presented. You see a lot of boxes
 that are locked in a pattern, and when zooming close to one of these boxes
 you discover that it consists of a lot of small boxes itself, and so on.
 The resolution is a bit low here, but the idea is good (seen before maybe,
 but good). Afterwards a "cell division" takes place, the "cells" are
 colored balls where new balls grow from the existing ones, cute. The
 following effects are mostly simple, but nice: Wireframe, distorted
 plasma, texture plasma, stretched plasma, two tunnels - one made from a
 lot of square vector plates, the other one with transparent balls flying
 in front of it - too bad the resolution is so low in this part. In between
 the music cuts (too bad), and a logo is shown. A new piece of music is on
 afterwards. Later in the demo there are two texture mapped boxes, one of
 them even with rotators on its sides, and at the same time its jelly.
 Cool! Also, a bunch of other effects are to find in the demo, it's simply
 amazing how many there are.
 The music ranges from demo/synth tunes to techno, all of a quite good
 quality, and they even fit the visual part quite well. The show ends
 without any kind of credits or similar, they really must have been low on
 time when it was put together! Instead of the traditional scrolltext it
 ends with a hexagon shaped texture mapped torus which hole's size
 changes... But I guess that's an end too.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} So many great routines, graphics and music in one demo - a hit!

@EndNode


@Node "EnforcingTheLaw" "Enforcing the Law / Powerline"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Enforcing the Law
@{B}Group:@{UB} Powerline

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 11 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.06 MB
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030 ('060 for the video sequences)
@{B}Note:@{UB} An enhanced version will maybe be released

@{B}Code:@{UB} Raylight, Chip, Scout/C-lous (c2p)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mad Druid
@{B}Music:@{UB} Wasp

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some nice and original effects
- Monochrome display, the video sequences are processor hungry

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A demo made with the '060 in mind, like many others of The Party 7
 releases. Powerline states that you shouldn't even try to run this demo on
 an '030 or less, it would simply be to slow, but an '060 should be able
 to run it with 25-50 frames per second. The truth is that the demo runs
 pretty well on a fast '030, but still a better processor is recommended
 for the video sequences that is shown here and there in the demo (in order
 to stick to the "law enforcement in US"-theme - I guess it's hard to show
 that using phong ducks and tunnels :-)). Powerline even warns you with a
 requester before starting the demo about the poor condition of your
 processor if it's below '060 of course, but you brave demo watchers out
 there should really press the button if just you have an '030, or else
 you'll miss a quite good show.
 After launching the demo a notice informs you that this demo is non
 racial, then you are told that it's made for monochrome monitors - yes,
 the demo only uses the grayscale - and finally you get the definition of
 the word "law" as taken from a dictionary. A video clip is on next, a
 fight between police and revolting people, and unless your processor is
 fast this is very slow. Luckily that's not the issue with the next couple
 of routines that are smashed into your face with the speed of a McLaren
 racer: Some cool 3D-columns seen from an oblique angle that moves around
 and rotates very fast, some nice plasma (even though plasma is nicest in
 colors), a water-drip effect (the resolution is a bit low here), and
 finally (for now) what looks like a voxel landscape seen from above.
 Up next are the group name and the title, shown with a "spotlight behind
 letters"-effect, a spotlight is pointing towards you while the letters
 scrolls over the screen in front of it, which gives a nice light beams
 effect. Up next is a buggy, but fast 3D landscape, where you fly at an
 insane speed through a canyon. There are lots of black lines here and
 there which shouldn't be there, and I guess this is one of the routines
 that really gets an overhaul if the enhanced version of the demo is
 released. The smoke routine next is one of those that really need some
 processor power, it's a tough job to simulate something as complex as
 smoke, but on the other hand it's a good simulation, however I wouldn't
 mind a better resolution here too. Also, this routine is used for writing
 some text that soon after blows away, looks very nice. Afterwards one
 of the classic discolight balls are presented - a ball with spotlights
 mounted on it, when one spotlight points directly in your direction you
 are blinded, but unlike many others of this kind of routines this one
 actually looks pretty much like real light, as it's more "analog" than
 the once seen earlier. Cool. After a multiple rotation of some kind of
 net, and a bit of a movie, another spotlight effect is presented, this one
 more or less like the one used when presenting the demo, just with a
 texture in front of it instead of letters. Finally there's a water effect
 again, and at last the credits are shown.
 The music is heavy rock, fast, and it fits the demo well.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} The film clips in the demo was grabbed from JFK (by
 Oliver Stone) and Menace to Society.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} The better processor, the better demo! Watch it!

@EndNode


@Node "TearDownTheWall" "Tear Down The Wall / Union"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Tear Down The Wall
@{B}Group:@{UB} Union

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Intel Outside 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 10

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.86 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz with cache burst active, or better processor
@{B}Note:@{UB} Running at to slow processors will cause the music and visuals to
 stop regularly

@{B}Code:@{UB} Musashi, Mad Mack
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Musashi
@{B}Music:@{UB} The Wall by Pink Floyd, Roberts
@{B}Design:@{UB} Musashi

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Great design
- Too big pixels, chunky copper routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Incredible! After this demo you can only ask yourself how Musashi
 has been capable to fit everything in only 868 KB, included the ARexx
 support! The only BIG drawback is an ugly chunky copper routine that ruins
 this great demo. Musashi has been capable to pack all of Pink Floyd's "The
 Wall" music (obviously with data loss), and he has developed the whole
 intro around this tune. There are few effects (space cut, gouraud shading,
 simple light shading), but all applied on many simple texturized 3D
 objects, sounds simple, but it's very original. Then you can see flying 3D
 letters in space-cutting, a head smashed by two hammers, a human shape in
 a rotating room, some flying bricks forming a wall, a 3D water closet and
 the camera that flies into it to show the famous scene of the hammer march
 from the "The Wall" film. Every scene is (probably on faster processor)
 quite in sync with words and the music. But the top effect is the
 voxelscape that appears when the famous guitar solo starts, while a guitar
 3D object flies around in the air, followed by some other objects. Then
 the music of The Wall ends, and the words "Amiga rulez" close this part of
 the demo. But there's a second part with new music (a tracked demo tune)
 and more effects! This part is in classic demo style: A little 3D ambient
 scene rotates on screen. After this ambient coming classic demo effects:
 Texture morphing on a rotating torus, phong shading, a room with a mirror
 where a rotating 3D cube is used to show the perfect mirroring effect, a
 bad bumpmapped cube (the chunky copper routine gets another victim!), a
 classic tunnel with a texturized polygon flying in space-cut. A good
 Descent section (something a bit different from classical the Doom
 sections) finally introduces a texturized rotating cube that clones itself
 into many space-cutting cubes filling the screen, and a torus
 texturemapped with a Union logo enters this space-cutted scene to
 eliminate all effects. The final piece of music (another one!?) introduce
 the credits scrolltext (also in chunky copper), and also all objects seen
 in this demo are represented. All this in only 868 KB. How did they do
 that it?! It could be a strange secondary effect of that chunky copper
 routine? :)

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A demo with great design, but too big pixels. With a c2p
 routine it would be near perfect.
                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "TheTribe" "The Tribe / Three little Elks"

@{B}Name:@{UB} The Tribe
@{B}Group:@{UB} Three little Elks

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Icing
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 6

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.14 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz, better processors to run in high-res
@{B}Note:@{UB} The hidden part is the file named: DontRunMe.elk

@{B}Code:@{UB} Explorer, Tabasco
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Ant, Nude, Tabasco
@{B}Music:@{UB} Coma
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Tudor/TBL

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Good design, funny introducion, animation bonus and hidden part
- Short, slow routines, especially in high resolution

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This is a funny demo, the usual 3le style. The title is shown on a
 plane starfield that scrolls vertical, then a 3D green, flat land appears.
 The camera flies around above this land to see a group of elks dancing
 around a pole to the tribal rhythm of the music in background. Two human
 shapes are attached by their hands on the pole as victims of a sacrifice.
 Then the camera flies away and the tribal music fades out. The music
 changes to a disco tune and a morphing tunnel dances on the screen. After
 the tunnel a complex phong shaded object with spotlights on flies in front
 of a zooming background. The music change again, and we see a wall - or
 rather a bumpmap showing prehistoric graffiti of a "elkian ship" and an
 elk that hunts a fat man and his dog.
 And after a shaded big mask, the end credits are on: Once again the intro
 routine is used this time showing some elks that appear to be coders,
 graphicians and musician of this production. The animation (that you can
 choose in the startup menu) and the hidden part are some funny jokes and
 no-sense animation on the elk theme.
 This demo has a very good design, and its comic style links the various
 parts well together. But the routines are quite slow and high-res is used
 only in the tunnel and phong shaded object parts.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A funny demo, well designed. Have a look.

                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "Trayanda" "Trayanda / Dinx Projects & Skid Row"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Trayanda
@{B}Group:@{UB} Dinx Projects & Skid Row

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Rush Hours
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.89 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Oster, Sachy/Skid Row
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Dr. D
@{B}Music:@{UB} Xtd/Mystic
@{B}Design:@{UB} Sachy/Skid Row, Tinner

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Multitasking, fast objects in 1x1
- No design, too few effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The evident goal of this demo is to advertise for a BBS and send
 some greets. Nothing else. But why did they use 3.89 MB only for this?
 Answer: Because after @{" Limes Inferior " link "LimesInferior"} someone thought that the phong
 routines could be faster, and they could do a demo that shows up to eleven
 complex 3D objects in phong shading on a slow scrolling base painted with
 some sentences or greetings. Ah yes! There are some beautiful pictures
 that break the objects show and there also is an intro: Some light balls
 that become brighter when they cross others, but this intro is very slow
 and is not too different from the same intro in @{" Limes Inferior " link "LimesInferior"}.
 So all bad in this demo? No: the synth styled music is OK, the pictures
 are good and colorful, the demo multitasks and the objects move very
 fast in 1x1. But there's no design and a demo can't be made with only one
 effect.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Coders could be interested, others could stop this demo before
 it ends.
                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "Goatraince" "Goatraince / Loonies"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Goatraince
@{B}Group:@{UB} Loonies

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 7
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 10 of 17

@{B}Size:@{UB} 
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Psycho
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Laika, Gafkhan, Lemniscus, Tarmslyng
@{B}Music:@{UB} Zoomorph
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Lemniscus, Psycho
@{B}Design:@{UB} Tarmslyng, Psycho

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Funny idea, a few nice effects
- Needs transitions, simple effects now and then, bad graphics

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Loonies is a well-chosen name for this group. Who else would
 create a demo about trains? But we start a quite different place: The
 first thing that happens when starting the demo is that you see the test
 picture from Danish television, channel 1. Afterwards someone zaps to
 MTV where a torus flies around with a long blurry tail after it. Another
 couple of zaps leads us back to MTV where a nice plasma effect is on, one
 that looks as if a ball is wrapped into the plasma. Next thing that
 happens is that the TV zaps to the info channel of the Copenhagen trains.
 A texture mapped sign enters the screen afterwards, followed by a lot of
 those hexagon shaped signs spelling the group's name. A quite ugly title
 picture is on next presenting a tunnel with a railway leading through it,
 which is exactly what the next routine is about: Driving on a railway
 through a tunnel. The routine doesn't run completely smooth, and basically
 it's just a texture zoomer, but it works. A train wagon is on next, not
 the last "trainy" object in the demo, and those objects are rather boring
 to watch - even though they are either gouraud or phong shaded it quite
 old-fashioned just to show a rotating object. Greetings are on next, or
 rather on a train seen from the side with the greets written on them (all
 that graffiti...). Some rather basic effects are on next, for example a
 bumpmapped railway lit up by a red and a blue lightsource, a nice twirling
 tunnel that also sometimes split up into two tunnels, ugly pictures (a
 matter of taste of course, but...), and a voxel landscape with the little
 touch that some railways are crossing through the terrain, ending up at
 a train station, and soon after a simple video sequence is shown with
 film from a station. The colors here are blue and red, looks pretty
 psychedelic. After a very simple texture plasma, a flatscape and some
 minor 3D objects the show ends with a reversed scrolltext...
 The music is - as the title suggests - goa techno, spiced up with the
 sound of an old locomotive... Quite okay.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For train freaks only! An extra star for originality!

@EndNode


@Node "Dirt" "Dirt / Mystic"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Dirt
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mystic

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} None
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.37 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} OCS/ECS, needs a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} MSS
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} C.I.A., Gunman
@{B}Music:@{UB} XTD
@{B}Design:@{UB} XTD, MSS

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Good code, simple and clean design...
- ... Maybe too simple, old effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} What a strange name "Dirt" is for one of the most "clean" demos
 I've ever seen! There aren't great effects in it, only some old vector-
 and dot routines. There aren't colorful graphics: Only four pictures in
 naive style (especially Love by Gunman). There aren't screaming sounds:
 The XTD's tune is a simple demo tune, sometimes also a bit boring. But
 every effect is synchronized to the music, and every effect's exit is made
 with vector planes moving or rotating as flying pages. Simple but
 efficacious.
 In this demo you'll see vector titles, some dot spheres pulsating to the
 music, then imploding to explode as a starfield, a vector football field
 on which a dot ball jumps, a very fast and clear rotozoomer, some vector
 filled squares rotating in 3D with persistence and mirror reflection, some
 vector filled fullscreen squares rotating, color cycling, and a classic
 flatshaded 3D big cube.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A simple, but nice demo. Have a look.

                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "Embraced" "Embraced / Floppy"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Embraced
@{B}Group:@{UB} Floppy

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Intel Outside 3
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 19

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.61 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor

@{B}Code:@{UB} Zig, Thorus
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Fame, Grid, Gabi
@{B}Music:@{UB} Revisq

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Cool code, great graphics, good music
- No design, too many tunnels

@{B}Comment:@{UB} If the goal of this demo was to embrace all categories of tunnel
 effects,then the goal is perfectly reached! Imagine as many tunnel
 effects you can: Deformed, rotating, with or without 3D objects in phong
 shade jumping or flying into them, with stormlight effects, bumpmapped
 with moving lights in a strange alpha channel mode. Yes, you'll find them
 in this demo. But it would be really boring to see only tunnel effects, so
 there is also a great phong shaded mask changing color while moving, a
 ripple rotating effects (this effect is circular like a tunnel :-), a pair
 of bumpmapped logos, and also a bumpmapped 3D object. A demonstration of
 powerful code like few others, obviously better if you have a fast
 processor. Also the pictures are great, all in hi-res interlaced. The
 music (two average demo tunes) is added only because that without them
 this demo would be incomplete.
 But there are no links between the effects. There's no design at all. This
 demo is and remains so boring! It's waste of this good material. What a
 pity!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} If you like tunnel effects this is the demo for you. Others
 can find something better.
                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "Ilex" "Ilex / Mystic"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Ilex
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mystic

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} Intel outside 1
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 1

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.77 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, need a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Charon
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} C.I.A., Trocek
@{B}Music:@{UB} XTD
@{B}Design:@{UB} Charon

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Good code, fine music, a pair of simple but original effects
- Lacks a bit of design, some effects are not very original, some
  backgrounds are taken from Scala...

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Like many other demos from the same year, this one is nothing new
 under the sun. There are some common vector based and dot based effects,
 but also a couple of interesting effects. There's a chunky copper anim
 which a vector starship seems to fly into, some digitized karateka's
 fighting anims (taken from a game they were developing), an opaque glass
 on which a hand is writing "Intel Outside", some dot morphing objects and
 curves that seems very much like the same in @{" Desert Dream " link "DesertDream"}, a classic
 3D cube with some vectorial "holes" effects on the faces, a very
 interesting picture shown as waving pages. A flat logo flies out of screen
 and the classic final scrolltext ends this demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A common and average old style demo.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} This is the 2nd Mystic's trackmo.
 The game with the fighting anims is TaeKwonDo Master from Mirage Software

                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "Ilyad" "Ilyad / Alcatraz & Asphyxia Design"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Ilyad
@{B}Group:@{UB} Alcatraz

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 12

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.21 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD installable
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030 or better processor using patched version v1.4

@{B}Code:@{UB} Hornet, Shagan/Asphyxia Design
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} PGCS, Cookie/Asphyxia Design
@{B}Music:@{UB} Zoltar

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Very impressive intro, many good raytraced anims, involving sound effects
- After a great start it's only a sequence of old effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Delusion. After @{" Odyssey " link "Odyssey"} you should expect something great enough
 like that production, maybe better! And the intro part seems to be a good
 start! A morphing dot face saying some words (well digitized) in heroic
 tune, then, after a laugh, explodes. Therefore a big picture of a
 starfield enters to introduce a planet, locked as in a star map on screen
 to show some data: An effect better than the same in @{" Odyssey " link "Odyssey"}! Then
 some raytraced anims starts that are the same scenes of the starship
 exiting from a hangar as seen in @{" Odyssey " link "Odyssey"}, interleaved by screenshot
 of titles and credits. Also this part is great with good graphics and
 involving sounds. Seems to be a film intro, and you expect that more
 quality production will be shown later!
 Well, the demo starts and what do you see? Another boring show of effects
 without design!!! Aaaaaaaaargh! What happened? Where are the raytraced
 anims? Where is that cool intro design? Alcatraz's guys wasted something
 great! Ilyad could have been a legendary demo, the right sequel of
 @{" Odyssey " link "Odyssey"}.
 Instead it's a delusion! The effects are a bit old but well coded: A
 vector tunnel, a texture mapped sphere, a dot rotating object (a
 galleon), raytraced bobble bobs with transparency effect, twisting flat
 shaded torus, deformed rotating picture called water rotation, a texture
 mapped torus, fractal fern, interlaced. But is design to show an effect
 after another, separated by a picture carrying the name of the last shown
 effect? I say no. And also the last effect, a wonderful 3D flat shaded
 flight simulator is not enough to save a so badly designed demo.
 Reading the final scrolltext, you have the sensation that they started a
 big project, but finished it a hurry because of the deadline.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A lost chance for something better.

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "LethalDose2" "Lethal Dose 2 / Faculty"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Lethal Dose 2
@{B}Group:@{UB} Faculty

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Hammering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.8 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, need a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Scribe
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Frame, Shark, Airsmith
@{B}Music:@{UB} Snotty

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Fast routines, good raytraced pictures and animations, good music
- Old and very common effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A well coded production is always welcome. If also it shows some
 good raytraced pictures and animations, it's even more welcome. This demo
 has all of it and can also offer a design that is not too bad. But even
 when they've tried to the traditional effects that is in this demo
 different, they are still very traditional, and that's a drawback.
 Two big objects rotates in spacecut with a bit of transparency, or credits
 shown with a waving plane of dots cannot be called "something original".
 A fast rotating picture of Cindy Crawford with a vertical mirror and a
 very large and fast dot landscape showing a Faculty logo are very well
 optimized, but still it's old stuff. The Cindy Crawford's face could
 be useful to stretch, twist and morph as much as you like, but something
 else shows that the same results could be obtained with any other picture.
 Finally the colored big ball with transparency effect and a jumping
 vector object twisted, completes the show of this effects-not-too-
 original-but-very-fast section of the demo.
 So they tried to include some original effects, and the results are an
 interesting dot tunnel with 2 layers of stars in 3 bitplane on which
 some vector rotozooming words appears to presents some Bezier curves...
 - That are not too different from any other dot lines morphing seen in
 other demos!
 Then they thought: "Why don't we let in a lens effect on flat shaded
 rotating 3D cube?" and they did it, but the result is a bit raw. So they
 included a classic morphing dot cube, and that's quite nice!
 Finally a cool raytraced anim of a little rabbit-toy playing guitar while
 walking is, by far, the best and most original effect of them all!
 Ah! Obviously there is the classic final scrolltext!
 I'm beginning to understand why this demo is named "Lethal Dose"... :-)

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth having a look at, but it's not original.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} This demo is the first Faculty's AGA production.

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "NotAgain" "Not Again / S.C.A.L.A."

@{B}Name:@{UB} Not Again
@{B}Group:@{UB} S.C.A.L.A.

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} None, just for fun
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.91 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, need a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Chaos/Sanity, Crash + Argon + Crazy Crack/Complex
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Sire + DSN/Lego, Agent T/Cream, Fashion/Static Bytes
@{B}Music:@{UB} Tommy/Avena

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Good coding, fun graphics, nice music
- Few effects, no design, ugly chunky copper routine

@{B}Comment:@{UB} What happen when you put together nine guys from the best German
 groups in a room for two day? They make a demo! But two days are too
 few to release something cool and Not Again suffers from this problem.
 This demo starts with titles appearing on a fast zooming base and
 suddenly introduce a very fast Wolfenstein labyrinth, but without ceiling
 and floor and with very big pixels. Then a rotozooming picture of a
 chicken jumps on the screen and in the background of this chicken a
 pseudo plasma is composed, while all this rotozooming is strecthed and
 deformed. Second rotozoom effect: On the logo - Not Again - some
 transparent shade bobs are drawn. Final effect: A digitized animation of
 all 9 Sceners sitting in front of the camera. That's all.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Watch it only if you want to see how it looks when 9 Amigas and
 9 of the most famous german sceners meet.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} The S.C.A.L.A. "party" was held from 25 to 27.02.94.
 If you run this demo on A500, after the Wolfenstein parts, a picture will
 inform you that this production cannot continue, because you have
 "not AGA-in"!

@{B}Note:@{UB} S.C.A.L.A. is short for Sanity, Complex, Avena, Lego And
 others
                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "Switchback" "Switchback / Rebels"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Switchback
@{B}Group:@{UB} Rebels

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} Doom's Day
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 5

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.56 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Zulu, Gray
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Kris, Slime, Teevaan, Demon, Eracore, Grey, Srl, Excess
@{B}Music:@{UB} Chromag, Vocal

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Good effects, good graphics, great music, good design
- All effects are in chunky copper, this means BIG pixels

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This is the first AGA demo by Rebels and it's a good start for the
 them. The effects aren't really innovative, though, but they are very
 well coded. The demo starts in a wireframe tunnel, but the choice  of
 colors are quite bad which makes it almost invisible. The title graphics
 are on next that appears and disappears in random positions on the screen
 very well synchronized to the music (a cool demo style tune by Chromag with
 a very good rhythmic base). Now the effects start: A picture twisted in
 whirlpool mode, a very cool picture by Kris, a five pointed star zooming
 with a strong shade effect, a distorted tunnel, a big Rebels logo twisted
 in sinus mode, a kaleidoscope, a very impressive 3D dot routine, Julia
 fractals deforming, and a distorted interference
 effects - really cool. But many of these effects are in chunky copper with
 too big pixels. Then the demo ends and the end scrolltext... No, it was a
 joke! The demo is on again and a blue fire effect introduces a very
 impressive raytraced animation of a roller coaster (a masterpiece by
 Excess) seen as if you are tripping on it. The coolness of this effect is
 that animation play is controlled by the music's rhythm. And I grant you,
 the distorted guitars of Vocal's tune make the voyage on roller coaster
 very involving! What a pity for that the pixels are so big in during the
 animation and also in the fire effect. The final scrolltext and a short
 funky tune (really) ends the demo.  It's a very good and innovative way
 they've used the animation, but it's not enough to make the demo a
 masterpiece.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} The roller coaster voyage is something to experience more than
 once!

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "Tenebra" "Tenebra / Biosynthetic Design"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Tenebra
@{B}Group:@{UB} Biosynthetic Design

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Somewhere in Holland 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 6

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.83 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Hedgehog, Metal Designer
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Lry, Parsec, Dixie Flatline, Fra
@{B}Music:@{UB} Parsec, Stun
@{B}Design:@{UB} Parsec, Metal Designer, Hedgehog

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Good code, involving sound effects, quite good design
- Old and common effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Tenebra is an Italian word that means darkness. A good theme to
 build a demo around. Some text pictures explain various meanings of what
 "Tenebra" is. With "dark" music, strange style, it forms sort of a logical
 link between the effects. The design isn't excellent, not bad
 either, but there are some seconds with complete blackout after the intro
 pictures: Seems that the demo crashed! I think it's a practical
 demonstration of what Tenebra means...
 After this "crash" the effects start. A lousy "tunnel" (it's a picture
 with a simple color cycle) introduces some morphing dot objects. The first
 shapes are the BSD logo, the second is the Intel Outside logo, then a
 torus and a ball appear. This ball begins to bounce around, and when the
 music changes, a full textured bouncing ball appears. Next effect is a
 little 3D textured cube with some animations as texture that morphs into a
 pyramid with some other textures on it. The music changes and a
 rotozooming picture smash on screen very fast, followed by a classic tunnel
 effect with big pixels. Finally some pictures of the authors of this demo
 are shown as credits, and after a very fast, but very low-res fire effect,
 the final scrolltext ends this demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Nothing exceptional, but not bad at all either

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "TheHoiSaga3" "The Hoi Saga 3 / Team Hoi"

@{B}Name:@{UB} The Hoi Saga Part III
@{B}Group:@{UB} Team Hoi

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} None
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.24 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, need a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Price/T.F.A., Rhino, Ritgore, Schwarzenegger/T.F.A.
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Metin 7
@{B}Music:@{UB} Ramon
@{B}Design:@{UB} Metin 7, Rhino, Ritgore, Schwarzenegger/T.F.A.

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ An impressive 3D multiscrolling plane
- Too long and old effects, lacking design, boring

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This is one of firsts AGA demos ever made. That's important to
 keep in mind. But that doesn't justify the big lack of design in this
 demo. The first effect is a Wolfenstein labyrinth without ceiling and
 floor but with mirror effects like on water: Ugly and slow. But it's one
 of firsts
 Doom-like effects in 256 colors and with animated textures. The second
 effect is a fast and impressive 3D multiscrolling plane enhanced by a
 funny sprite of a character with a jetpack floating on this base, and
 some scrolling bobs and stars that enhances the depth.
 Everything is very well synchronized, but it takes too long and of course
 it gets boring. Then it's time for some promotional pictures for the game
 Moonchild (I don't know if it was ever released) appearing with some old
 copper effects, but also this gets boring. After that there's a funny
 moment: With some texts they caricature Star Trek's characters (Captain
 Jerk, Miss U-Whora, etc.) to present a rotozooming effect with two "sexy"
 pictures, especially when zooming closer to some female anatomic parts...
 Obviously also this effect is shown for too long, but at least it's a bit
 more attractive! The final effect is once again that 3D
 multiscrolling plane fly with a new texture and new music, and (aaargh!!!)
 also this is shown too long! Then, after greetings and credits, there's no
 more. The "link" between effects is a boooooooring little animation of
 three wheels. Tunes are in classic demo style, but nothing exceptional,
 the same goes for the graphics.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Its only worth is the historical value.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} In the bootblock of disk 3 a hidden message
 say that near end of demo there's a hidden part, but I haven't found it.
 Have you?

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode
@Node "NakedAce" "Naked Ace / Cirion"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Naked Ace
@{B}Group:@{UB} Cirion

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Juhla
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 8 of 12

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.9 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} ASA
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mindeye
@{B}Music:@{UB} Amber

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Some nice routines
- Short, some blitterscreen used

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A very short, little demo this is. It contains only three or four
 routines, one or two of these use blitterscreen, and all of them are fast.
 Cirion most be movie fans, the demo starts with something that looks a lot
 like the 20th Fox logo (the one with the letter monument and the
 spotlights shining towards the sky). Of course the spotlights are in the
 demo too, however, they are more simple than the "real" thing.
 The first real routine is the credits part that introduces some simple
 letters formed from a few dots, thus making it hard to read, and when a
 nice fire blur routine is added it's almost impossible to read - but what
 the hell: It looks nice! Also the next routine is nice. You're flying
 through a lot of texture mapped columns that raises from the bottom of the
 screen to the top. It's a fast routine and the textures are well drawn.
 Last effect is three lensflares flying around, nothing particular to see
 here, but not bad either. A picture is shown now, an average one that has
 nothing to do with anything previously, or later, in the demo (I guess).
 The music is hard to define. I guess you could call it experimental,
 traditional, demo techno?! I've heard better music for sure, but then
 again: I've seen better demos for sure!
 It all ends with an ugly textscreen written in Finnish language, not to be
 understood by everybody else than themselves!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} I guess they should have waited to release the demo till it was
 finish!

@EndNode


@Node "ShakkaLakka" "Shakka Lakka / Digital"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Shakka Lakka
@{B}Group:@{UB} Digital

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} A hot day in June
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.93 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA. To install on HD it needs a patch, my patch requires:
 2 MB chip-RAM, 1 or 1.5 MB fast-RAM, and a HD...

@{B}Code:@{UB} Dillenger
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} GFX-Twins
@{B}Music:@{UB} G.T.O.

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nice dot routines
- Many simple or primitive routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The show starts with some pictures that tell you the name of the
 demo and group - the quality of these pictures are okay, but nothing
 exceptional. One thing you notice quite fast is the little rotating logo
 located in the upper left corner of the screen, it's there throughout the
 entire demo. The first routine is a slightly blurred dot tunnel, looks
 good with that blur, it somewhat raises this tunnel above many other dot
 tunnels. The credits are up next, also this is a dot routine: A rotating
 cube shows the tasks, while the names are shown in the corners of the
 screen. Like many other demos this one also contains a doom routine, but
 as this routine wasn't very well developed back in 1994 (especially not
 on Amiga) this one is rather primitive. The display area is small, so is
 the dungeoun that has no ceiling or floor and only one kind of texture on
 the walls. On the other hand it's quite fast. Next up is a small jelly
 vector cube, followed by a fractal generator that makes lightning look-a-
 like fractals. After having drawn a couple of those (quite fast) another
 dot cubes zooms towards you, and it shows that it has a hard to read
 scrolltext one it. Dillenger is really happy about those dots? After a
 picture a you are presented to a zoom/rotator/stretcher effect. The only
 drawback about it is that in order to get it running fast enough the
 resolution is made (too) low. Too bad! After some text a torus is on, and,
 yes, you guessed it; it's a dot torus making some interesting morphs, thus
 still being a torus.
 Suddenly the demo-style music is cut of abruptly, making room for a quite
 piano piece and a scrolltext, better known as the endscroller.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Even for a 1994 demo the standard is quite low I suppose

@EndNode


@Node "Ninja" "Ninja / Melon."

@{B}Name:@{UB} Ninja
@{B}Group:@{UB} Melon.

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 4
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 7 of 22

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.8 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} HeatSeeker (Ivar)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Joachim
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jason

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice cartoon style animation
- Lack of plot

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A cute little animation - not demo - from Melon. that obviously
 was a hit at The Party as it entered the top 10 there, despite of its
 simple story. But the stylish drawings and the atmospheric film-like music
 somewhat saves the show anyway.
 As you have probably guessed by now its about a ninja. He wakes up when
 there is the need to do so, and this is now. It could be funny to know who
 the victim is (if any?)!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Have a look! Reminds me of cheap, but professional cartoons!

@EndNode


@Node "Boggledop" "Boggledop / Sanity"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Boggledop
@{B}Group:@{UB} Sanity

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.36 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Tron
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Havok, Sire, Christine
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jester

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Funny style, nice music
- Simple routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The thing that really makes this demo different from most others
 is the way that Sanity has used a cartoon style to introduce the whole
 thing, and mixed it into the demo here and there. For example the whole
 show starts with a mix of cartoonish sounds, nothing happens on screen:
 "It's boggledop time"! You might remember Sonic the Hedgehog. His our
 host, the one that introduces us to the Sega style logo. It's all a nice
 little animation in this first part.
 The second part is a classic "effect after effect"-part, where we have a
 logo in top of the screen, the effect in the middle and a scrolltext and
 a little game in the bottom - the game is about getting a potato with legs
 to the other end of the screen before the water melon gets there by
 jerking off the joystick (connected to the computer). Hint: connect the
 mouse to the joy-port and move it quitely around, that'll have a much
 greater effect than tearing the joystick apart :)! Most of the effects are
 just as exciting as the game, seen with nowadays eyes. It's different kind
 of box-objects exposed to different kinds of effects (shading, glenz,
 morph to other objects and simple vector objects on their sides).
 Also, there's a little, simple plasma, and as the final effect (which is
 a fine raytraced animation): A cute chicken walking across the screen,
 made by Sire. The demo ends with a picture drawn by Jester's girlfriend,
 Christine, presenting Spirou and his teacher... And then there's the
 scrolltext. All in all the demo seems to be a little too long, but
 Sanity's odd humour really seems to help making it more interesting than
 the average oldschool demo.
 The music is a little amusing tune, today a pretty famous one too. Tends
 to get on your mind - not on your nerves...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a technically good demo, but worth having a look at

@EndNode


@Node "Extension" "Extension / Pygmy Projects"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Extension
@{B}Group:@{UB} Pygmy Projects

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1993
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 8

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.7 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} OCS or better, 1 MB chip-RAM, Backstab.library (included)
@{B}Note:@{UB} Exists as both disk and file version

@{B}Code:@{UB} Coconut, Flame
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cenobit
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jester/Sanity

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice vector routines, good music
- Small bugs, resets on exit

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Pygmy Projects hasn't lived for nothing, this demo proves that.
 The pace is high, the routines mostly simple, but nice and the music quite
 catchy. After a loader picture and a Pygmy logo the first routines appear
 together with the credits. It's a square dot tunnel, a little change from
 the often round ones. The demo demo's name is presented in a highly
 original way: The name is written with big black letters across the
 screen, while in the background a vector cube is pushing part of the
 letters from behind, so that they wrap around the cube thereby getting
 nearer towards the viewers. Dotscapes is up next, some colorful and fast
 ones that is, but unfortunately there's a bug here that makes the music
 loose its beat. Next on is a "cube in cube in cube"-effect, that is a lot
 of cubes are placed as if was some kind of Chinese box. The inner one
 twists around, but as it is somehow tied together with the one in the next
 layer it fails to move much, instead it pulls the other one with it
 around (I suppose it's easier to understand if you see it for yourself).
 Two versions of this routine is presented, and they are really worth
 watching. Afterwards some 2D vector morph is on the screen, transparent
 too, so that you can sense the background through the objects. The routine
 is fast, but also a bit buggy. The next one is my favourite: It's a
 combination of the just mentioned morph routine and the silhuette of a
 3D city rotating in the background (actually looks like 2D). Furthermore
 noise is added to the picture to make it even more interesting. Next up
 is a series of flatshaded 3D vector objects, shown as a pair of two, a big
 one and a little where the little cast its shadow on the big one. At this
 point the good, traditional demo-pop music (you've probably heard it
 before: Cyberride) changes into a more quiet and atmospheric tune, which
 fits the night-flight over a 3D vector city pretty good. The only thing
 you can see is some white dots representing windows in the big buildings,
 but still the illusion is quite good, considering... Last effect is cute,
 3D vector, and also original, not ingenious though. A rotating cube is
 placed below a line of falling pixels, and as the pixels hits the cube
 they are smashed into a direction that matches the way the cube turns.
 Looks good. Finally there's a lot of textscreens and then the computer
 resets.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth having a look at. Many simple, but nice routines.

@EndNode


@Node "QuiteUnusual" "Quite Unusual / Razor 1911"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Quite Unusual
@{B}Group:@{UB} Razor 1911

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 6 of 11

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.65 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Colorbird
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Danny/Spaceballs
@{B}Music:@{UB} Lizardking (and maybe Chorus & Sid?)

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Good music
- Only one "routine"

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A quite unusual demo that only contains one routine, or rather an
 animation, maybe (yes!)? What happens is that you fly around in a small
 3D-world, and that's it. The show are colorless, only the grayscale is
 used, and the display is a bit "unclear". Also the resolution isn't the
 best, but acceptable. As this 3D-scene is the only effect it gets rather
 boring to watch after a while (and it's on for a long time), but the
 brilliant music somewhat saves this (that is if you like Lizardking's
 style - in my opinion the module in this demo is one of his best!). The
 demo ends with a scrolltext containing credits, critisism of The Gathering
 and commercials, just to mention a few topics.
 Two questions pop into my mind: 1) Can you call this a demo? 2) Is this
 actually coded - most likely not I guess, but on the other hand noone gets
 credits for animation...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} If you like Lizardking music this is the demo for you!

@EndNode


@Node "Prurient" "Prurient / Rebels"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Prurient
@{B}Group:@{UB} Rebels

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.3 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Zulu, Grey
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Smoke, Grey
@{B}Music:@{UB} Chromag

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Some simple, but nice routines
- Some routines are "too simple"

@{B}Comment:@{UB} As they say themselves in the demo is is a mix of old routines,
 which have been put together to create this little, simple demo. Five or
 six routines are to be found in it, some simple, but nice, others too
 simple. The nice ones are a interference effect, where three points
 attached to the box's sides they move within causes a nice effect (hard to
 explain, but infact it's quite simple to understand when you see it...).
 Another one is a cute text plotter that presents text on a textscreen in
 various ways. The "too simple" ones are a 3D "box world", where simple
 vector boxes are placed here and there. The positive thing about it is
 that you can control the "camera" yourself using the mouse and a joystick.
 Also the last routine, a rotator, is what you could call below average
 simply because of the low resolution and the small display area used.
 The music is a happy calypso-like tune, makes you dream about long white
 beaches, the blue ocean and nice women (or men if you're a woman?!) in
 bathing suits (in worst case), or if you're a women in shorts (or less)...
 :-)
 Even though it's a fine tune (especially the technical side of it) it
 doesn't match the demo quite well. It's simply too happy.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Old routines can be nice, just watch this one (once)

@EndNode


@Node "LurkingShadows" "Lurking Shadows / Suburban Shape"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Lurking Shadows
@{B}Group:@{UB} Suburban Shape

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.21 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ECS or better, 2 MB RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Randall, P. E. N. 
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Eracore, Sniffer
@{B}Music:@{UB} Randall
@{B}Design:@{UB} Randall, Sniffer

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Different
- Some tasteless effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is somehow different from most others. Firstly, there's
 a quite unreadable font that is used a lot for some fast textscreens here
 and there. Secondly, most effects are totally acid! The show moves at a
 great speed, you have to be an experienced watcher to enjoy the show, but
 on the other hand if you are experienced you'll found out that the demo
 isn't exactly state of the art demo production. The before mentioned
 effects are fullscreen rotating, galaxy-shaped, colorcycling "things"
 that'll make you go insane within a few minutes if watched intensly. Also,
 there's a line effect that looks a little like when you move a laserbeam
 quickly around through smoke. There's also a tunnel animation, but like
 all of the other effects the number and choice of colors are quite
 tasteless. Of positive thing there are some signs of design here and there
 that helps on the overall empression, still it can't hide the lack of
 quality in the effect area. The music during the demo's mainpart is a
 medium piece of drum'n'bass, and when the endtexts appear a good techno
 tune is played.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not recommended, unless you like hypnosis-effects

@EndNode


@Node "Code187" "Code 187 / Sunshine Productions"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Code 187
@{B}Group:@{UB} Sunshine Productions

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} -
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.46 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020, AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz or better, 2 MB fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Mr. Coke
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Grid/Balance^Freezers, Mr. Coke
@{B}Music:@{UB} Digit

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nothing particular
- Needs variation, mismatching music

@{B}Comment:@{UB} After starting this demo the first screen that appears is a
 drawing that looks as if it was drawn by a child with the group's name on
 it. I thought something like: "Ĺh nej, er det nu endnu en af disse
 spille dum demoer?", which means something like: "Oh no, is it once again
 one of those playing stupid demos?", but fortunately I was wrong. The
 next thing that happen is that the sun on the picture becomes a phong
 object while the rest of the picture quickly disappears. Another
 background is added and the object flies around with a short blur tail
 after it. So far so good, but the problem with this production is that
 that's almost all there is: Phong objects flying around one by one. The
 Exception is some texture mapped cubes with a picture on their sides,
 but that's all. On the other hand it's a short production, so you don't
 really get bored, it's just so very uninteresting when that's all there
 is. The routine running those objects is okay, not the fastest ever seen,
 not slow either, and with no sorting errors observed, but that's far from
 enough.
 The music could be good, but because of a noisy bunch of rhythms running
 at a lot of BPM's it's not. First of all it doesn't fit the visual part's
 steady speed, and secondly it doesn't sound good.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not recommended

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} Code 187 is the code used by the police when someone
 has been killed. The demo's textfile accuses someone for not spreading
 demos that are not released on a party, but just for fun, and they find it
 very devistating towards The Scene (which is quite understandable). That's
 most probably the reason for the demo's title (interpret that!).

@EndNode


@Node "PantaRhei" "Panta Rhei / Talent"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Panta Rhei
@{B}Group:@{UB} Talent

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.62 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Stripe The Gremlin
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Zytron, Mace, Jackass
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jukebox
@{B}Design:@{UB} Zytron, Mace, Jackass

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Fast routines, refreshing speed, nice design, perfectly timed music
- Simple routines, short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} An oldschool like production with some fast, simple routines,
 traditional and good demo music (perfectly timed) and nice logos.
 Everything runs quite fast, so you're never bored, but that also means
 that the show doesn't last for very long. A couple of minutes and it's all
 over. It starts presenting the group and the title (shown with nicely
 drawn logos), followed by the credits that are placed in the middle of the
 screen, while transparent chess-like squares slowly moves away from the
 text in the top and the bottom of the screen. Everytime a new name is
 shown the music makes an appropriate beat, and that goes for the rest of
 the demo as well too: Good timing! Next routine is also those checked
 plates, but this time you are flying through them. There's both a "plain"
 version and a transparent. After a not too nice picture Stripe is proud to
 announce: "For the first time on the AMIGA: realtime 3D fractals, 16
 colors". Looks like voxel... You're flying above the ocean looking at some
 small islands. The display area used is very small, but on the other hand
 it's fast (at least on my computer). Afterwards a 32 color glenz diamond
 is on, followed by a very simple 3D-rollercoaster, that is it's vector
 graphic (of course), you see no sign of any trails, but just simple
 plates, blue and yellow. Even though it's extremely fast it's not quite
 enough to give you the illusion of actually being in a rollercoaster
 wagon.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For those who like the demos from late '80s, early '90

@EndNode


@Node "Talentiaden" "Talentiaden / Talent"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Talentiaden
@{B}Group:@{UB} Talent

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.16 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Scourger
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mace
@{B}Music:@{UB} Sundance Kid, El Loco
@{B}Support:@{UB} Cindy, Lord Stradh

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Fast routines
- Simple and few routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Very few routines is included in this dentro, and those that are
 included are simple. Actually it mostly looks as if Talent wanted to make
 a greeting production instead of one worth watching except for the ones
 greeted. The few, simple routines are a glenz object with a glenz cube
 inside it, pulsating color bars with small color differences adjustd after
 its width and finally transparent and lightsourced cubes, a red and a
 blue. During the pulsator routine a scrolltext including the credits and
 some greetings are shown, and when the demo is over more greetingss and
 credits are shown on a lot of textscreens. The music reminds me a little
 of the music froma typical gameshow, but I guess it fits the demo okay
 anyway.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not recommended

  @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Talentiaden1.GIF"} A cute little routine

@EndNode


@Node "Showtime" "Showtime / Talent"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Showtime
@{B}Group:@{UB} Talent

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.1 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Cindy
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mace
@{B}Music:@{UB} El Loco, Sundance Kid
@{B}Design:@{UB} Cindy

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Interactive
- Simple all the way through

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A very short and very simple dentro. After a couple of nice logos
 that present the group, a scrolltext explain you how to control the
 dentro, it's somewhat interactive (that means that by pressing the mouse
 you either skip to next routine (LMB) or pause it (RMB). After that a
 vector logo is on, lightsourced, and after that a couple of 3D vector
 objects, also lightsourced. Finally there's some end texts with a 3D
 starfield in the background, and yes, you can control it by mouse.
 The music is a little happy tune, easy listening I guess.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Very short and very simple, avoid!

  @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/ShowTime.GIF"} Simple 3D

@EndNode


@Node "YulBrynner" "Yul Brynner was a SkinHead / Universal Soldiers"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Yul Brynner was a SkinHead
@{B}Group:@{UB} Universal Soldiers

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.42 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Suny, GFX-Twins
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Good music
- Some routines are simple

@{B}Comment:@{UB} After some logos introducing us the show (among them a traced
 US logo), the title is shown on a funny picture by Suny. Next on is a
 hypnotic effect consisting of some rotating two colored circles in the
 background and rotating lines and growing circular lines in the foreground
 (pretty hard to explain and understand). Some messages are printed at this
 screen. After that a simple gouraud shaded figure is on, followed by a
 worm hole. That means you see a whole in the ground from an oblique angle
 that (in this case) spews out a lot of texture (ugly texture too). The
 hypnotic effect is back followed by an excellent picture by Woody Allen.
 Finally a buggy and simple 3D-logo is shown, which ends the demo (or is it
 just a bug in my version?).
 The music is a good, laidback and quiet piece of funk.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Some of it is worth watching, but as an overall it fails

@{B}Inside information:@{UB}
 The title refers to the American actor Yul Brynner (1915-1985) born in
 Russia. He was of Swiss-Mongolian gipsy stock. But was he really a
 skinhead? :)

@EndNode


@Node "Idea" "Idea / Depth"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Idea
@{B}Group:@{UB} Depth

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Compusphere
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 5

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.93 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Pigeon, Omen
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Sprocket
@{B}Music:@{UB} Brainstorm

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some fast routines
- The music isn't too good

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Depth is in general known for their crazy productions, but as it's
 a group of many facets they have actually made a quite nice, serious demo
 here. It starts with a collage where also the demos name is present. The
 first routine is on shortly after, it's a tunnel using a few red colors,
 while the group's name is jumping around in the middle of it all. The
 tunnel disappears and the credits is shown, also with restless letters.
 Afterwards a duble bumpmap routine is on, that is two transparent bumpmaps
 that runs over/under each other. This routine is fast, and so so is the
 next one: A lightsourced zoomrotator. The lightsource is a spotlight that
 brighten a little part of the blue texture, while it spins around and
 slowly zooms in and out. The coders have done a very good job here! Untill
 now the music has been a quite noisy piece of techno with fast triphop
 drums, but now it changes to some silent tunes and sound effects. The
 reason is that a plasma effect appears on the screen, a nice one too, but
 it seems to move to fast compared to the music. And it's on for a little
 too long. A transparent twin tunnel is on afterwards, together with the
 noisy music. It's just like with the bumpmap where you see the same effect
 running twice at the same time. Nice! The final effect is a rings-in-water
 effect with the title collage as background. This routine is quite slow,
 but in a good resolution. Finally there's a textscreen, and clicking the
 right mouse button ends the demo.
 The demo is put together in quite a hurry, which is the reason why the
 design is a bit strange, but then again design isn't everything...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Fast routines, but needs some polishing here and there

@EndNode


@Node "TLA" "T. L. A. / The Experience"

@{B}Name:@{UB} T. L. A.
@{B}Group:@{UB} The Experience

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Coven
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.67 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} Raven
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Epsilon, Traksion, Raven
@{B}Music:@{UB} Epsilon

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Some fast routines
- Bad music, bad design, short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} T. L. A. is short for "Three Letter Acronym", but no matter
 what that means I can't see what is have to do with the demo... There are
 no innovative effects, music or graphics in it, and only the code is
 really  worth mentioning. The house music is quite bad, while the graphics
 ranges from bad to average. Both the demo and the effects run fast, and
 they have to in order to keep ones attention as it is quite common
 routines, but wrapped into quite bad design. To mention is a tunnel
 zoomer, two different "texture disturbers" (like looking through bumpy
 glass), a fast rotating Siepenski triangle build from dots, and finally a
 wallwrap routine with a glass ball in front of it (a texture is moved
 around on the screen, and the parts of it that are near the screen's
 borders are close to you, while the center part is away from you). The
 ball is a nice touch, and the speed is excellent. The demo ends with some
 textscreens.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} You sure can live without it

@EndNode


@Node "Inside" "Inside / Polka Brothers"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Inside
@{B}Group:@{UB} Polka Brothers

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.1 MB

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ----

+ Beautiful message
- Booooring

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Polka Brothers are wellknown for their strange productions,
 this demo, however, is a failure. Or rather this slideshow. What happens
 is that a lot of pictures presenting more or less random chosen people
 faces, common for them all is that they don't exactly look like super
 models. All pictures are grayscaled, no colors are used. This slideshow
 goes on for several minutes, while hypnotic drum'n'bass sounds and rhythms
 are heard in the background. But there's a point to this madness: If you
 are patiented enough to hang on to the end of the show you'll be asked:
 "Where does real beauty come from?", and to guide you a big, red,
 pulsating, cartoonish heart is placed in the background (hint, hint).....
 
@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Most people hasn't got the stamina to go through this!

@EndNode


@Node "WaterWhisper" "Water Whisper / Chryseis of Hoodlum"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Water Whisper
@{B}Group:@{UB} Chryseis of Hoodlum

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} -
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.1 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, A lot of chip-RAM, runs on '020 and better

@{B}Code:@{UB} Unix, JMS
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Unix, Dr. Pat, Angel
@{B}Music:@{UB} Unix

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Pretty nice design, fitting music
- Short, a bit boring

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is one of the few silent demos that is out there.
 Both the speed, choice of colors and music seems to be considered when
 making it, and it surely pays off. The effects are common, but pretty
 fast, which isn't that odd since the whole show runs in widescreen, only
 about half of the screen is used for the demo part.
 It starts with a nice Hoodlum logo with a red "ocean" behind it. Looks
 like a big sea of slime slowly waving up and down. The perspective is
 perfect. The title screen is on afterwards (quite ugly) and another plasma
 like effect is presented, this time a texture moving around behind some
 rings (looks like rings in water that has been frozen, so that they don't
 move). Next up is a fire effect, except that it doesn't look like fire,
 but water, both because of the color and because of the way it has been
 used with a lot of blur on it, and a lot of X-axis movement. This routine
 is on for too long, though. The last effect, except for the credits, is
 a pulsating bar that looks like morphing chess pieces seen from the side.
 Quite nice in all its simplicity. And then the credits is shown for a very
 short period of time using a zoom/rotator routine (not the fastest in the
 world). Back is the endscroller with a beatiful logo in the background.
 The music is a very quiet piece of acid inspired techno, fits the demo
 very well. Except for a part where Unix tries to make a melody in it (I
 think) it's enjoyable, also without the demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A relaxing demo, try it if you feel like it

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/WaterWhisper01.jpg"} The start effect is hidden behind the group name
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/WaterWhisper02.jpg"} And the title "picture" is boring...
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/WaterWhisper03.jpg"} A traditional, but nice plasma/water effect
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/WaterWhisper04.jpg"} Looks like a chess piece, but it vibrates
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/WaterWhisper05.jpg"} An excellent logo ends the show

@EndNode


@Node "Tetsuo" "Tetsuo / Depth"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Tetsuo
@{B}Group:@{UB} Depth

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Scene Meeting
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 2

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.44 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, runs on '020-'060
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030

@{B}Code:@{UB} Optima, Blueberry/Efreet (system code), Cosmos/Sanity (player)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Optima
@{B}Music:@{UB} Curt Cool
@{B}Design:@{UB} Optima, Corial

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Lots of routines
- Lack of design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo was released at a small party in Denmark, about 43
 people attended (I know because I was there). And compared to the party's
 size I must say this demo is rather good. It got the first place with just
 one point more than its competitor @{" Mental Brain Disorder " link "MentalBrainDisorder"} by Loonies, even
 though I guess it should have won. But that's the way it is... The demo
 features a lot of different routines, strange soundtrack with a mix of
 many different styles of music: Triphop, jungle, easy listening, fusion.
 The few pictures that are used as fading backgrounds are scans of asians
 taken from some Internet porn-site (but you only get to see the faces, so
 relax :)). It all starts with a flickerscreen where you see the group
 name, title, a wireframe object and one of the before mentioned pictures
 fading in for a short while. The first "real" routine is some meta-like
 lightballs flying around with a simple starfield in the background, but I
 don't think that it looks very nice, but interesting it is. Tunnels are
 common, and of course there's also one in this demo (with all the many
 routines it would be wierd if it wasn't there!). The tunnel is actually a
 texture zoomer which has been seen before, but this one is with a
 spotlight in the end of it that shines towards the viewer. Looks quite
 good, even though I would have prefered a better resolution. Also
 torusses have been seen before (actually way to many times), but the one
 Optima uses is a bit more interesting than the common torus: It's made of
 wireframe, and it got a dense blured tail behind it. Next on is a
 flatscape (planar), grayscale, with one of these asian women pictures
 as transparency effect, fading in and out. The greetings are on next
 written on a boring textscreen (might not be so boring for the IRIS
 memebers...), followed by more meta-like balls, just with another color
 and a new filled vector background. Next on is a flower-shaped plasma
 (nice, but like the tunnel the resolution is a bit too low), then wallwrap
 (the part of the texture nearest to the edge is close to you, while the
 part of the texture that is near the middle of the screen is far away from
 you). An interesting bumpmap routine is next: The wireframe torus is back,
 but this time exposed to bumpmap and what follows (that is a spotlight).
 Quite nice! Another wallwrap like routine is on afterwards, but this one
 has a ball in the middle with the background's texture wrapped around it.
 Unfortunately it lacks colors I think, more of them would make smoother
 fades between the colors. The last routine also suffers from this
 concerning the background, while it is fully intended on the primary
 routine as it is a simple, filled, pulsating vector column. Not too
 interesting and on for too long. All in all a bad ending on an on many
 points quite okay demo. The routines has all been seen before, runs at
 a good framerate (measured on a '030/50MHz), the design is, let's say,
 mixed... The music fits it all okay.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Lots of routines, lots of different design... Try it if you
 feel like it!

@EndNode


@Node "YourAstralPilot" "Your Astral Pilot / Johan Alpmar & Co"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Your Astral Pilot
@{B}Group:@{UB} Johan Alpmar & Co

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Remedy
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 6 of 6...

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.86 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} -

@{B}By:@{UB} Johan Alpmar, Mikael Kalms, Bjorn "Mr U" Flink, Martin Kalms

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ----

+ Trancing, multitasking
- Monotone, few effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I'm not sure you could call this a demo as it contains only
 one effect, a colorcycling strobe light... That doesn't mean that the
 screen just flashes in different colors. It is designed to look as if you
 look directly into a flashing spotlight, and to make it a bit more
 interesting some lines of different colors is merged into the light, which
 results in a star shape. All the time through the whole "demo" the screen
 flashes, and if you read the readme-file (which is addressed to "earthly
 or otherwise") you'll find out that the goal with this production is to
 meet the alien within yourself... With a good help from the fairly good
 trancy techno you might succeed in finding that alien, but I suppose that
 you have to inhale some LSD or the like while watching the "demo" to make
 that happen. Except for the colorcycling there's actually a picture
 included in the show, which (of course) also flashes, but you have to be
 really patient to get to that part, and even more patient to see the short
 credits in the end. No wonder they warn epileptics before the show starts!
 I would say this production belongs to a techno party rather than in The
 Scene.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Trance freaks: Put on your sunglasses (the rest of you
 look elsewhere...)!

@EndNode


@Node "Relic" "Relic / Nerve Axis"

@{B}Name:@{UB} @{" Relic " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/RelicTitle.GIF"}
@{B}Group:@{UB} Nerve Axis

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 7

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.92 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020 or better, AGA, PAL, 1.7 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM,
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060
@{B}Note:@{UB} Following parameters can be used:

@{B}Code:@{UB} Schlott
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Meson, Wade
@{B}Music:@{UB} Ganja
@{B}Additional design:@{UB} Zone, Crash, Halflob

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ****

+ Very nice 3D scenes, good graphics and music, atmospheric, magnificient!
- May be a little boring to some

@{B}Comment:@{UB} When Nerve Axis released their first great demo at Assembly
 1997 all Sceners were stunned. The English based group had been very quiet
 before that release, and the only thing that they were known for was the
 diskmag Pressure of which they've published just a single issue. Nobody,
 or at least just few, though that they could be a "threat" to the
 more established and wellknown Scene. But they sure could. @{" Pulse " link "Pulse"}, their
 Assembly 1997 demo, beat all other demos by far, and was to find in the
 top of all demo charts quickly afterwards. At The Gathering 1998 Mellow
 Chips/TRSi made a, for Amiga, completely different demo called @{" Rise " link "Rise"}. A lot
 of different opinions among Sceners were heard, because of the fact that
 the demo consisted of 3D scenes all the way through, more or less. The
 technical scene of that demo was good, no doubt about that, it was the
 contents or lack of it that was the big question. However, Nerve Axis
 doesn't seem to have been affected by all the arguments about Mellow Chips
 demo. What they've done is to create a demo consisting of 3D scenes all
 the way through, more or less. And the result is magnificient! The demo is
 the story about the end of the world. The year is 10191 (so don't worry).
 The story starts in space - of course - when a spacecraft appears in a
 flash near the Earth. A lot of time we fly around this craft, so that we
 can enjoy the Star Wars-like textures. In between the group's name and
 credits are shown with some kind of blur routine, which make them quite
 unreadable, but it looks okay. The spacecraft suddenly power up an
 external power supply that causes three big artificial lightnings to
 dance outside the craft, just to be gathered and concentrated below it,
 where a ball shaped object appears, some kind of probe. Soon after this
 probe flies towards the Earth. All you untill now have seen has been 3D,
 except for the blur texts. Now it's time for some 2D, the title: It's
 actually a quite simple effect, but as simple it is, as cool it is. At
 first you see sand, but this sand is slowly blown away and reveals the
 title of the demo. Looks great, but a'060 is definately recommended, that
 goes for this effect, as well as for the rest of the Relic. The next
 part takes place at the surface of the Earth, where we're flying above a
 green slopy 3D-landscape. Out of the fog appears an old Inca temple, and
 you can now see that there's a bit of motion blur added to the scene.
 The moment after a new scene is on, and we're flying through the clouds,
 observing the probe that is getting nearer and nearer to the Earth, more
 precisely to the temple's location. Soon after it arrives, and while
 hoovering above the old Inca building a powerful beam of light is
 generated between the probe and the temple. Powerful enough to make some
 untill now invisible windows in the temple shine very bright. What happens
 next is - believe or not - the entire building breaks loose from the
 ground, chunks of soil is falling from it while it in full majesty leaves
 the earth. And now you discover that the temple is only the top of a big
 arch. Nerve Axis sure is heavily inspired by the story about the arch of
 Noah, this one is just more intergalactic! Again we break through the
 cloud cover, and as soon as it exits the Earth's atmosphere it takes of in
 a flash, similar to when the other craft arrived (just the other way...).
 "So", you might think, "isn't it the story about Judgement Day? Where's
 the destruction?". Here it comes: Suddenly a big black hole opens close to
 our dear planet, and explodes in a gigantic and very beautiful flash that
 sends a big heat wave out into space, and big fireballs towards Earth.
 And you are now about to see some of the greatest explosions ever made on
 a computer! The fireballs hit the surface of the planet, big lightflashes
 and heatwaves are seen. But even better is when you see how big cities
 filled with skyscrapers are made into dust when hit by the explosion. If
 you've watched films as Independence day and Terminator 2 you have a
 pretty good idea of what this looks like. Awesome! The big finally is
 when the planet Earth itself explodes, spreading glowing rocks in all
 directions. Simply amazing, I'm out of words...
 All left is the Arch that floats away with the light from the exploding
 Earth in the background.
 Now comes the big question: Is all this just an animation? The destruction
 of the cities sure could look like it, but then again Schlott has proven
 his great talent before.
 The music is performed very well, and adds an extra dimension to the
 already highly atmospheric demo. When you're slowly observing the
 spacecraft or the temple the music quietly floats with you, and when the
 action starts it develops into some well controlled techno. Another good
 thing about is the sustain and echo effects that makes it sound as if a
 lot more of channels than the Amiga's four standard channels are used,
 maybe there are? Also the many sound effects are perfectly timed,
 not least the explosions. And as mentioned before the textures are very
 nice, and also the single picture there is in the demo (by Wade) is well
 drawn.
 Now for another big question: Which one is the best, Relic or @{" Rise " link "Rise"}? The
 two demos have the one big similarity, the 3D scenes, while the contents
 are completely different. Personally I like Relic the best, but closely
 followed by @{" Rise " link "Rise"}. I guess Relic's story is best, while @{" Rise " link "Rise"} has the
 advantage of a bit better code (?) and more colorful textures (not to
 forget the babe :-)). Relic's soundtrack fits it great, the same can be
 said about Mellow Chips' demo, but the Relic sound is a bit more perfect,
 I guess. On the other hand you can use some of the music in @{" Rise " link "Rise"} as both
 demo and listening music. In the end it's a matter of taste, as always.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} One of the best demos in 1998!

  @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/RelicTitle.GIF"} The graphics is great, the code and music ditto!

@EndNode


@Node "ScrapsOfBeings" "Scraps of Beings / Mankind"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Scraps of Beings
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mankind

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Mekka/Symposium
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.14 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 or 8 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '040, enough RAM (if not it'll crash!)

@{B}Code:@{UB} Krabob
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Krabob, Grenat
@{B}Music:@{UB} Tex
@{B}Objects:@{UB} DDG, Seven/Ramses

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ****

+ Amazing transitions, very good code
- The music and choice of colors could be better

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is one of the most overlooked demos I know of!
 It really deserved the first place at Symposium, but when competing with
 well-known groups like Haujobb (that won the compo) and Abyss (that took
 the second place with their demo @{" Extra Life " link "ExtraLife"}) it can be difficult to
 convince the masses that this demo should win. But it didn't, it was
 ranked third despite it's great transitions and code. But there are also
 some things dragging it down, for example the music that does not seem to
 fit the demo too well, and is of a low quality compared to the demo's
 high standard at other points. It's a mostly drum'n'bass tune that is
 played a low speed, added with some interesting sounds here and there, but
 it's not enough... Also, the demo has some problems with the color choice.
 I don't know if the Mankind-members couldn't agree, but it looks as if
 everyone got what they wanted - in small amounts spread all over the demo!
 Generally it all looks quite nice, but even though the colors are dimmed
 to be more dark than many other demos (compared to for example many of The
 Black Lotus colorful demos) the mix of them is a little odd. But besides
 from these two points there's nothing negative to say about this great
 demo! Let's start from the beginning: A dark blue picture is smoothly
 zoomed towards you while the sound of something odd is heard, and I really
 mean smoothly because it's a bit blured which means that there's a very
 short tail after it. In front of this some text are faded and stretch,
 looks cool. After this little and atmospherical introduction the music
 starts for real and a fine plasma is presented on the screen. In most
 other demos that would be it, you'll watch this plasma and just wait for
 the next effect to follow, but Krabob does some magic things and succeeds
 in getting no less than two other routines on at the same time! Firstly an
 eye is moving around in the lower right corner of the screen, which means
 that the picture fades into the plasma, and secondly a pulsating skull is
 slowly zoomed towards you, motion blured and transparent! That's
 impressive! The secret to run all these routines may be colorcycling, but
 if so it's cleverly used. Looks good, no doubt about that! Afterwards the
 group's name is also zoomed and then we continue to the next routine,
 which is a amazing morph routine. I guess it's the same kind as used in
 one of Madonna's music videos. The idea is that you have a picture -
 Mankind uses photographs of (among other things) a monitor - and you take
 a part of this picture and morph it so that it fills the entire screen,
 then you take the new picture and do the same and so on and so forth.
 Looks great, and compared to the amount of graphic the computer has to
 move it's really fast (however, not as fast as Madonna's video...). Also
 the way the routine is used is great. The monitor on the picture is (of
 course) used to present a new routine. That routine is a new plasma with
 a transparent eye located in the middle of it, followed by another plasma
 with the shape of a flower and the colors of a lot of flowers! There seems
 to be no limit of how strange (and tasteless) the color choice is during
 this plasma! And "as usual" some other effects are presented in front of
 the plasma, this time a texture mapped hand and some lightballs. The
 transition to the next routine is amazing: The plasma is whirled away like
 ink in water. The routine is used elsewhere in the demo for quite a long
 time, so that you really get a chance to enjoy it in it's full pride.
 Looks great! Behind the plasma that has now disappeared is a zoom/rotator
 effect and a couple of lips, nice! After a while this routine is flushed
 away to the left just to reveal a nice and colorful bumpmap routine. The
 transitions are at this point quite simple, but very effective and
 entertaining! There is no smart transition to the next routine, though,
 which is a fade between two pictures and a moving background (as the
 pictures naturally are transparent). At this point the techno music is
 very slow and silent, but suddenly it starts moving, and so does the
 visuals: The morph routine is used once again, and greetings are shown in
 front of it. Then a slow flash is seen, actually it shows up to be a
 spotlight that is blinding you. And when a spotlight is present, why not
 use? A Mankind logo moves from the top to the bottom of the screen in
 front of the light with a colorful torus (sigh...) right after. You see
 the arms of light from the spotlight where there's no letters or torus to
 stop it. Beautiful! And what is a demo without a 3D-scene? The one in this
 demo is first of all quite nice, and colored lightballs fly around in it.
 The camera doesn't move from its location, but slowly turns around so that
 you can enjoy the scenery. The end of the demo is getting close, but
 before it's all over Mankind demonstrates their lack of color design once
 again. They use an eye for the purpose that is placed in the middle of
 colored beams of light. A nice routine, but those colors are not exactly
 helping it to be perfect! We almost end where we started with a zoom
 routine. A blue circular shape is zoomed back and forth while credits are
 shown in the bottom of the screen.
 In my opinion this is one of the best things that has happened to the
 Scene in 1998. Much of the code seems to be inspired by @{" Art by Coincidence " link "ArtByCoincidence"}
 by Spaceballs, but this demo has so much more to offer than ABC, even
 though ABC is still a good demo. I'm really looking forward to see
 Mankind's coming demos, if they just adjust those colors it could be a
 real killer!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} One of the best demos in 1998!

@EndNode


@Node "PhaseOne" "Phase One / Capsule"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Phase One
@{B}Group:@{UB} Capsule

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Abduction
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 8

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.14 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020>, 8 MB RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060/50MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Peskanov, Dr. Slump, Oops!, Keved
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Humphrey/Centolo!, Cyclone/Abyss, Danny/Ex-TBL
          Leunam/Network, Dvize/Limited Edition, Made/Bomb
@{B}Music:@{UB} Estrayk, Evelred
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Oops!, Peskanov, Alvin/TLOTB

+ Lots of different routines, nice pictures
- The design disappears quickly

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

@{B}Comment:@{UB}
 A couple of years ago Capsule was for most people either an unknown group
 or a group who's production was of more or less low quality (the first was
 mostly the case). However, last year at the Euskal party in Spain they
 managed to conquer the second place in the demo compo with Trailway, a
 demo that, without being highly innovative or in other ways superior, was
 worth having a look at. And with this new demo Capsule has moved a step up
 on the latter of fame.
 Most of the routines have been seen before, we know the pictures shown,
 and the music is the kind of industrial mix of different electronic genres
 that you forget as soon as the demo is over and you return to reality, not
 that it is bad, it isn't, it fits the demo very well. But two things make
 the difference: 1) The design, and 2) The amount of everything! Let's
 start with the first topic, the design: Capsule has worked very carefully
 with the design - in the beginning of the demo (as seen several times
 before in various other demos - of course caused by those always early
 deadlines!). It's in short terms a very nice demo start. The background is
 black when lines are drawn here and there which results in the outlines of
 what is to be on screen shortly after, the group's name in the bottom of
 the screen and a nice lady placed to the right. The rest of the screen is
 used for hard to read text, as it is flipped 90°. Everything seems to be
 worked through, and also the change to the first routine is well figured
 out. The screen simply scrolls just to reveal another beatiful lady, now
 to the left, and different texture mapped 3D object entering and exiting
 the screen from the right in a great hurry. This part is wrapped into a
 very modern and fancy design, but it doesn't last long before it all turns
 into a more traditional look. A shame, but trust me: Despite of that
 you're not bored watching this show, which leads me to the second point of
 the demo's charistica, the amount of contents. Only few demos contain that
 much of everything! Especially the number of routines and pictures are
 amazing, and if you look at the credit list you see why. Four coders and
 five graphicians is not normal for a demo, and Capsule seems to have had
 some difficulties making it all fit in the same production, but has done
 it anyway, which I believe is the main reason for the "variated design".
 Also worth noticing is that non of the graphicians is member of Capsule...
 The pictures are almost all of high quality, and a many of them has been
 seen before at different occasions, among other Cyclone's MS'97 winner
 picture. After the good beginning sequence the style changes a bit, and
 different blured wireframe objects are shown, beginning with a torus (will
 they never learn...?). Afterwards the style changes completely as a
 zoomrotator hidden behind what looks like a bumpy window appears. Looks
 nice, but with all it's colors it simply doesn't match with the start's
 bright "clean" colors. I won't say that these changes are fatal, but you
 can't help taking notice of them. One of Cyclone's creations are on next,
 followed by a fast free flight tunnel routine, unfortunately with a quite
 ugly texture as tunnel walls. Rapidly another picture appears. This one is
 on for quite a long time. The zoomrotator with its bumpy window is back,
 this time with some quite unreadable text bumped into the glas. This is
 followed by yet another picture (by Danny), and many more will follow here
 and there later in the demo, so I'll stop writing everytime that happens
 (would almost be easier if I wrote when it didn't happen :-)). Well,
 afterwards we have two routines in a row (that means with no pictures in
 between), the first being a shadecluster build from small dots, and with a
 background that looks like a monitor with a music program running (not
 Protracker). Looks okay, even though Peskanov and Slump aren't too happy
 about it themselves they say in the readme-file that covers a range of the
 routines in the demo (tech-stuff for the interested ones). The other one
 is inside a texture mapped torus, with transparent lines of data scrolling
 across the screen. Not super original, but nice. Now there's a fairly long
 brake (while watching a picture...), and afterwards some lightballs with
 metaball tendencies appear. More interesting is the zoom rotator that is
 shown a moment later, followed by another one, both of them are very fast
 and enjoyable. At this point in the demo many seen-before effects have
 been presented, but the next one is something completely new, and it even
 looks as if it's a digitized camera recording. But Peskanov claims that it
 actually is coded. So who should you believe? Watching this sequence, that
 looks like sand being poured, you will most likely be convinced that it
 isn't code. The display is special, and uses only every second line I
 guess, but the speed is good. I wouldn't say that it is pretty, but sure
 it is innovative! Coming up next is a more traditional kind of 3D, simply
 a more or less simple 3D scene presenting a landscape with roads and other
 Earthly objects. It's all texture mapped, but is nothing special. The
 engine is okay though, and the way the greetings are build into this scene
 is good: We dive into a hole in the ground and discover a missile with the
 greetings written all over it, funny idea. Another kind of 3D is presented
 to us next. It's two balls, gouraud shaded I suppose. They have an extra
 feature, they are transparent. A part I really like is the endscroller.
 The special thing about it is that a lot of small, simple 3D vector
 objects slowly float from the bottom to the top of the screen, while the
 scroller itself is in the background. A good alternative to the usual
 endscrollers.
 I would recommend this demo, even though it sure isn't a killer. But still
 it has some qualities, and not least the amount of it all makes it
 interesting. The way pictures are put in here and there, quite often, does
 not help the design, as they seem to be picked after how welldrawn they
 are, not after if they would fit into the demo. But then again they really
 are nice. I guess I've seen Capsule make better demo parts, but as an
 overall this is their far best demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} So much stuff in one demo! Recommended!


DareDevil's review:

+ Many interesting effects, a real slideshow of pics, excellent tunes
- Little coherence between parts that produce a dispersive design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Spectacular demo this one, with many interesting ideas and full
 of very good pictures from great guest graphicians. This good production
 reminded me of the good "old skool" feeling, and this is both good and
 bad. Good because it means that the effects are presented in the right
 order, pepped up by a lot by all the pictures that avoids the hated
 cut-passage between two effects. It's bad because this means that the
 effects haven't a real coherence and this results in a dispersive design
 that is in my opinion the only big drawback of this demo.
 The first impact with the demo is excellent: In a high-res interlaced
 screen some lines traces the edges of the graphics that appears when the
 lines ends. Suddenly some text rotated to 90° anti-clockwise appears
 composing a message, then the whole screen scrolls to left to introduce a
 new picture and many 3D textured objects with various polygonal shapes
 that enter and exit alternating fast. In the next effect some other
 wireframe objects (distorted cubes, stars and cog-wheels) appears tracing
 a motion blured trail. And a bump mapped logo with background texture,
 rotozooming, is on afterwards, followed by a fast tunnel with textures
 lightsourced in planar mode. A new bump mapped message and a picture of
 Claudia Schiffer introduces an interesting cluster shade growing in a
 wireframe cube, but the most interesting part about this effect is
 actually the background, a screen grab of Protracker which has been
 manipulated in a graphics program. The following voyage into a texture
 mapped torus, while many lines of transparent assembly codes scrolls fast
 across the screen at the same time, seems to be a bit too slow on my '040
 (But it runs quite good on my '030/40MHz!? - DRD) However, the second part
 of the demo is more interesting, introducing a hypersphere with metaball
 in each vertex that seems simply to be a group of metabobs in position to
 compose a dot ball with a core that moves to morph the ball. The coders
 say in the readme-file that it's a projection of a 4D sphere rotating on
 its axis. Anyhow, it's a very good effect, so is the following rotozoomer
 in full 1x1 pixel resolution with an extremely high dot precision. A bit
 more chaotic, but also choreographic is the zoom of rotating textures with
 a relative "waste'o'meter" that is a meter of waste of CPU time while
 running this strange and weird effect. This one seems to be intended as a
 joke and not a useful effect, if you read the readme text, but in my
 opinion it's not so bad! There are no doubt that the sand effect
 following afterwards is simply a great piece of code, especially because
 it  seems to be a real animation! But the coders say that it is in
 realtime and offers a lolly-pop to anyone who can guess the effect that
 generates it. Well, I have lost that lolly-pop! :-( The next 3D scene is
 great: It's night and a metallic dome is in the center of a group of
 streets. The dome opens and the camera enters to discover a rocket! And
 the rocket is covered with names of some of the most important Amiga scene
 groups. It's very easy to understand the hidden meaning of this scene that
 really doesn't seems to be the greetings part, also because the full
 greetings list is presented in the final scrolltext! The music of this
 part is very good and enphasizes the "rocket ready to launch" sensation
 well. On next is two simple big transparent 3D balls rotating on their
 axis, and that is the last effect before the final scrolltext. This one is
 simply impressive: In high-res interlaced screenmode many and various
 sized classic 3D textured objects such as cubes, pyramids, spheres and
 toruses flies up from the bottom to the top of the screen, space cutted,
 while the text scrolls. They say that this entire effect is made in only
 three bitplanes. That's incredible!
 All these goods, nearly all in 1x1 pixel resolution, are supported very
 well from the energetic techno modules. Especially the drum session after
 the rocket scene, I like it! And also, if objects are very common, their
 use is more choreographic than functional to the effects and the excellent
 3D scene raise the final judgement.
 The (pre)-conclusion is that it's a good demo with some small design
 problems, like many others. I hope it's a prelude to a fantastic following
 production.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Spanish scene is showing its very sharp claws!

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne01.jpg"} The design in this part is good, but it doesn't last
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne02.jpg"} Nice looking blured wireframe figures
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne03.jpg"} Shadeclusters in a box with an original background
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne04.jpg"} We are about to zoom into a tunnel - excellent transition
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne05.jpg"} One of the title pictures!
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne06.jpg"} Small lightballs form different objects
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne07.jpg"} A very special and weird effect, looks like sand
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne08.jpg"} The 3D scene is nothing special
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne09.jpg"} Cyclone demonstrates (once again) is talent for drawing
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/PhaseOne10.jpg"} The endscroller is cute

@EndNode


@Node "Reflexity" "Reflexity / Sector 7"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Reflexity
@{B}Group:@{UB} Sector 7

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Belgian Scene Event
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 2

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.2 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more

@{B}Code:@{UB} NoName
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} JCS
@{B}Music:@{UB} CDK

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Pretty nice routines, good graphics
- Standard music, short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A little thing from the Sector 7 crew that definately won't
 be written into the great book of Scene History, but then again, it was
 made in a couple of days just before the BSE. The routines in it are quite
 good, most of the pictures too (even though the intro- and title picture
 suffer from being converted from hi-color to less colors), while the music
 is quite average, but timed well to the show. It's techno by the way.
 It all begins with some title screens presenting the demo's name and the
 group in reversed order. Texture plasma is on next, a bunch of plasmas,
 actually, shown after each other. There's also two variations that
 combines two screens by using every second line for one plasma, and the
 other lines for another plasma, looks quite good. However, I think the
 effect is best on a screen that is a little blured (like a bigscreen or an
 old TV). The most interesting in the demo is by far a scene where we see a
 tree with leaves and branches (it is a tree you know...) very close to the
 "camera" and with a spotlight (or maybe the sun) behind it. The tree
 slowly spins around, sometimes covering the lightsource, now and then
 letting in the light that leaves you blinded. The resolution is quite low
 (again a bigscreen would be a good idea), but even worse I believe it to
 be an animation? See it and make your own decisions about it! More plasma
 and a great picture is shown near the end of the short demo that ends with
 a very "interesting" plasma with some primitive drawings of a cow and the
 letters BSE... Cute.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Quite okay, but short.

@EndNode


@Node "Automatic" "Automatic / Nature"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Automatic
@{B}Group:@{UB} Nature

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Remedy
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.26 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or faster procesor

@{B}Code:@{UB} Yomat, Pezac
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Rex, Pipe, Pezac, Cybrid/Edv
@{B}Music:@{UB} C-Frog
@{B}Design:@{UB} Yomat, Pezac

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Fast 3D routines and HAM8
- Some minor lacks in design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I like this demo very much. Finally someone tries to code
 something a bit different and the alpha channel effect used on the title
 logo is different! But also the other effects are so colourful that I
 suspect a large use of routines in HAM8. And this is very impressive.
 Also the credits part is very impressive with a 3D phong ball morphing
 into a multi-pointed star, with motion blur, all in 1x1 pixel resolution.
 Then another experiment: A cartoon styled 2D picture with bump mapping
 made with at least three different moving coloured lights, so that when
 the lights intersects each other a kind of colour sum reflex is formed on
 the enlighted bumped section. Original if compared with classic 2D bump
 mapping effects, but in 2x2 and probably in HAM8 (I'm not sure about
 that!). Afterwards three 2D punched rotators appear on screen deforming
 a colourful texture in 1x1, then a kind of 3D gyroscopical rings is on (is
 that a cover to show some torus?! well, good trick! :) ) rotates to show
 that in the middle there's a strange object with the form like a bunch of
 crystals. This scene is pretty fast considering the dimensions of the
 rings and that they are all texture mapped, phonged and in 1x1 pixel
 resolution. Here ends the first part.
 The second part of the demo is introduced by a picture used to show the
 most interesting effect of the demo: In full transparency to the previous
 picture a 2D punched rotator in 2x2 moves around, to introduce three
 alpha channel planes of the same rotator also in 2x2 using a wonderful
 palette of colors, for sure in HAM8. Then a motion blured starfield dances
 around, introduce another colourful effect. This time it's an enlighted
 tunnel voyage that ends in an ambient 3D-scene with a strange daisy with
 petals flying around. Also two columns, very ugly textured, are present,
 all in 1x1. Finally, on the last picture shown the classic end scrolltext
 starts.
 This demo shows a very high level of coding, but also a not too exciting
 graphics concerning the 3D objects' textures. Instead the colourful
 punched 2D rotators makes the difference! The final scrolltext says that
 the music is a bit boring: Yes, it is! But it's also functional to
 introduce the effect changes, when the transitions between the effects
 aren't running too smooth. This means that the design could have been
 better. Who's perfect?

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} The way to perfection is long... but this is a very good
 start for Nature!

                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "dELTA" "dELTA / Embassy"

@{B}Name:@{UB} dELTA
@{B}Group:@{UB} Embassy

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 6

@{B}Size:@{UB} 8.62 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, FPU, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060, Cybergraphics

@{B}Code:@{UB} Sly, Humanoid
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Oakgrove, Humanoid, Neure
@{B}Music:@{UB} Temen, Basscadet

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Some good ideas, some original objects and very good 3D
- The color choice is not good, it's too slow

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Embassy's guys makes me hungry! They are very, very talented,
 maybe they are capable to produce the greatest things ever! AND they
 release another demo that eat a lot of processor time (that means that
 it's slow if you haven't got at least an '060) and without other purpose
 than to show the power of their 3D engine. Why?! It's possible that no one
 in their group is capable to come up with a concrete idea to develop a
 demo around? Is it so difficult? I guess that there were no competition
 against a "monster" like @{" Relic " link "Relic"}, but the good 3D engine, if used for
 better purpose, could be the right rival against that monster!
 I can't believe that design is not so good ONLY because the demo was
 developed in one week, as Embassy's guys says at end. If so, I will be
 very happy to see their next production with the right design. But this
 one is another lost chance. Of course this production could be proud of
 the good code with great effects (especially tranparency and raycasting),
 but it's too slow and sometimes I've noticed problems with the texture
 perspective correction in a couple of scenes. Also, graphics and music
 are all of high quality. I must say that they tried to estabilish a kind
 of graphics style that I could define "industrial", using very pale colors
 and with tones like rust and dirty metal, as a logical link to the
 different 3D scenes, but it's not enough to call it "design".
 The first things shown is a group of dark cubes, and on their sides there
 are the letters to spell the name Embassy. Then this changes to a good
 transparency effect that introduces a 3D space scene in which the Earth is
 covered by a transparent atmosphere and the moon sometimes comes out on
 its way around the Earth, and meanwhile credits are shown with a distorted
 fade effect that is very interesting. Afterwards a raycasting, scrolling
 message says: "Can you see the images of our mind?". At the end of this
 message we enter a 3D-scene with a very tall column that has a four star
 pointed base on top with a transparent glass dome that reflects light. Out
 of it burns a strange fire, while a spotlight fly around this structure.
 Then a very interesting effect is on: The camera moves around a strange 3D
 object distorting a texture as if it's wrapping a rubber plain on its
 surfaces. This effect introduce a very good 3D Scene: A hangar with a
 monolith with three transparent cog-wheels rotating on it. There are also
 a clock and a monitor on the top of a portal. The screen of the monitor
 shows a recursive camera view. Next effect is composed of multilayers of a
 scrolling and rotating technical mess, while some distorted texts add
 more confusion to it. We enter a machine shop where a big light creates
 shadows over some pipes, while the camera is moving. The greetings-part
 with manes of greeted groups follows moving over a kind of plasma made
 with some moving colorful layers. This is the worst effect in the demo. I
 think that a good old copper plasma would have been much better! So the
 last 3D-scene is on. In a new room there's a very strange metallic
 structure covering a drinking fountain, very fine. At end some pictures
 describes the effects seen and shows the final credits and some messages.
 An idea that differs from the classic final scrolltext.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A demo for fast processor, with an "industrial" cold soul.

                                                        DareDevil

@{B}Comment:@{UB}
 Seemingly from nowhere they came back in a real comeback of seldomly
 witnessed dimensions. After their first placed 'Bangcock' form the
 Motorola Inside in June, they spit out 'dELTA' at the Assembly hitting the
 second place. More than reason to honour (well) them with a wellminded
 review. To be honest, even if I was not wellminded towards I would have
 found little to argue about. First of all: The demo supports CyberGFX as
 indicated by the screen that gets opened in 8bit 320 X 240. Unfortunately 
 I was not able to run it properly as the screencontents were messed up.
 Still, I wouldn't call it a mistake within the demo. Something which isn't
 so nice, however, is the fact that it seemingly doesn't run under
 68030/50; about 68040/25 or 68040/40 we were ot able to get any
 information. The demo itself starts with an Embassy logo, which turns out
 to be printed on vectorcubes (well, at least on walls placed in zigzag) as
 when the camera moves around the objects, the letters of the logo get more
 and more replaced by the word "presents" painted in the same style. As the
 camera continous its turn around the otherwise black screen, the letters
 get laid transparently over eachothers until they start to move fastly
 towards the viewer and disappear. Then a Photoshop-fullscreen saying
 "dELTA" in greek letters on colorful bump background. The next effect,
 however, already breaks the norm. What they call to be made of "three
 primitive objects" is indeed the most impressive starfield I have ever
 seen and who has Graham's excellent universe from @{" Exit Planet Dust " link "ExitPlanetDust"}
 still in mind knows that this is something really special. Then a
 raycaster illuminated from behind. To be exact it is a scrolltext with
 some introductory words being enlightened from its backside so that only
 through the shapes that the letters throw the text is to be read. Then a
 complex 3D cavern with light effects, particle fire on a pillaresque
 podest. Looks great, is Lightwave. The following effect is known to the PC
 for long, but I have never met it on Amiga so far: We see two objects, one
 in the front being some kind of latice, the second one in the back a usual
 undefinable phong or so. The later tries to squeeze itself through the
 latice so that this one gets deformed in the manner the phong moves. On
 top of this all an independent lightsource. That's what I call complex.
 Then we get confronted with yet another Lightwave scene with transparent
 cowheels in motion being fixed on a vertical standing marmorised plate.
 The scene reminds of a hangar and includes a mirror effect. A door on the
 backside of the hangar opens and we find the next effect. This is an
 interference fullscreen with flickering text, just look at it and you know
 what I mean. Not so important. Following is something which is highly
 fashionable these days a multilayered effect of two "blueprints" both
 (zoom-)rotating independently from each others white on black. This
 sequence includes blurred texts, schematics, rotatings, filtering,
 distorsion and text-cumulating. The next 3D-scene comes in realtime as
 indicated by the lower resolution, but it really is an eyecatcher. A
 surreal undergroundworld filled with pipes in counterlight. Needless to
 say that the objects also cast shadows. Then the obligatory greetings part
 which comes as somekind of plasmablur with text laying over it. A final
 3D-scene before the static endtext and description of the effects. A
 machine hall with a fountain in the middle including perspective
 dissonance and the two needed lightsources. This dark and gloomy release
 which is said to be made in just one week (hard to believe) comes with a
 fitting soundtrack that does underlay the show without playing it to the
 wall and features adequate graphics and astonishing abilities. Indeed it
 does not provide anything new, but might give a hint on how to optimise
 ideas. Technically seen it is the winner of the Assembly despite the
 surely brilliant Lightwave converter of the Nerve Axis crew - which plays
 the one from Embassy to the wall. on the other hand when realising the
 perfection of the display of the winning demo compared to the sometimes
 half-hearted presentation of "dELTA", it is not a real wonder that
 @{" Rise " link "Rise"} won so clearly. Here it gets obvious: The trend is appearance,
 not importance. If this is a healthy trend or not - well, let's wait and
 see. So far I can only say that @{" Rise " link "Rise"} is the demo that I show to
 non-Sceners, "dELTA" is the one I show to people who know what Scening
 originally meant.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A demo with many good qualities, but it still needs the final
 touch that makes the real difference.
                                                        RockDaZone/Endzeit

@EndNode


@Node "JesusWasADemomaker" "Jesus was a Demomaker / Ramses"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Jesus was a Demomaker
@{B}Group:@{UB} Ramses

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Euskal 6
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.39 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040 or better processor

@{B}Code:@{UB} Krabob, DDG
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Zaac, Lord, Kelson
@{B}Music:@{UB} Traven, Next
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Krabob

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Good code, refined design
- A picture is incomplete.

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Impressive title for a demo, this one! And the demo itself is
 very good too! These guys show to the entire Scene that design is one of
 the most important things for demos. They are using music changes only
 when needed (and without abusing it!), while the transitions to the next
 effects are represented mostly by a simple but cool 2D twirling
 plasma-like distortion, a flash or a zooming screenshot.  Something that
 is seen all the way through the demo is texts shown using an incredible
 effect of lines moving like in Tron game clones (maybe better know as
 worms, and that is not the Worms game from Team 17), and themes of
 church-wares and christian iconografy. If this isn't design, then what is
 design?!
 The demo begins with the twirl distortion that presents a Ramses logo. A
 couple of meta-like distortion plasma rings appear on the logo, when they
 get close enough to each other they grow together, shortly after they
 split up. After a twirl distortion and a fade a 3D-scene appears, inside
 a church. The camera moves around showing us some wonderful stained
 windows, while credits are shown and the "Tron-lines" is moving around
 here and there. Another fade, and a Jesus picture zooms towards you with
 a bit of motion blur, and the "Tron-lines" composes the title of the demo!
 Great effect! After that the title and the picture are zoomed out, a new
 3D-scene appears. It's a room with a cubic altar surrounded by columns.
 A bump mapped and texture mapped chalice is flying around. A kind of "I'm
 very drunk"-effect is added to this scene, looks really cool (including
 motion blur and tranparent plasma distortion)! Other objects are later
 present (a cube, a cross, a pentagonal ring and a chalice cover with a
 little cross on the top). This scene zooms out and here ends the first
 part of the demo.
 The music changes and the second part is introduced by a picture
 (incomplete they says) of a woman with Jesus' heart on her hands. This
 is a classic catholic picture, but with the Jesus face! Well, the picture
 is called "Virgin" (in the readme-text) so I don't think that there were
 blasphemic intentions, but it's a too strong image for my taste. Then the
 greetings-part is on. Another 3D-scene: A cave with a little mountain in
 it on which there are three crosses (like on Mt. Calvary) and a group
 of spotlights are moving in the direction of another cross build from
 rotating cubes with names of greeted groups on their sides. Another twirl
 distortion introduces a picture presenting the guy called Jesus laying
 down beneath a cross, while a little bump mapped Ramses logo appears
 on itand a lightsource is moving around above it. Another fade shows the
 "Mt. Calvary cave" distorted in "sinus mode". Then the altair scene
 appears again but this time seen through a "fisheye" lens, while the
 "Tron-lines" draws some casual symmetric lines on the screen. New
 distortion and the last effect comes up. A 3D-scene of a simple texture
 mapped room in which three gouraud shaded objects, a cross and two
 morphing stones, are flying and rotating. A scrolltext ends this demo.
 This production can be very proud of a good code, great graphics and
 great tunes in classic demo style. All effects are in 1x1 pixel resolution
 and are quite fast and smooth, but a fast '040 is recommended. They says
 in the readme-file that design isn't as good as they wanted it to be
 because of the deadline at the party. Well, I cannot help asking how it
 would have been, if they've had more time.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} One of the coolest production available! A real
 "must have"!

                                                        DareDevil

@{B}Veto:@{UB} This is a historical moment (20:18, 7/10-'98...), the moment
 the first veto ever in The Demo.Guide is interposed. And it almost agrees
 with DareDevil...
 Jesus was a Demomaker is a good demo, but... Even though the routines are
 quite fast you still need quite a lot of CPU power due to the 1x1
 resolution. The colors in the 3D-scenes are partly well chosen, but what I
 dislike is the chunky textures, some of them looks as if they were made
 from big blocks. This could have been avoided by choosing a more smooth
 palette I guess. And finally, even though the transitions are good it's
 almost the same transition used all the time, again and again. A little
 more variation here would have been prefered. But it is a very good demo!

                                                        Dreyer

@EndNode


@Node "NoSex" "No Sex! / Zenon"

@{B}Name:@{UB} No Sex!
@{B}Group:@{UB} Zenon

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Abduction
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 8

@{B}Size:@{UB} 4.30 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, FPU (?), HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor
@{B}Note:@{UB} Will not run on Dreyer's computer, not even with a clean boot!

@{B}Code:@{UB} Tissi (?)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Oma (?)
@{B}Music:@{UB} Rasva (?)

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Interesting experiments and fast effects
- Minimal graphics, lacks design, it's too short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} At first a little preface: I can't give a clear judgement to this
 demo, because the Zenon guys show some words in Finnish in some parts and
 I'm not sure about their function. Well, Finnish isn't my strongest side!
 So I'm judging this demo mainly from a technical point of view, and the
 judgement about design is made WITHOUT taking care of the words.
 This demo is very good coded, runs in 2x2 pixel resolution, but hasn't
 many effects in it. Zenon seems to solve this problem making it rather
 short. But a sudden end is not a solution, but a signal of an impending
 deadline! However, a demo that starts with a water distortion of three
 pictures (the credits?) and continues by adding a transparancy effect
 including two 2D raylight distortions to a water effect isn't something to
 forget easily! The following bunch of transparent and colored balls
 moving like a starfield and with motion blur is also valuable, especially
 when two 3D phong objects shaped as hearts also appear on the screen.
 Furthermore a picture is shown, zooming, when a bumpmap routine is on
 afterwards. Then there's the return of the transparent starfield of balls
 around a multi-pointed 3D phong star, and all this appear in a tunnel, and
 all with motion blur. Suddenly a bouncing breast (an animation or a 3D
 shaded object?) shows the title of the demo. That's all.
 Well, I can't avoid to notice that except for a repeatation of the same
 effect (the bunch of coloured balls) and the zoom of the picture showed
 previously, there aren't too many opportunities to catch a glimpse of
 design, except maybe for those text brushes shown during the demo (if only
 I could understand what they mean!). Also, the music is not the best
 techno tune ever heard. Only the good code and a bit of graphic save this
 demo from a worse judgement.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Good prefaces, but not the results that could be expected
 compared to the quality of the effects.

                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "Pusherman" "Pusherman / Tulou"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Pusherman
@{B}Group:@{UB} Tulou

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Remedy
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 4!

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.77 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040/40Mhz, Cybervision

@{B}Code:@{UB} Dr. Strangelove, Todi
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Joker
@{B}Music:@{UB} Fossil

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ A strange design with '70 years feel, Cybervision supported
- 3D routines could be improved, the design, slow routines mostly

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I don't like psychedelic things and things related to the
 '70s, but I do like Bruce Lee movies, and this demo is inspired by both.
 This basic idea is very good as for example Melon. has demonstrated more
 than once, but Tulou's guys are not Melon.! So it seems as if during
 the development some of the original ideas was lost.
 The opening title screenshot, and especially the music with some cool
 guitar samples, re-creates the full feeling of Bruce Lee's movies. But
 when the first effect appears - you're flying amid some 3D textured
 rectangular columns that seems without end in 2x2 pixel resolution - the
 music changes... into jungle?! Hey! Where is that '70s feeling? It's lost,
 because the next effect is a texture mapped sky plasma-like thing,
 distorted, and a deformed voxelscape as seen through a fisheye lens. All
 these effects are in 2x2 pixel resolution seem to be a bit too slow on my
 '040. Then comes the most important effect: a 3D voyage into the holes of
 four pierced layers with bump mapped texture on them. Very slow indeed,
 but in 1x1 pixel resolution (looks great! - DRD).
 Finally, someone remembered the original idea, and, after a picture
 presenting a face that is shown for too long time, a simple animation
 consisting of very few frames, shows a karate guy moving. But at this
 point it's too late to recover that initial feeling. The final scrolltext
 with another jungle music ends the demo.
 It isn't as good as it could be, if just Tulou had put a bit more work and
 time into it. But what puzzles me much more is how a demo with a so great
 lack of design has reached the first place?! Well, this is not the first
 episode of mis-judged demos, and it will not be the last.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a demo worthy of a first place, something was lost on
 the way for sure!
                                                        DareDevil


@{B}Comment:@{UB} 
 Quite an uncommmon sight to see Tulou winning a party. Uncommon as they -
 despite being quite active in the past - rather concentrated on
 fun-design (if I may put it that way) rather than on hitting style
 features. Well, may the Remedy in Solnahallen/Stockholm from the 11th to
 14th June 1998 have been a start into something new for the group. In the
 end they managed to leave prominent groups like Nature and Mystic behind
 themselves which really gives one more good reason to have a close look on
 this "Pusherman" which indeed pushed its way to the top. Now what do we
 have here? After quite a long time of decrunching, some strange graphics
 pops up on the screen. On a light background black outlines of karate
 images enriched by some color dots announce what we are about to see,
 followed by the credits, which come up the same way, just that the names
 shake hectically. All of this alone takes around 30 seconds, which appears
 too timeconsuming on the second look, but due the quite uncommon design
 rises interest while the first viewing. The first "real" effect gives
 quite an impressive sight. We pass a field of huge shaded and textured
 bars and while our fly down their endless length, we cruise around one
 after another. From time to time the screen flashes hectically timed to
 the soundtrack by Fossil. This one looks definately smashing, although
 somehow - with an eye of the 3MB the whole demo swallows in length - I can
 not deny the feeling that this is not made in realtime. Yet this is just
 an unverifiable impact. The next effect is somekind of interference twirl
 running on a sky-like texture. As with this definition no one can actually
 make a picture of what I mean, something more descriptive: Imagine a
 common tunnel, but make it infinitivly deep so that you don't see a real
 middle apart from a darker point. Then widen the tunnel to such an extreme
 that actually the walls don't appear anymore tube-like but rather like a
 bended flat surface. On all of this you place a texture that indeed looks
 like a twisted sky and then you just rotate over that tunnel into all
 directions. This  effects runs like the first on in a resolution of 2x2.
 If Modem/Darkage knows a better definition, he is invited to tell anyone I
 should stop doing reviews. (* Oops, pardon! *) Next up is a voxelspace
 featuring a textured sky which strongly reminds of the formerly described
 one. Maybe identical? Doesn't matter. The voxel indeed gives quite a speed
 on 68060/50 and although there is nothing specifically new to it, the
 movements and perspectives are quite interesting. Especially bouncing from
 the top directly onto the surface has something interesting. Then the
 indesputed highlight of the demo: A sequence of textured surfaces layered
 one behind another is shown with elliptical gaps which enable a look on
 the floors beneath. The viewer flies to and fro the different levels which
 are not bumpmapped although the textures on the first look evoke the
 feeling that they are. A surely nice one here in 1x1 resolution. Basically
 that is it for the demo. Every now and then some screens with karate
 images and anims pop up and enlarge the demo. One way to hide away the low
 number of "real" effects. In the end follows a vertical endscroller and
 that's it. The soundtrack basically is an oldstyle Jungle-breakbeat
 adventure which fits the demo perfectly as it changes attitude with the
 style of the effects. Technically not very demanding it increases the
 enjoyability of the demo quite significantly. "Pusherman" features a dense
 design and surely scores mainly by its visual and audio input. Something I
 would rather call a design demo, especially as it works best on the first
 while the second placed demo by Nature convinces more on the long run for
 the effects, less for the design. In the end the demo with the better
 first impact wins and regarded from this angle, Tulou deserved their first
 place. Strange only that "Pusherman" is supposed to support the
 Cybergrafics library. Maybe it does but the advance it takes from it
 remains in the dark as wether one runs it under Cybergfx or plain AGA
 makes no difference - at least on my hardware.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A quite enjoyable demo!
                                                        RokDaZone/Endzeit


@{B}Inside information:@{UB} The attached file "Tlu-Pusherman.dat" is a classic
 Pong game (but it tends to hang when you try to exit... :( - DRD).

@EndNode


@Node "Terminal" "Terminal / The Experience"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Terminal
@{B}Group:@{UB} The Experience

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Remedy
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.11 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor, 16 MB fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Axon
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Traksion, Mesh
@{B}Music:@{UB} Epsilon, Traksion
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Axon, Mesh
@{B}Design:@{UB} Epsilon

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Well coded, good raytraced animation
- Too common objects, average design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Despite the name of the group, this demo shows the "classic"
 lacks of experience that makes it suffer of "wannabe syndrome". This
 doesn't mean that it's a bad demo, only that there isn't any coherence
 between the effects and the music doesn't help at all. In few words:
 Lack of design! What a pity, because the code is good, and also the
 graphics and the music is okay. And also, there are a couple of good
 ideas. But this demo is a demo with many effects put in the wrong
 order. Let's start with an animation of a little logo that introduces a
 red tunnel. Out of it comes the title picture on a 3D layer. Next up is a
 very interesting credits part with bump mapped names of the authors. The
 names is divided in the middle by a green monochrome terminal screen while
 some lines of assembly code scrolls over it when the coder name appears,
 a hex-print of an iff file when the graphicians' names appear and a
 Protracker pattern for the musician's name. The first effect after the
 credits is an object, texture mapped like an old monitor (Commodore 1084)
 that flies while it shows some frames of a little raytraced animation (a
 starship in a gallery). The monitor flies away and a new effect appears.
 Some gouraud shaded classic objects (a torus and various kind of
 multi-pointed stars) rotates on their axis, alternating at the music's
 drum hits. When the drums end the last object, which is a multi-pointed
 star, morphs into a polygonal ball. This effect is in 2x2 pixel
 resolution. Then a rapid sequence of messages (of which I haven't
 understood the meaning!) appear on the screen and a texture mapped tunnel
 with many E-letters on. Now a rotating texture mapped cube comes out and
 a moving fore sight points at it. Next effect is a wallwrap covered with
 a sky texture (with clouds) moving together with a rectangular framed
 green glass 3D object with textures on its sides. Then a classic effect of
 bumpy 2D glass and a picture that introduce the greetings section appear.
 The greetings consists of four monitors rotating around a green phong
 object, in 1x1. Each screen shows some names of greeted groups. Afterwards
 a full raytraced animation of a spaceship flying above a railway in a
 tunnel, but this time in 2x2 pixel resolution. The next effect is a joke:
 Some messages present the first triangular texture mapped object, with
 gouraud shading, phong, anti-aliasing, mip-mapping, etc., but it shows to
 be a common wireframed cube... Shortly after another message says: "Ok, we
 lied!"... Another effect is a phong star object moving on a "exp" logo.
 Then a gouraud landscape and five conic objects is on begin  rotation on
 the screen, which is followed by a very impressive effect. Some wireframe
 objects of a DNA chains, a ball, a torus and an unidentifyable object
 moving alternately on screen, and the junction points are enlighted like
 spots, so when they moves on the Z-coordinate the lights sum their
 intensity in a shade bob effect. Very well coded. The last effect is a 3D
 object of an "exp" logo rotating while the names of the authors appear,
 transparent. Then the final... no! there isn't the final scroll text, but
 a sequence of fading texts while a piece of multi-channel music (the best
 of this production) plays in the background.
 It's evident how a great bunch of effect like this needs of a good link
 to be valuable, but this link is missing (so that is the missing link? -
 DRD)! And it's a big drawback for this demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Potentially could be much better.

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "UnauthorizedLands" "Unauthorized Lands / Nah-Kolor"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Unauthorized Lands
@{B}Group:@{UB} Nah-Kolor

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Abduction
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 8

@{B}Size:@{UB} 4.48 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor

@{B}Code:@{UB} Hedgehog, Metal Designer, Scout (C2P routines)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Amiflash, Fra, Stile9, Unreal
@{B}Music:@{UB} Estrayk
@{B}Design:@{UB} Magic, Case

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ A great HAM8 voxelscape, very good pictures, funny tone of some parts
- Not many objects and not very original, the design isn't great

@{B}Comment:@{UB} If you don't know the background of this demo, most of its
 point is lost. But who in the Amiga world doesn't know the TBL productions
 like @{" Darkside " link "Darkside"} and @{" Tint " link "Tint"}? Very few people indeed! But therefore this
 Nah-Kolor madness is very welcome. It's impossible to stop a smile when
 you see the Nah-Kolor logo on which the water trace begins to move with
 some @{" Darkside's " link "Darkside"} sound-a-like tune! And the high quality pictures shown
 throught the demo grant a good graphical impact of it all.
 Of course there are also other "serious" effects, such as a tunnel with
 bump mapped textures with transparent credits scrolling down its sides,
 the title picture that allows you to see a short glimps of a couple of
 faces before it disappears and especially a wonderful and colorful
 voxelscape in HAM8 with a transparent shaded object moving in front of it
 when it stops. These are evidences of good code. The greetings part is
 made using a big picture that scrolls up and down that reminds me of
 another similar effect in Rebel's @{" Switchback " link "Switchback"}, and the greetings part
 continues on a strange texture mapped object composed like a wireframe
 cube with cubes at the vertex, conjuncted from rectangular pipes. A little
 motion blur trail is also visible. But the biggest smile appears on your
 face when you'll see the big fish of TBL's @{" Tint " link "Tint"} (a 3D object
 with bump mapped texture and motion blur) moving around in front of a good
 2D twirling distortion background. Then the final picture ends the show.
 The music is a good techno module by Estrayk, but really not the best tune
 from this spanish musician. However fits the demo well enough.
 You can see that this demo isn't the most original demo ever, but its comic
 verve is funny, and I guess that the real intention for the Nah-Kolor guys
 is to have fun!

                                                        DareDevil

@{B}Comment:@{UB}
 After an inspirational break, the italian Nah-kolored around Metal
 Designer are back with yet another attempt to crash through barriers at a
 party. This time with a demo which a prominent member of Nah-kolor claimed
 to be Arte2 in the forefield. Something that would set new standards.
 Naturally this raises expectations and can therefore be dangerous for a
 productions reputation. Well, we are curious if this mate was right and if
 we really might have a trendsetter here.
 The demo itself starts with a small Nah-kolor logo on black ground in
 hi-res interlaced, which changes to 2X2 resolution, when a watereffects
 runs over the logo.  Always a beauty and also the speed is high, but
 nothing new here.
 Then a rendered fullscreen picture of a spaceship flying through a gate
 saying "The Truth is out There" in some futurist urban surroundings.
 Nicely done with a load of details by Amiflash.
 On our hunt for the promised sensations we get stucked in our enthusiasm.
 A tunnel is shown with a texture. So far this would only be boring, but
 why the hell is it so slow? Actually on a 68060, the whole tunnel almost
 doesn't move at all. There is reason to believe that on lower machines,
 the speed might be reasonable but somehow this is strange. Still then the
 effect uncovers something interesting indeed - although I can't say if
 there had been demos with a similar effect. A scroller appears darkened-
 transparently on the texture, fitting in perspective and movement to the
 bending of the tunnel. Additionally lighteffects run timed to the music
 over the walls. A nice display and the scroller which features the credits
 runs faster than the tunnel itself so that there is a contrast in the
 movement, which increases the positive impact.  Again: This could be
 different on 68030.
 Then my favourite:  Although "only" a fullscreen by Unreal is displayed
 next, the in and out fading of it is lovely. How to describe it? Imagine
 a black screen and then parts of the screen are faded to transparency and
 reveal the picture behind it. I said parts, because the parts which stay
 longer onscreen in fact give another image for a short time: Three faces
 (children or women I am not sure) are visible for the friction of a second.
 The same happens as negative with the outfading of the picture, when the
 transparency turns into a black screen back again. Why, however, they also
 state in that fading effect that "Rio/Eleven 11 is gay" remains their
 secret. Hopefully some kind of friendly teasing.
 Something that seemingly is not to be laid to rest are voxelspaces and also
 in this demo we have another one. Speciality here: A strongly coloured
 texture moves with the mountains and valleys and also the perspective is a
 little inconventional, which gives a good impression. Yet in the end it's
 a voxelspace and there is nothing more to add about it.
 When a transparent object in the form of a monolith starts moving of the
 voxelspace, the later one is freezed in his moment which somehow disturbs
 the scene.  To see them both moving would have been something more
 appealing. In this way it simply is an transparent object.
 Then follows a two-screened background picture once again by Unreal which
 scrolls vertically while the greets are displayed in the foreground,
 followed by another real nicely composed fullscreen picture by Stile9.
 Some further greetings are shown while a cubic object, consisting of
 pillars connected by cubes at the edges runs over the screen for a short
 time.
 Then the last effect already comes in. Another object, this time in shape
 of a fish dances around playfully in the water, which is represented by a
 twirl in blue and white in the background. Much like the other objects,
 also the fish features motion blur.
 The final picture by Unreal is shown as extroduction and comes in the known
 and expected Unreal quality.
 The music fits the release and is timed to the ongoings onscreen. It gives
 the needed athmosphere and remains in the background, which really is what
 a demotune is supposed to do. Only odd here is with a load of Prodigy
 samples, taken from their 1997 "The Fat of the Land" album the score partly
 sounds like a medley, only that it is enriched by Discoparts.
 A short and compact demo which doesn't wait so long with displaying its
 effects that it ever could get boring. It indeed has some interesting
 details which increase the overall impression and no doubt we have seen a
 release here which fullfills all common demands and that also convinces.
 What we have not gained however is the promised trendsetter. No "Arte2",
 rather an "Episode2" as it clearly follows the style of their demo released
 at the Gravity'97, although the people behind that demo where not the same.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Recommended to run after some TBL productions!

                                                RockDaZone/Endzeit


@{B}Inside information:@{UB} The picture that appears when the title
 picture disappears shows the faces (from left to right) of Psycho/Figa
 Production, Rio/Elven Eleven and Metal Designer.

@EndNode


@Node "Aphrodisiae" "Aphrodisiae / Haujobb"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Aphrodisiae
@{B}Group:@{UB} Haujobb

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Symposium-Mekka
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.74 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Darken
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} JCS, Kidlove
@{B}Music:@{UB} Muffler
@{B}Design:@{UB} Owl

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Very good code, good touched images, adrenalinic tune
- Ordinary 3D objects, functional design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Aphrodisiae seems to be a derivation of the word
 "Aphrodisiac" that is something caused by sexual excitement, but I really
 didn't find anything "sexual exciting" in this demo. So I guess that the
 real meaning of the title is a synonym for beauty. The beauty is some
 sparkling stars dancing on the title picture, in colors mixed in a twirled
 distortion, in images of female photos elaborated with special effects.
 It is in a 3D-scene with a gourad shaded Haujobb logo dancing towards six
 monoliths, in an adrenalinic (that's their intention, indeed it's a bit
 slow) tunnel voyage amid protruding points. It is especially in a 3D
 mountain flower opening its petals, while sparkling stars exits from the
 bud and begin to dance around the flower like fireflies. It is in some
 incredible twisting and distorting textures in 2D.
 It is a bit less in a 3D ring with four pyramids around it and a phong
 cube morphing into a pointed star, while the same kind sparkling stars as
 with the flower are running around this object. It is in the 2D  bump
 mapped glass background presenting a little obscure comment: "A healthy
 mind is one free of pressure. A healthy mind is one at eace!". And it is
 on the final picture with the endscroller scrolling in front of it.
 It's a show of electronic beauty, but it is so beautiful after all? I
 cannot answer this question, but it sure is a fine demo, and it's one of
 the very few examples where the music changes very well according to the
 effect changes. This is the result of good coding with and an amazing
 techno style tune. A very good piece of work.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A very good demonstration of solid work. Recommended!

                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "DesertDream" "Desert Dream / Kefrens"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Desert Dream
@{B}Group:@{UB} Kefrens

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1993
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 6

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.63 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} OCS/ECS, 1 MB RAM, needs a patch to install on HD

@{B}Code:@{UB} Laxity, Zeus, Vention
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} R.W.O., Airwalk, Blizzart, Laxity
@{B}Music:@{UB} Laxity, Dice
@{B}Design:@{UB} Laxity, Zeus, Airwalk

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Great design and atmosphere, good music
- It's an old glory demo from back then (but is that bad!? - DRD)

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Space. You see Earth as a big blue ball and a little alien
 spaceship is entering the atmosphere. Zooming into Earth you reach Cairo,
 Egypt. In the desert there are three famous pyramids: Cheops, Mikerinos
 and Kefrens. An alien spaceship arrives, flying in front of Kefrens
 pyramid. It's ready to launch its menacing weapon: A melon! Will that
 glorius pyramid receive a so hard insult without replying? No! So two
 cannon appear from a secret port on the pyramid's surface and shoot two
 missiles against the spaceship. The aliens try to escape, but the missiles
 inexorable hits their target and in a flash the aliens are gone. This is
 the most famous and funny intro of a demo ever seen, all of it is flat
 shaded 3D vectors. It is also a joke (or a war declaration?!) to Melon
 Design! Now the real demo starts: A very cool disco tune introduces the
 Desert Dream logo rotating in fake 3D to the rhythm of the music. A 3D
 bouncing scrolltext welcomes us to this Kefrens production. Then a classic
 3D shaded cube is shown, it's composed of 10.000 little zooming dots.
 Laxity loves to compose mathematical 3D dots structures dancing on screen
 and the music seems to adapt itself to this dance, changing when new
 effects start, for example a 3D vector tunnel or some classic, big,
 colored balls that dance and rotates on the screen, flat shaded, and with
 transparency effects. The balls morph into a circular picture that morphs
 itself into a disk saw-blade that seems to hit and break the screen! And
 a fitting noise, very well syncroniced, enhance this great effect. Another
 music change, another effect: A dancing vector ball moves to the rhythm of
 the music. Now the first part of the demo ends.
 The second part starts with a new piece of music and a scrolling text with
 a strange bitmap font that seems to be in 3D because some parts of the
 characters is enlightened or darkened according to the position of a
 little lightsource. Then some colorful bitmap copper bars dance on screen,
 followed by a 4800 dots starfield in 2 bitplanes. When reduced to 1200
 dots, something interesting is shown: A 3D flatshaded cube with copperbars
 on it. The music changes again and two big textured 3D balls jumps around
 on the screen. Then a dots circular tunnel introduces a little rotozooming
 picture with darken reflex on the bottom and 4250 dots floating in sine
 curves. After a deformed sine-copper chess-board base the end of this demo
 with the classic final scrolltext is reach.
 In the hidden part you find some dancing 2D vectorlines with a little
 blur tail and greetings and addresses of some Kefrens members on a
 deformed sine chess-board base similar to the last effect of the demo.
 Code, graphics and music are very good, but firstly Desert Dream (as
 Sanity's @{" Arte " link "Arte"} ) is a masterpiece of old school design. This demo has
 very old effects, 32 color graphics and shows only 3D cubes or dots dance,
 but everything flows and is timed well, it's very well coordinated (the
 music changes helps very much!). This demo shows that also a simple A500
 demo is capable to teach something to the late '90s lifeless productions
 without being memory- and processor-hungry.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A great demo lessons from old school. Watch it and learn.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} This was Kefrens's last OCS/ECS production.

 The hidden part is found booting from 2nd disk. When a black screen
 appears you have to press both mouse buttons and the joystick button.

 The three pyramids are the only "Wonders of the World" that are still
 standing, all others have been destroyed by wars, earthquakes and the
 like. They are located at the Gizeh plain near Cairo, Egypt, and build
 about 4000 years ago (measured from year 2000) during the 4th dynasty.
 How they were build is still a mystery, however, the most common theory is
 that about 100000 slaves (some say workers) placed the big blocks of
 stone to build the huge tombs (that's whats pyramids are made for is the
 common opinion, but I guess Kefrens among others has another theory...).
 Today the pyramid's conditions are pretty bad due to age, pollution and
 tourism.
 (Source: Basic - Emneleksikon (published by "12 Břger"))

                                                   (Pyramid info: Dreyer)

                                                        DareDevil

@EndNode


@Node "VisibleWorld" "Visible World / Mawi & Venus Art"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Visible World
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mawi & Venus Art

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Rush Hours 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.90 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD, AHI, XPK library
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor

@{B}Code:@{UB} BJSebo, Noe
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Zoltan, Jacko, Azzaro
@{B}Music:@{UB} Dave/Haujobb
@{B}Design:@{UB} Azzaro

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Incredible raytraced pictures, good design, multitasking
- It's a slideshow with effects - not a real demo

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This one is a strange product! I can't say if it is a
 slideshow with a demo base or a demo with a slideshow incorporated. The
 only clear thing is that Zoltan's raytraced pictures are great with a
 fantastic use of all features of Maxon Cinema. And around this production
 pictures was developed for this "slidemoshow" (it's an ugly name, but I
 really don't know how to call this strange thing!).
 The most interesting thng about it is that the design is really accurate:
 Azzaro wrote some poetic words in style to introduce and to follow you in
 every picture, like in a voyage in Zoltan's art. But with words only this
 slideshow would be very poor... So in the background you can see a very
 interesting tunnel with a rippled texture and some flying lights, a
 classic 2D background rotation, and some phong and env-mapped flying 3D
 objects surrounded by lensflares and light reflections, such as a
 five-pointed star, some cog-wheels, a strange extruded thing with four
 rounded points, another one like a tri-pointed shuriken pierced in its
 center and finally the two Mawi and Venus Art words.
 Thank to the Visual Art 3D library all this is possible, a bit too slow,
 but possible, and in full multitasking! Only the music, a trance tune with
 underground sonority, is a bit below expectations and sometimes it's also
 a bit boring. Textures are only functional, but of course the real star of
 this slideshow is Zoltan!
 After all it's not only a show of good graphics, but a wonderful voyage
 into one's imagination with a good touch of Sci-Fi.
 I won't describe the pictures - they really need to be seen by yourself.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} It's an original way to develope a slideshows and it's
 an interesting experiment, but it's not a real demo.

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "Synergy" "Synergy / Sector 7"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Synergy
@{B}Group:@{UB} Sector 7

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Siliconvention
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 1

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.57 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '030/50Mhz, AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 6 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50MHz, cache databurst disabled

@{B}Code:@{UB} NoName
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} JCS
@{B}Music:@{UB} Marc
@{B}Design:@{UB} NoName, JCS

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some good raytraced animations that seems to be 3D effects...
- ... but all are in 2x2, some lacks in design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The first time I saw this demo I thought it had the fastest
 3D-engine with blur I've ever seen. However, it isn't: Using some
 raytraced animations with a realtime blur effect, and with the right
 colors, they reproduce some classic 3D effects faster than using a real
 3D engine, it's still in 2x2 resolution, though.
 That's probably a great idea, because using a good design, it could be
 possible to create great effects and, of course, a great production. Well,
 this demo tries to do it, but I think that a bit more accurate design
 would produce a better result. I'm explaining: The intro part is an
 animation of a voyage into a temple with a light in the center and lens
 flares reflections, then we reach a group of phong toruses, exploding. A
 good preface. After the title pictures (with a good "presents" animation),
 another anim of some torus and five pointed stars objects moving on screen
 with high persistance and blur effects is on. There's a kind of logical
 link to the previous effect. That's good. Now, why the next effects are
 all introduced only by the music changes (a good dance tune) and nothing
 else? Maybe because a plain bump mapping and a plain ripple twisted bump
 map does not contain a torus?! This is a lack in the design. Next effects
 shown are a tunnel (I'm not sure, but also this seems to be an animation
 with that blur effect) and a nice true colour picture in interlaced-mode.
 Then there are some very interesting variants of the classic bump map
 effect: The first is a chain object of "glass" used to deform the
 scrolling background picture. The second, coming after the credits
 picture, is an animated Amiga word bumpmap on the same background picture,
 but this effect is in 2x2 resolution. This effect is very interesting
 because it seems as if a water surface logo is coming out of screen!
 It's probably the best effectin the demo, except for the 2x2 resolution.
 Then another animation of some submarines (or spacecrafts?) apears.
 They are floating on an azure depth, but is too blurred (and in 2x2
 resolution) to be clear. Another piece of music is on and the final
 scrolling titles appear on a deformed glass background (of course it's
 bumpmap), a scrolling picture of a bikini girl. That's the end.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Some interesting effects make this demo worth to have a look
 at, or two.

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "Rise" "Rise / Mellow Chips of TRSi"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Rise
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mellow Chips of TRSi

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 10

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.39 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor

@{B}Code:@{UB} Aivo
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ReWired, Asa
@{B}Music:@{UB} Kalsu/Artificial People
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Ola, Lich, Tequila, Aivo
@{B}Design:@{UB} Mellow Chips

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ****

+ A great production in code, graphics, music, a new horizon in design
- Code could be improved a bit to use 1x1 pixel graphics

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Like a dream... A beautiful girl, Jane, in a yellow bikini walk
 towards you in a dark tunnel. Then stops behind the entrance of a cave
 hidden behind a waterfall. The camera flies around her wonderful body and
 she's ready to jump into the waterfall, a big jump in a kind of little
 paradise with great and colourful flowers and a temple with a big portal.
 Another scene: Under the water in a dark and obscure room a trap-door
 opens and an octopus exits.
 Jane has just entered the temple and she's looking around: Big windows
 show a blue sky and green trees, and in the last room there's an altar for
 the goddess (the mother goddess?) with two templars standing next to it
 and a stained glass ceiling. Jane goes to the altar and she's ready to
 rise in a cone of blue light with an explosion of colorful spots.
 This girl can't be reached by the evil forces and the snake can only wait
 for another victim, but not this one!
 Yeah! Finally a demo which can define a new standard in design!
 All in this demo is made keeping in mind a storyboard. And also if some
 things in the demo are not completely clear (for example what does the
 octopuss represent? ;-)) and the effects are nothing new, you don't mind!
 You are watching a brief story with a concrete sense! That's what I call
 "Design"!
 The 3D engine is the same as in other productions such as @{" Divine " link "Divine"} and
 @{" Dim " link "Dim"}, maybe a bit improved, but with the same 2x2 pixels graphics and the
 same persistance effect. Interesting, but in some parts such as the
 paradise, the persistance effect is a bit annoying. Without this effect
 there might be more CPU time for a 1x1 pixel resolution!
 The 3D objects are really incredible and the Jane gait remember Lara Croft
 (but Jane is more sexy! ;-)) Worth noticing is also the title part with
 sparkling stars joining in the word "presents" and a laser beam writing
 the word "Rise" on a marble plate amid sparks and lens flares, very
 impresive!
 The 2D pictures are very good and technically valuable. Of course also
 the rendered title picture are great with a wise use of translucency and
 colours. Musics are not only functional, but very atmospherical and gives
 the right enphasis to the various scenes.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A must for your collection!
                                                        DareDevil

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} This demo is the first "3D-only" demo for Amiga. It's a
 genre that is wellknown on PeeCees, and also known to be quite boring in
 the long run, and that run is something quite short...
 However, luckily Rise is not an example of a boring demo. On the contrary!

                                                        Dreyer

@EndNode


@Node "Nostalgica" "Nostalgica / Nukleus"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Nostalgica
@{B}Group:@{UB} Nukleus

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 10

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.33 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ECS, 2 MB chip-RAM, 1 MB fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Balder
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Browallia
@{B}Music:@{UB} dIS

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ----

+ Maybe there's a bit of design (very little)
- All!

@{B}Comment:@{UB} What do you could expect from a demo with this title? Maybe a
 demo with old effects, in old skool style? Maybe something with good, old
 copper bars? Nothing of all this is in the demo!
 In my opinion this demo was spread as something with kind of a style, but
 it hasn't! Yes, I could say that there's a bit of design, and I could say
 that the graphics have a proper style, very "naive" (it's a question
 of point of view!), but please don't tell me that this demo is something
 comparable to today's stardards! I cannot believe that this demo has
 gained the 3rd place at The Gathering 98!!!
 The music is not acceptable, but the most terrible thing in this
 production is the coding, without any kind of VBlank refresh test in the
 3D section. The only merit of this demo is to be ECS compatible.
 What a pity that, on my 68040, it didn't want to start until I disabled
 the VBR in fast-RAM, and what a pity that there are no notes of this
 problem in the readme-text (I really don't want to annoy you with how I
 discovered this trick!).
 Let's speak of the "wonderful" effects of this demo: After an intro
 picture in hires interlace, a couple of 3D pixel objects, to be precise a
 pair of eyeglasses and a male symbol, rotate on the screen, followed by a
 gouraud shaded (?) 3D object representing a coke bottle and a torus with
 changing color palette. Then the "nostalgic" part begins: It's a
 comparison of some things from the past and today's equivalents, proposed
 as 8 color brushes (Wow! Is it in dual-playfield? No, it isn't!) moving in
 each side of the screen. The objects are an abacus and a scientific
 calculator, some prehistorical graffiti and a page of an exercise-book, a
 drum and a hifi-system, some heavy socks and a Nike shoe, some huts and a
 skyscraper, a meridian and a digital watch, some letters and an e-mail
 symbol "@". Afterwards is the presentation of their 4K intro, a Pacman
 running on the screen, and after that an ECS picture in full 32 colors
 (the only interesting thing in the whole demo). Afterwards the greetings
 appear and then it's the end of the demo.
 Ah! Now it all becomes clear! Now I understand: This entire demo is kind
 of a joke reserved to someone (maybe one of the organizer at the party?).
 It's the only reasonable explanation I could find to justify why a "thing"
 like this gained that 3rd place.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Can we call this crap a demo? Avoid it!

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "Nebula" "Nebula / Dual Crew Shining"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Nebula
@{B}Group:@{UB} Dual Crew Shining

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 10

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.15 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor

@{B}Code:@{UB} Shape
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Adam, Shape, Illusion
@{B}Music:@{UB} Tweek, Muffler/Haujobb
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Adam, Shape
@{B}Design:@{UB} Adam, Shape

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Very fast 3D engine, very good intro part
- Some minor annoyance in code, design a bit lacking

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Interesting demo! Good idea to show the intro part as titles of a
 50's Sci-Fi TV series! But after this funny intro, the other effects are
 just variations of some common ideas. There's a good use of textures and
 lights, but the code is not perfect. I had some problems with fragmented
 memory running this demo, and I would be very happy to be advised about
 this bug in the readme text, if someone did remember to write a note!
 Of course, this is not a big problem: A simple boot without startup-
 sequence is the right solution (but irritating - DRD).
 The real problem is a bit lack of design. When you see such a great intro
 with a so interesting name, don't you expect something with the same
 theme later in the demo? Well, I don't think that the flying 3D-plants,
 3D-scenes and a flower with a bunch of stars exiting from its petals are
 linked to the Sci-Fi theme!
 With the right background it could be considered as alien plants, but
 there's no background! Maybe the tunnel with the bump mapped texture,
 with one enlightened outline, anonther dark, with some pulsating stars
 moving in helix path could be considered a more fitting effect for the
 purpose. Instead there's a very cool b/w picture of a man in whom's
 eyeglasses are two tunnels! Also the "teletransport" 3D-scene of a
 transparent object that moves from one teleporter to the other with many
 little lightsballs here and there is a very "Star Trek"-like effect. This
 effect is nothing screaming, but is an interesting idea! Very well coded
 and original is the greetings part: A deformed, twisted texture on which
 fade the names of greeted groups. The twisting bump mapped tunnel voyage
 with a textured object flying in it is a common effect (in 2x2
 resolution), but it's very fast. Final effect: Another 3D plant scene with
 a star object with some lights in its core is rotating with a reflex on
 the bottom, like a water surface. When the lights explodes from the core
 of the object the final scolltext starts. Some notes about the music: The
 intro tune is very cool, even though, it's only a simple digitizing of a
 50's TV series tune, but this music enphasizes the 50's atmosphere of the
 intro. On the other hand the demo tune and the final tune are a bit under
 the usual standard, but fits the demo very well because they are well
 synchronized with the effects changes.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A very good intro part, and a demo with a good style.
 Have a look!
                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "Napalm" "Napalm / Floppy"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Napalm
@{B}Group:@{UB} Floppy

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Rush Hours 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.36 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040/25Mhz or better

@{B}Code:@{UB} Zig, Rzyg
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Fame, Def
@{B}Music:@{UB} X-ceed/Appendix
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Yasi

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ All in 18 bit true-color, very good design
- 2x2 pixel resolution

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Great demo! It's like a punch in your stomach, both from a
 technical point of view and concerning the style!
 The first thing you can see is the Floppy logo on a rotating circular 2D
 figure, followed by some tunnels, circular and a four-leaved flower
 shaped. On these effects some zooming words describes some thoughts of a
 solidier in Vietnam. Then another 2D effect, a sort of distorted
 interference is on. When this effect is running there's a little flashback
 with two transparent 3D-scenes mixed together, and when the 2D effect ends
 these scenes are shown clearly. The first one is a strange object composed
 of four columns with a base on a cylinder and a ball (?) on the other
 side, the second is a pierced cube with some strange objects like long
 leaves from a tropical plant. Both these scenes are shown alternately with
 a heavy persistance effect. Afterwards another 2D effect, a distorted and
 moving bumped out flower, introduce another 3D scene. This one is composed
 of some columns and a ball, alternating the textured scene with
 wireframes. On this one some other words (other thoughts) are zooming. The
 last 3D scene reveals the real shock of this lost mind: A moving swing
 (infancy) and a guillottine with a moving blade (death). Then the title of
 this demo (on a background of blurred raylight) show what caused this
 nightmare: Napalm.
 Well, this demo has a great style! But what about technical aspects? Also
 great! Let's see...
 ALL effects are in HAM8 18 bit true-color, but using a 2x2 pixel
 resolution, sometimes it's even to heavy for my 68040/25. Of course it
 isn't a great problem (maybe only some 68030 owners will not be very
 happy). Two logos by Fame are very nice, and also the 3D-scenes with
 objects and textures in HAM8 are very impressive. And the module is of a
 high quality with a great drum sequence and a techno style that fits the
 demo well.
 But the real force of this production is a good design: The effect changes
 are very well synchronized to the music. It's a demo with hard messages
 transmitted with music, with words and with objects. A very fine piece of
 work! This time the Floppy's guys hit the target very well!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} You must see this shocking production!

@{B}Note:@{UB} Has nothing to do with the real-time strategy game Napalm.

                                                        DareDevil


@EndNode


@Node "Bangcock" "Bangcock / Embassy"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Bangcock
@{B}Group:@{UB} Embassy

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Motorola Inside 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 8

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.04 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM, FPU, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060, Cybergraphics

@{B}Code:@{UB} Humanoid, Sly
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Humanoid, Temen
@{B}Music:@{UB} Temen

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some new ideas, good graphics
- A big lack in design, it's too slow on processors lesser than 68060

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Very difficult to judge a demo like this! This demo is explicitly
 developed to run on '060 and has some of the most interesting effects
 that I've ever seen, all in 1x1 pixel resolution. On the other hand so
 powerful effects is very slow, also on fast processors as my '040, and,
 the biggest lack in my opinion, it's a simple show of incredible effects
 without soul and design. For this reason it will probably fall into
 oblivion. What a pity! Because this demo shows its high quality code right
 from the start with an impressive bilateral distortion of the Embassy
 logo, then continues with a fisheye lens 2D distortion of a background
 on which a transparent 3D sponge moves around! The next effect is a very
 fine texture mapped vector landscape with a bit of phong, but very slow.
 Then the title logo follows, very well distorted. The next effect is a big
 3D object, textured, and full of spot lights rotating on its axis, while a
 picture presenting a woman scrolls in the background. When the full
 picture is on the screen it disappears and a new object, a morphing
 sponge, is on together with another lady picture. Then a group of strange
 symbols overlaps this scene, changing randomly. Afterwards there's a new
 scene. The same big object as seen previously, but this time phong and
 env-mapped, rotates in front of two 3D textured planes amid a group of
 flying spot lights. Then it's time for greetings that appears scrolling up
 on a background that shows an incredible 2D distortion of rotating
 textures. The music changes and a new effect comes up. This is an
 undefinable phong object (the internal section of a torus?) moving very
 slowly in the background while a picture moves in the foreground. Now we
 are ready to follow a deformed 3D torus in its fast fly into a texture
 mapped vector tunnel. The last effect is simply wonderful: The strange
 big object returns, now transparent, while stretching a full screen
 texture in the foreground with a cool effect of surface tension on the
 object border. Very impressive, but also very slow! The demo ends with a
 big Embassy logo on a 2D texture, distorted.
 Thr code is great, but slow. Graphics is okay, but with a choice of colors
 that is sometimes monotone. Music is a strange techno piece with some
 good parts and some parts that are less good, but it's functional to
 support a few of the visual changes.
 Why did Embassy's guys develop a so incredible masterpiece of code only to
 show that they are capable to do that and nothing else? They lost a good
 opportunity to do a great demo!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Design problems are common and this will be something to take
 care of for the next Embassy demo!

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "EverythingDiesPPC" "Everything Dies PPC / Venus Art"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Everything Dies PPC
@{B}Group:@{UB} Venus Art

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Rush Hours 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} Not in competition

@{B}Size:@{UB} 7.27 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD, AHI, PPC Processor
              Tested using the 2nd PPC patch
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060 (for 680x0 processor) or PPC processors, Cybergraphics

@{B}Code:@{UB} Noe, BJSebo
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Madd, Neuromancer
@{B}Music:@{UB} Wierza
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Zack, Calf, At0m
@{B}Design:@{UB} Venus Art

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Fast with PowerPC, some good textures, support for AHI and Cybergraphics
- Too slow on 680x0, lacks design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This is the first PPC demo ever released and I think that it's a
 good demonstration of the real power of PPC. I don't want to offend no
 one, but I must say that Virtua Art 3D's routines aren't really fast
 compared to other non-Venus Art's productions.
 I presume that the reason is because these aren't written in assembler,
 but in C with the whole demo running in full multitasking.
 Of course, this disadvantage on 680x0 that constrict to use a very fast
 processor (possibly faster than 68060!) to obtain the right speed.
 A PPC processor is a great advantage! C sources are easily portable
 without too many changes and, to tell you the truth, it's a BIG pleasure
 to run something showing its real power on a PowerPC, especially if
 compared to 680x0!
 About the demo: It's an average production with the common lack in design,
 as seen in too many demos, that is to use music changes as link between
 effects that are completely different from concept and theme.
 After the classic Venus Art logo with the Venus marble bust, some 3D
 letters enter the screen composing the title of the demo. Then a big ball
 with bump mapped texture and some horns fluctuates on the screen. The
 following object is an env-mapped star covered with some transparent 3D
 layers in that breaks off to reveal metallic reflection on the star's
 surfaces. Then four env-textured gears flies around while rotating on
 themself.
 The next effect is very impressive: A helicopter full of lights and lens
 flares reflections is flying among some skyscrapers (very ugly textures
 though). The flight ends under a bridge on a river. After a nice picture
 there's a little Quake-inspired scene: A girl with a big gun is running
 on a bridge and stand before three crucified human shapes and a big horned
 devil. Another picture and a wonderful scene appear: A kind of aquarium
 with tropical fish with very good textures. Then another picture is shown
 and another scene: A bee is flying among light reflexes, it lands on a
 cheese (?) object on a table. The camera rotate, and, on the same table,
 a spider is walking towards the cheese. Last effect: A strange 3D object
 breaks a transparent layer to reveal its dance on the screen while some
 words appear to conclude this demo.
 Some of the objects in the demo are very original and with fantastic
 textures (like the tropical fish), others are common (the star) or
 recycled (the spider is the same as in Quagmire, a Venus Art intro).
 The pictures are okay. The music is a good demo style module with a touch
 of techno.
 Worth mentioning is that this demo also runs with Cybergraphics and uses
 AHI for music. There's only one disadvantage: This demo crashes if running
 on a interlaced AGA screen! If it worked it would be an incredible
 demonstration of power for a PPC board!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} If you have a PPC board you must have it! But not
 recommended for 680x0.
                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "ExtraLife" "Extra Life / Abyss"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Extra Life
@{B}Group:@{UB} Abyss

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Symposium-Mekka 98
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.67 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Spin
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cyclone
@{B}Music:@{UB} Muffler/Haujobb, Bay Tremore/Haujobb
@{B}Design:@{UB} Spin, Cyclone

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ good code, a very original graphic style
- some little lacks in design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Nice demo indeed! The effects are quite common, but
 the way they are coded is visibly different than most other demos. Also,
 there's a secret part, but I wasn't able to find it. The graphic style
 by Cyclone is very interesting and different and the music is of high
 quality, however, it sounds to me as if some sounds in the second tune
 that are a bit too distorted. The only lacking thing is design, especially
 in the second part of the demo. But the real lack is the usual habit of
 many coders (and Spin it's not an exception), that is to link
 non-correlated effects together, where only with music changes save the
 transition.
 The demo is very clean with a Workbench requester to advice you that all
 multitasking will be suspended and with a gadget to enter the secret part
 (it's a joke!). When you start it the Abyss title introduces a twisting 
 tunnel composed by a lot of circle-shaped bobs overlapping each other to
 form what could look a bit like textures. This effect has a technique
 very similar to an effect seen in second part of Dr. Skull's @{" Psychedelic " link "Psychedelic"}.
 That one had an X and Y movement, this one is also moving in Z. Afterwards
 four balls deforming a texture by moving around above it (or in it?).
 That's followed by another tunnel with a very strange texture effect:
 Seems as if a big circular bob is floating on the screen in which every
 pixel defines luminosity. The applied texture rotates in classic tunnel
 mode. Looks quite a lot like plasma. This is the end of the first part.
 The second part is introduced by a very cool picture, after that credits
 are shown and another tunnel appears made with circle-shaped bobs, but
 this time it's build from four spirals. Afterwards four rotating points
 dance in the same mode as seen before with the balls. The next effect is a
 vertical rubbish rotator with light moving on it all in 1x2 pixel
 resolution and the last effect is a 2D rippling wave. All effects,
 except for the rubbish rotator are in 2x2 pixel resolution.
 At the end the final scrolltext is presented on a background with a simple
 but nice interference effect.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A nice demo worthy of a look or two

@{B}Inside information:@{UB}
 There's a secret part to discover!
 At Symposium the organizers that showed the demo was very eager to choose
 the "I hate Abyss"-gadget found in the demo's start up menu. Finally they
 chose not too...

                                                        DareDevil

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Extralife01.jpg"} The graphics and design is something special
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Extralife02.jpg"} Tired of the insides of tunnels? Abyss seems to be!...
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Extralife03.jpg"} The title constantly moves according to the music
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Extralife04.jpg"} Four fast moving balls covered with a color changing texture, great!
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Extralife05.jpg"} A fancy transition leads to this picture (that even won the pixel compo)
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Extralife07.jpg"} A nice, lightsourced party twister
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Extralife08.jpg"} Difficult to see here, but this is actually voxel seen from above

@EndNode


@Node "Flea" "Flea / Appendix"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Flea
@{B}Group:@{UB} Appendix

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Rush Hours 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 4

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.27 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50Mhz or better processor

@{B}Code:@{UB} Informer
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Lazur
@{B}Music:@{UB} X-ceed

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Runs in 1x1 pixel resolution...
- ... but is too short!

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A short review for a very short demo. In a textured
 3D-scene a lightflare flies around while 3D letters spelling the Appendix
 name, env-mapped, enter. In this scene the credits and the title of the
 demo appear. Then the demo starts with the only effect of this little
 production: A voyage into a very well textured tunnel with four light
 flares flying from one side to the other with an extreme four-leaved,
 morphing effect in a pulsating light.
 That's all, and it's too few effects compared to other production in an
 standard demo competition. Is it a victim of deadline or is it a project
 born as dentro and spread as demo? Maybe we'll never know!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} It's too short, could have been something...

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "GhostInTheMachinePPC" "Ghost in the machine PPC / Venus Art"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Ghost in the Machine PPC
@{B}Group:@{UB} Venus Art

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Rush Hours 2
@{B}Placing:@{UB} Not in competition

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.48 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD, AHI, PPC processor
              Tested using the 2nd PPC patch
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060 (for 680x0 processor) or PPC processors, Cybergraphics

@{B}Code:@{UB} Noe, BJSebo
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Lazur
@{B}Music:@{UB} Wierza/Venture
@{B}Design:@{UB} Venus Art

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Support for AHI and Cybergraphics
- Lacks design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Ghost in the Machine is the second PPC demo ever released,
 however, it was developed some months before @{"Everything Dies" link "EverythingDiesPPC"}, the first
 PPC demo ever. Of course the Virtua Art 3D library routines are the same,
 so the considerations made for @{"Everything Dies" link "EverythingDiesPPC"} goes for this demo
 aswell, including the lack of design. Strange! I didn't know that design
 was dependent from a library of routines!?!
 I saw this demo when issued for 68k some months ago and it didn't give me
 a good impression. Too big 3D objects textured or env-mapped makes this
 demo an application that can make an 68060 sweat, but with PowerPC there's
 no problem!
 So, when the Venus Art title has disappeared, it's a beautiful sight to
 see the entering of 3D objects of the demo title, overlapped by a big
 env-mapped phong object, all of it is fast. But better than the titles
 is to see that a BIG and complex manga-styled, env-mapped chrome phong
 girl face rotating on your AGA screen fluently and fast! This object on
 68040 runs very, very slow! Of course, only PowerPC makes it possible! ;-)
 The rest of the demo is below average. The forthcoming Quake scene of a
 man hunted by a doberman dog who enters a room, shoots the dog, shows a
 really bad texture clipping on the polygon, also when transparent object
 and bump-mapped walls is seen. Afterwards a big object with a big hole on
 its center and bump mapped texture rotates on the screen together with the
 background, while a little object enters into its hole and comes out from
 the other side. Then an old Lazur picture appears, followed by a phong
 roller coaster, very ugly. The evident purpose is to remember the Rebel's
 @{" Switchback " link "Switchback"} scene, but the "velocity" impression is almost
 non-existing, even on PowerPC. I guess that the choices about the camera
 path-points were wrong. A animated 3D pterodactyl object flying in the air
 is on next, but it's too slow! The strange thing about it is that it runs
 fine in the 680x0 version!? After another 3D scene presenting big credits
 and a picture, a Virtua Art 3D logo with bump mapped textures that ends
 this demo appears.
 The music is of the same quality as in the first PPC-demo @{" Everything Dies " link "EverythingDiesPPC"},
 and the genre is the same, demo/techno.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Good to test the PPC processing power, but it isn't
 worth a second look.

                                                        DareDevil

 Click @{" here " link "GhostInTheMachine"} to go to the MC-version.

@EndNode


@Node "Love" "Love / Virtual Dreams of Fairlight"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Love
@{B}Group:@{UB} Virtual Dreams of Fairlight

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} South Sealand
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.63 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, HD installable
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast-RAM, '030/50Mhz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Dr. Skull
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Jaco, Matti Hänninen (final raytrace animation)
@{B}Music:@{UB} Jogeir
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Alien

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Smooth routines, good graphics, great music
- Lacks design a bit

@{B}Comment:@{UB} To be honest I don't like this demo very much. However a Dr.
 Skull's demo is always a bit above many other old skool productions,
 because his routines are very smooth and well coded. Probably the title,
 too pretentious compared with contents of the demo, is the cause of my
 judgement, but when a demo is called "Love", don't you expect something
 great?! The preface is good: The words of a lyric appears timed to the
 music's rhythm (a wonderful dance tune) and the last word of this lyric,
 "Love", is zoomed. A good effect. Then a 3D flat vector "love" word
 appears in a cool space cut effect. Afterwards a wonderful picture of
 Marilyn Monroe with a gory face make you perplexed! But when you see the
 deformed rotating base with mirror reflection and the two logos of
 Fairlight (gouraud shaded) and VD (flat) in space cut, there are no doubt:
 Love is referring only to the music that reminds me of the Haddaway's tune
 "What is Love?" and nothing else. The follwing are classic demo effects,
 cool considering the coding, but cold: An incredible twisted texture
 mapped phong cube, a raytraced animation floating on the screen, a good
 rotozooming base on which six soap bubbles are dancing and distorts the
 background with a lens effect, some dots morphing and rotating objects
 (very fast), a complex interference effect with mirror reflex and a
 fantastic realtime fractal zoomer. All these effects are well synchronized
 to the music, but a bit boring.
 The final (and greatest, as they claims) effects is a big raytraced
 animation of a Fairlight logo on which the final scrolltext appears, with
 a soft piece of music in the background. What else is there to say? I'm
 deluded from "Love"!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Pretentious and technically powerful, but with a boring style.

                                                        DareDevil

@{B}Veto:@{UB}
 I don't think the style is so very boring as stated above! First of all
 the technical level of the demo is high (as stated above), but it isn't
 cold. On the contrary. Instead of having some traditional black
 backgrounds, maybe with a starfield, VD has chosen some stylish pastel
 shades and naive shapes. The routines are fast and almost bugfree,
 however, they have nothing to do with love (I can't see what anyway).
 There is that nice picture presenting Monroe, but if she is the one they
 love how come she cries tears of blood? It's not a superb demo, just a
 good, traditional one.

                                                        Dreyer

@EndNode


@Node "MegademoIV2" "Megademo IV 2 / Artwork"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Megademo IV 2
@{B}Group:@{UB} Artwork

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Symposium-Mekka 98
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 8 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 4.36 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 2 MB chip-RAM, 4 MB fast-RAM, HD, '030 or better
 (including PowerPC, excluding PeeCee, but a PeeCee version exists), FPU
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Cybergraphics, PPC processor with WarpOS and RTG library

@{B}Code:@{UB} Azure, Tron, Steffen Hauser (PPC version)
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Fiver2
@{B}Music:@{UB} Sire/Lego, Halfbyte
@{B}Design:@{UB} Azure, Tron, Fiver2

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ The code is ported to any platform
- Unpleasing style, the music is a sequence of noises

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Some peoples like to spend time on real art, things like pictures
 in a museum,  and also music videos. Demos contain pictures, music and
 animation, so we could say that also demos are a sort of art! Now, many
 pictures and videos are really ugly considering "artistic performances",
 it's too obscure for common people. Probably this is a question of Design!
 There were and are so many artistic trends with particular styles for
 pictures and videos, but this doesn't mean that ALL pictures and ALL
 videos are pleasant!
 Is it the same for demos? I think that Megademo IV 2 is exactly in this
 situation. There's no doubt that there's a design, very strange, but a
 design. But it's not a pleasing design!
 Trying to imagine what thoughts Artwork's guys had when they developed
 this demo. Surely they were not happy because this would be the last
 Artwork production. Probably they wanted to do something different.
 This is the first demo that is ported to other platforms than Amiga,
 probably to shock people who, after this demo, will remember Artwork's
 demo for a long time: A real Megademo. Well, it's my opinion, but the result
 is not good! They can declare that this demo is "an audiovisual
 experiment" and that "you may not understand or like it", but my opinion
 is as stated above. All demos are "an audiovisual experiment", but this
 doesn't mean that a demo cannot be understood by all!
 If your demo is only a chaotic sequence of scrolling and fading layers
 above other layers, exposed to zooming of digitized electrical household
 appliances, some rotating colorful brushes, shade bobs effects and some
 strange, unclear texts, you can port it on to as many platform as you
 like, you can create a whole Internet site about, you can make it
 Cybergraphics and PPC compatible (simply faster!). But, really, do you
 think that your demo could be "understood"?! (I would say "appreciated" is
 a better word). Of course "The people at MS98 didnt" and I did neither!
 If Artwork will be remembered for a long time, this will be thanks to
 great productions such as @{" The Gate " link "TheGate"}, @{" Exit Planet Dust " link "ExitPlanetDust"}, @{" Megademo IV " link "MegademoIV"},
 Creep, Phi, Dawn, Wave, but do not count Megademo IV 2 on to this list!
 Artwork is dead, long live Artwork!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A failure to realize something different...

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} This is the last Artwork's production, Artwork
 died at Mekka-Symposium '98. It is said that it happened because of lack
 of communication, and because that the talented members was unable to work
 together.

 Click @{" here " link "MegademoIV"} to go to Megademo IV

                                                        DareDevil
@EndNode


@Node "84T" "84T / Da Jormas"

@{B}Name:@{UB} 84T
@{B}Group:@{UB} Da Jormas

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.98 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Raato, Peeka Pou, Vesuri
@{B}Music:@{UB} Lumenensii

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ A very different demo with a very different design
- The design is tasteless, the demo becomes monotone after a while

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Everyone that knows Da Jormas also knows that their demo
 is always different in some way compared to all other demos. This one is
 no exception! I'm not sure about the title, but the 84 could mean the year
 1984, which is quite easily spotted in the demo. It is very 80's in it's
 design. That doesn't mean that the routines are flatshaded vector boxes
 and shadebobs, it's only the picture and the way the effects are presented
 that lead your thoughts to back then. The colors are mostly bright, and a
 lot of photos and TV-snapshots are used as background, while in the
 foreground the most of the effects are presented. These effects are
 actually not that many. A close look reveals that there are only about
 three  different main routines in the demo, but there are many variations
 of these, and besides they are disguised in the 80's design which makes it
 a bit more interesting to watch. But it doesn't last in the long run. You
 get bored watching the phong objects and lightballs (sometimes with some
 blur added) and the strange plasma-zoomer (that uses a weird display).
 And then there's a nice and colorful bumpmap routine.
 The resolution is a bit low, but the frame rate is quite good. And then
 there's the music, which is a mixture of different genres, resulting in
 a easy listening tune with some groovy elements in it, or the other way
 around. It is very well timed to the visual part.
 Da Jormas has sure made a very interesting demo, but I feel that it's
 quite hard to like something that has a so 80's style and feel! It's
 plastic, loads of make-up, electric household appliances and strange
 color compositions.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth experiencing. A very different demo!

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/84T01.jpg"} The title shown using a beautiful bumpmap
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/84T02.jpg"} Many effects at once. Note the "design"
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/84T03.jpg"} A nice 3D flower
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/84T04.jpg"} Fungus are by some reason always popular...
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/84T05.jpg"} More strange design
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/84T06.jpg"} The credits screen

@EndNode


@Node "GenerationX" "Generation X / Haujobb"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Generation X
@{B}Group:@{UB} Haujobb

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.36 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, 6 MB RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} DRF
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Wave, Peachy
@{B}Music:@{UB} Dascon, Jazz

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Well timed music, excellent pictures
- some low resolution effects, lacks design, no quit

@{B}Comment:@{UB} An okay demo by the German Haujobb, where we get to see
 a bunch of quite common effects and some excellent pictures by Peachy, and
 a good title picture by Wave. The show starts with some zooming grids with
 the credits written in front of them. Afterwards the title is shown and
 the demo is about to start for real. A colorful zoom-rotator that twists
 and wrench is shown. The speed is good, but the resolution low. Later in
 the demo there's a similar one, but that one is also blured. A 3D-triangle
 like object, gouraud shaded, is on next (simple but nice), followed by a
 fast color zoomer, an effect that zooms a lot of colors towards you.
 Peachy then shows of his talent for drawing with an excellent underwater
 picture. After the other zoom-rotator a office lamp jumps across the
 screen - I believe that they are inspired (not to say have stolen the
 idea) by Andromeda's Nexus 7. Afterwards a low-res texture plasma is
 shown, then a torus that is lightshaded. Some of all the above mentioned
 effect is shown on screen together with some graphics here and there.
 Gives the demo a touch in the right direction, but the design is not
 state of the art. Some sequences last to long, some to short, there are
 no transitions, the choice of colors could be better, etc....
 The music is pretty traditional demo music, not bad, and timed well to the
 rest of the demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a must see, but worth spending time on.

@EndNode


@Node "TheLarch" "Larch, The / Mystic"

@{B}Name:@{UB} The Larch
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mystic

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ACG Hack VII
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1

@{B}Size:@{UB} 4.43 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, '020, 4 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Merko, Kermit
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Claw, Faust
@{B}Music:@{UB} Daiz'l

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Good coding
- Common routines, non-interesting pictures

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A demo that contains a bunch of quite common effects, techno
 music and pictures that have been made using a 3D program (that is,
 pastel backgrounds and stylish 3D-fonts - not breathtaking at all!).
 The demo starts with some of these 3D-pictures that introduces us to the
 demo. The pictures crossfades which looks nice. The first "real" effect,
 however, is a blue texturemapped flatscape with both floor and ceiling. It
 uses a strange kind of display, but you don't really see that because of
 the texture. It's a nice, fast routine. Afterwards the only pixelled
 picture in the demo is shown, but the quality is not very good. The eagle
 in the front looks like an eagle, but the background really needs some
 work. The next routine is a free-flight tunnel with a colorful texture on
 its wall. It seems as if Mystic is trying to tease TBL a bit, because
 they've put some lightnings on the texture (of course I'm refering to
 TBL's fantastic Tint). They aren't quite as succesful as TBL, though...
 The tunnel disappears to make room for a nice zoom-rotator that shows to
 be much more than that. It doesn't just display a picture, no, it plays a
 little animation (some chess pieces). And suddenly it starts to behave
 like a plasma too! Really great! The next effect is a flame routine. The
 flames is placed in a cup made of small polished stones. This is also the
 greetings-part where the greetings are written using the flames. The last
 effect is a nice, and very traditional voxel landscape using standard
 earth colors (green, brown, white, blue...). It's well coded, but is on
 for too long anyway. Finally some credit pictures are shown, followed by
 a nice traced end-picture.
 The music is well timed, but technically not impressive. The beat is good,
 though.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Many common, but well coded routines. Have a look!

@EndNode


@Node "Scout" "Scout / Genesis"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Scout
@{B}Group:@{UB} Genesis

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Italian Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 2 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.34 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040/'060

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ It's different
- Few and slow routines, bad music, strange short animations, strange
  design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A really strange production this is! For a start no names
 are mentioned at all, nor the title. Secondly, the demo is split into
 three parts even though they contain pretty much the same kind of stuff:
 Small animation and scanned pictures of planets, in particular Mars and
 that little buggy they send up there to investigate what's going on.
 The most advanced code is a tunnel look-alike with some kind of explosion
 in the end, 3D-starfields and a slow flatscape. The first part actually
 has some kind of design. We see a view over a desert, then the picture is
 scrolled up into the sky, up in space. From here the starfield takes over,
 and we see some planets flying around. The two last parts are unfortunate.
 The music is three pieces of bad techno. Not much to say about that.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Strange. Not strange enough for you to have a look.

@EndNode


@Node "A-Sensations" "A-Sensation / Ramses"

@{B}Name:@{UB} A-Sensation
@{B}Group:@{UB} Ramses

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Volcanic Party IV
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 4.4 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020 or better, AGA, 8 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060
@{B}Note:@{UB} The demo doesn't work correctly with a Squirrel in the SCSI
 port, so free it (the SCSI port, not the squirrel)!

@{B}Code:@{UB} DDG, Seven
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Zaac, Lord
@{B}Music:@{UB} Traven
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Helix
@{B}Additional work:@{UB} Ntsc, Lens

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Generally nice routines
- The 3D-scenes needs a lot of CPU power, repeats itself, lacks design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} 3D, lots of 3D. That is what you find in this demo. And
 some plasmas too. Nothing but 3D and plasma you might ask, and the answer
 is, unfortunately, no. But it's some nice and pretty fast 3D, at least if
 you forget the 3D-scenes for a moment. Those 3D-scenes really needs an
 '060 to run smoothly, but on the other hand they run in 1x1 resolution and
 is covered with nice textures. Just like the other objects. Non of them
 are very original, and that go for both scenes and objects. Last mentioned
 is nothing but blobs, however, these are mapped in different ways:
 Standard phong shading, bump mapped and env-mapped. And when they are on,
 one by one (sometimes more of the same kind at once), some scrolling
 textures are shown in the background, but they don't always fit the
 foreground concerning the colors. The plasma runs in 2x2 resolution, but
 is, besides from that, quite nice.
 I think this demo has three problems: The lack of variety in routines, the
 lack of design and transitions, and the fact that everything (more or
 less) seems to repeat itself twice. The blobs are shown twice, there are
 two 3D-scenes (different, yes, but placed one after another). Fortunately
 there are a few pictures to solve the problem a bit. They are in general
 well-drawn, however, they don't seem to have much to do with the other
 visuals. The music is okay, not well timed, but you never miss completely
 with a demo/techno piece (?)!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Too much 3D, too little variation.

@EndNode


@Node "DalaHorse" "Dala Horse / Razor 1911"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Dala Horse
@{B}Group:@{UB} Razor 1911

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} Didn't compete (by unknown reasons)

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.43 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ? 
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030 or '040 (if it runs on '040)

@{B}Code:@{UB} Hammer, Psionic
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Diesel8, D-Design
@{B}Music:@{UB} Lizardking, D-Design, Mantronix
@{B}Design:@{UB} Razor 1911

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Some nice routines, fine transitions, good music and graphics
- Torusses, the design is sometimes "out of key", some low-res parts

@{B}Comment:@{UB} There are a number of unanswered questions concerning this demo,
 and I'm afraid I can't answer them myself. But at least I could ask them:
 Why didn't this fine demo not compete in the Assembly demo compo? Did it
 compete at Remedy same year instead? How much of this demo is animations?
 What is a horse when it is `dala', or hasn't it anything to do with
 horses? Will this demo be the reason for more questions asked in the
 future? Well, now that is done let's take a look at the demo itself.
 First of all, this production is good craftmanship. The code is good, the
 graphics is good (even though some of the background could be better), the
 music is good (gets better and better during the demo, especially the
 end-part music by Mantronix and Lizardking is good. Unfortunately there
 seems to be a few timing-problems), there are some good (and a few bad)
 transitions. The design is okay too, but more work with the colors
 wouldn't do any harm.
 The show starts with a very nice drawing of a face that looks as if it was
 drawn with color pencils. In front of this flies a big gourad shaded torus
 (it's a bit buggy). Afterwards the authors are presented with nicely
 designed credits pictures, which are followed by A big texture mapped
 morphing box. A Razor logo appears in an interesting way in the bottom of
 the screen and is doing interesting things, while the box morphs from box
 to six small boxes. On next is a torus with a red surface in different
 shades (texture mapping I believe). Both speed and resolution is okay,
 which goes for the next routine aswell, a transparent texture mapped
 3D-box. A beautiful girls-picture (that is also shown later in the demo)
 by D-Design is used as texture on most of the sides, while another picture
 is used on the rest (a face). And it's all transparent. Very nice. The
 next one is a quite interesting one, it's some kind of tunnel routine. Or
 is it an animation? The display is not perfect (a variation of
 blitterscreen where every second line is diplaced a pixel), but when the
 routine starts you forget that rather quickly. In the beginning it almost
 looks like a fractal, but when you start to fly through one small tunnel
 after another located in what looks like small mountains you realize that
 it is probably not. A fast '030 should be able to run this smoothly
 (unless it's an animation!). A texture mapped plate and a ball is what the
 next effect consists of. The plate is seen from an oblique angle, slowly
 spinning around, when a ball is suddenly dropped on it and is bounced back
 by the elastic plate. Maybe seen before, but rarely as well coded as this
 I guess. And as if this wasn't enough the plates disappears and the ball
 falls down into the blue background, and we discover that it is water, and
 is rewarded with a beautiful circular wave (the resolution is a bit low,
 though). Three gouraud-shaded pyramids that flies through each other is
 presented next, when another ball (or maybe the same as from before) joins
 them. Soon after the pyramids disappears and the ball is wrapped into the
 nice girls-picture also used on a cube earlier in the demo. More 3D is on
 next, this time three env-mapped rings, followed by a phong mapped
 Razor-logo. These 3D-objects are rather slow, but the resolution is 1x1.
 What happens next is rather strange, because the picture used as
 background for the 3D-routines are slowly replaced by a quite ugly
 picture, about 20-30 lines at a time. Maybe some kind of alternative
 fractal calculation routine? This ugly picture is bounced away to one
 side, and another ugly one (very low resolution too) that could look like
 a tunnel is on instead. In front of this a slow, env-mapped 3D-blob
 enters. I can't really explain the low framerate, they were doing so
 relatively well with the previous objects... Anyway, the blob passes the
 screen, and when it's gone the background that looks like a tunnel shows
 to be a tunnel. Actually more like a maze. The low resolution and the bad
 choice of colors here does that you aren't really blown away by this
 effect, but it's quite good anyway. After this tunnel trip a strange
 3D-box with RGB-interference in it is shown, looks different, but nice.
 And finally one of the strangest routines ever is presented (and once
 again I ask: Is this an animation?). It's hard to explain it, of course,
 but imagine some colored water in slow motion that are spinning around
 the same point, and at the same time disappears and reappears (a bit like
 inflating a ballon and then let the air out again). All in 3D. Looks very
 cool! A short scrolltext (with some strange statements in it) is on as the
 last part of the demo.
 The music is rather traditional Lizardking-style demo music with a touch
 of techno, and the one in the end-part is a silent synth tune, a good one
 too.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A demo with many different and interesting effects,
 good graphics and music and mostly nice design. Watch it!

@EndNode


@Node "Driidirijia" "Driidirijia / Ephidrena"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Driidirijia
@{B}Group:@{UB} Ephidrena

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering (maybe)
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 7 of 10 (maybe)

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.9 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, probably more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '040 or '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} Cyberstarr, Loaderror
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cheetah, Stoney
@{B}Music:@{UB} Frequent
@{B}Additional work@{UB}: Zixaq

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Nice design, graphics and routines, excellent transitions
- Needs a lot of CPU power, it's a bit short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This nice demo begins with a wallwrap routine that unlike others
 of its kind also waves up and down here and there. In front of it the
 credits are shown. Then a pulsating ball-like thing is on, most likely
 made from a plasma routine, texture mapped. A bright light shines from its
 center, and when we zoom closer into it there somehow appears a bunch of
 small light balls forming a circular pattern appears, a very nice routine
 with a very nice transition. Of course these balls of light is
 accompagnied by a wallwrap routine in the background and a stylish picture
 covering just a part of the screen as middleground. Another picture is on
 afterwards, a comical one by Stoney that doesn't fit the demo at all. A
 shame to use such a picture in this demo. Next routine is some quite slow
 flat plains, floor and ceiling, with a partly transparent picture of a
 lady (of course?) in the foreground. Nice, but needs some CPU power.
 A tunnel routine is presented to is next, together with a Ephidrena logo,
 phong shaded. The logo disappears and a lot of small texture mapped
 fragments appears. These fragments is put together and you see that they
 all together makes a picture (of a woman...). Really nice! The tunnel
 can still be seen through the picture as it is transparent. Finally the
 picture is shown without any interference in the background and the demo
 ends.
 The music is industrial drum'n'bass with sounds that sounds as if the
 sample rate ought to be at least the double. But I guess it fits the demo
 okay.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Rather short, but nice, especially if you've got a fast
 processor.

@EndNode


@Node "Neo" "Neo / Darkage"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Neo
@{B}Group:@{UB} Darkage

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Italian Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 3!

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.53 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060
@{B}Note:@{UB} A special version for graphic boards is said to be released later,
 this version will also be bugfixed

@{B}Code:@{UB} Modem, Dip, Washburn
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} DeciBel, Orome, Modem Kaosmaster
@{B}Music:@{UB} Nork
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Washburn, Modem
@{B}Text:@{UB} Gandy
@{B}Design:@{UB} Modem

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some nice routines, beautiful pictures, fitting music
- Needs a lot of CPU power, short

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A nice, but short and CPU hungry demo from the Italian based
 group Darkage. The short length can easily be explained: It is made in
 only five days before TIG (or at least that's what they say)! Very
 impressive I must say. Of course you can see that it's made in quite a
 hurry, but only on it's length actually. It simply stops quite early.
 The design is pretty good, the colors well chosen (maybe except for the
 last routine, a fast, texture mapped 3D tunnel), and there even is a nice
 transition in it. But on the other hand it requires a '060 to run smoothly.
 Let's have a look at the effects: The first one is a text blur effect that
 present some text in the beginning of the demo. The text is blured away
 on the x-axis only, looks very nice. At the same time the music starts, a
 piece of slow techno that gives you time to hear the details in it and
 fits the demo well. The shaking credits are presented next with a rather
 slow voxel tunnel in the background. The title picture, which is pretty
 nice, is on next. A transition leads us to a nice, and fast, routine that
 includes both some phong objects and a texture mapped background that is
 deformed. It is "sucked in" one place and "spit out" another forming a
 circular, symmetric pattern. A beautiful picture by Orome is shown
 afterwards, that man really got some talent! Next routine isn't very nice,
 at least in my opinion. It's some kind of texture mapped flatscape with
 peaks sticking up everywhere, so that it looks as if you are moving
 through a small canyon. The texture is made so that it looks bumpmapped,
 but the illusion doesn't work very good, and one could believe that it
 was a voxelscape with problems keeping it up. On the contrary the
 following scene is something: It's some kind of 3D-scene where the
 "camera" is pointed towards a certain point, a green, bumpy background
 with blocks of stone flying in front of it. These stones form a circle
 and are soon afterwards used as scrolltext writer. Very nice, and very
 CPU hungry! Another one of Orome's beauties is on (yes, another naked
 girl), and finally the fast 3D-tunnel that is mentioned earlier ends the
 demo.
 An odd way to end a demo with a fast moving tunnel, but you can't really
 expect much more from Darkage when it's put together in five days.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Worth watching, could have been a hit if they'd spend some
 more time on it!

@EndNode


@Node "Partyhall" "PartyHall / Oxyron"

@{B}Name:@{UB} PartyHall
@{B}Group:@{UB} Oxyron

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Symposium
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 7 of 14

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.83 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} TTS
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mad Hexroom
@{B}Music:@{UB} Parsec/Elven 11

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---
§
+ Made at the party place, you are able to control it a little
- CPU hungry, monotone

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Have you ever been to Symposium? Now you got the chance! This
 little demo is, as the title suggest, the Symposium Party hall remodelled
 in 3D. Complete with tables, organizer booth, big screen (presenting
 credits), loud speakers, etc., but without any computers there (must be
 before the party started). Also a few people is there - strange, seems to
 be the same character all over the place... Actually there's a scene more
 in the beginning of the demo, one featuring lightsources and mirrors.
 Nice, but slow. To speed up you can change from the 1x1 resolution to 1x2,
 or change the display area (not documented in the readme-file).
 However, the fact about this demo is that it is monotone. Well, it is
 impressive that it was put together on the party place, but it doesn't
 make it nice. A plus is that you are able to control a bit of the demo
 using mouse and/or keyboard to control the camera. You can point it in
 different directions - not up and down though - but it tends to move back
 to its original position immediately.
 The music is a quite silent piece of techno, not really anything and keeps
 looping in the end.

@{B}Note:@{UB} The keyboard controls found are:
 Left/right: Arrow keys
 Jump: A
 Target: I
 Strange numbers: `Del'
 Resolution: F1
 Display area: Keys no. 2 and 3 to the left of backspace (next to 0)
 Quit: F5

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} It's much more fun to be there for real!

@EndNode


@Node "Dimensions" "Dimensions / Role"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Dimensions
@{B}Group:@{UB} Role

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Wired
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 1...

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.82 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, '020 or better, lots of Chip-RAM (about 2 MB), 8 MB
 fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040
@{B}Note:@{UB} There are some bugs: The music may be a little out of sync. Under
 OS 3.1 the interlace pictures are not displayed properly.

@{B}Code:@{UB} MVOOVEK/Candid
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} "G", The Chronic
@{B}Music:@{UB} Vip
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Zuber/Role^Candid

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Very interesting credits routine
- Everything is pretty average or below, contains some bugs

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A very average production that may be able to entertain you
 once, but not twice. The show begins with some stripes that looks like
 falling rain. In front of it some text and the title are shown. Some very
 gloomy tunes are heard. After that we are suddenly in space, in our solar
 system to be precise. We fly around the texture mapped Mother Earth, the
 sun and also get to see the moon. The planets are shaded so that the side
 that is not facing the sun is dark, but I don't know if this is fake. The
 most interesting about is all, I guess, is actually the stars in the
 background. Everytime we move they get a tail after each one of them. This
 is not a blur routine as it isn't fading away smoothly, it just disappear
 when it has reached a certain length. Interesting. All in all a little
 more time should have been used to improve this scene. It doesn't move
 steady, the stars jumps up and down everytime there's movement. But it's
 actually an okay routine despite that. The next routine is probably
 supposed to look like the sun seen in profile shooting out flares.
 Actually it's just a variation of the common fire-routines, but a pretty
 good one. Also this routine has its disadvantages though: A dither
 seems to have been used to simulate a lot of colors. That can be seen if
 you look at more than a couple of seconds. And you do, because it's on for
 way to long! Gets really boring. The demo now changes to more common
 routines like phong- and env-objects (including a Win-logo getting flushed
 in a toilet :-)). A '040 is a good idea to display these. Last effect
 before the end credits is a Role picture that is exposed to a lightsource
 and some bubbles or bumps floating above it making interesting distortion.
 This routine isn't perfect either as you can see that the bubbles aren't
 circular, they've got a square base. The credits part is really
 interesting. Actually it's just another lightsource routine, but the way
 it's made makes it different. The lightsource is a burning torch, and the
 credits are carved into a wall. May not sound that interesting, but see
 for yourself.
 The music isn't good. The atmosphere is there, but the technical
 perfomance is another story. The genre is gloomy, movie-like sound, but it
 fails because of lack of quality. The graphics are a mixed pleasure, some
 pretty good (not fantastic), some defective.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a must, needs lots of small improvements

@EndNode


@Node "Zoom" "Zoom / Anadune"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Zoom
@{B}Group:@{UB} Anadune

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 5

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.64 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, probably more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} Mr. Acryl
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} KAZik
@{B}Music:@{UB} 

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice "dark" style, some fast routines, good graphics, fitting music
- Some CPU hungry 3D scenes, too much 3D

@{B}Comment:@{UB} As always with Anadune demos this one starts with presenting
 the almighty Anadune logo. And soon after the show begins for real. Many
 nice routines, graphics and some fitting music are included in the demo,
 all designed in a quite gloomy, dark style. That doesn't mean mood from
 hell or Death is knocking on your door-atmosphere, it means that the
 colors are kept down at a low intensity-level. Maybe you wonder about the
 title, and after seeing the demo you'll probably not be any wiser. The
 only real zoom in the demo is in the beginning when an Anadune picture is
 zooms away and the title picture is zoomed towards you. A fast zoom
 routine that is. In front of this title picture an env-mapped phong blobs
 appears, and soon after the next effect is on. It's an interesting, weird
 thing, a combination of twirling plasma and a tunnel routine. Actually
 there are two texture mapped plasma-like things that make the illusion of
 a tunnel, looks cool! Coming up next is another 3D-blob, this one with a
 texture that fakes a bumpmap, and suddenly it is morphed into a fungus!
 The routine is quite fast, and like everything else it runs in 1x1
 resolution. At this point in the demo the first of three 3D-scenes
 appears. Actually this one is just a bunch of different texture mapped
 objects assembled in empty space, and it really needs a '060 or similar
 to run at an acceptable frame rate I suppose. Furthermore it's on for too
 long, halve the time would have been enough. A very nice and atmospheric
 picture is shown afterwards, which is followed by the next 3D-scene. It's
 just as slow as the previous one, but more elegant and much shorter. A
 submarine is flying (?) through a landscape of small mountains with the
 sky in the background that is covered with stars. More 3D is following
 this scene, another texture mapped blob with a background that looks like
 a tunnel. And suddenly it moves, it is a tunnel! Looks nice. The last
 3D-scene in this demo is a city in space, quite nice without too many
 details, though. Anyway, fascinating. Another fine picture is presented
 to us afterwards with a Manga-style woman in the foreground. A variation
 of the plasma-twirl tunnel is on the screen as the next effect, and Acryl
 has even put a phong blob in front of it this time. It even runs okay on
 a fast '030! The demo ends with a nice credit picture, and (of course?)
 a env-blob flying around in the foreground. And finally there's what
 looks like a textscreen (it's actually a picture).
 The music is a quite quiet drum'n'bass/industrial techno piece that goes
 well together with the visuals.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Too much 3D, but with a nice style. Have a look!

@EndNode


@Node "1994" "1994 / Ram Jam"

@{B}Name:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Group:@{UB} Ram Jam

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1994
@{B}Event:@{UB} American Ram Jam New Year Party (1993-1994)
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.4 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Not much

@{B}Code:@{UB} Booger
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Pedro, Deus, Rip
@{B}Music:@{UB} Executor

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ A pretty good picture, low system requirements...
- Few routines, bad remixed and ripped music, boring add, some ugly
  pictures

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A little production to celebrate the new year 1993-1994.
 I sure hope that the party was better than this intro/demo is. It contains
 only few routines, pictures that besides one are rather bad, and music
 that are mainly stolen from the master Jean-Michel Jarre's Chronologie
 Album (Chronologie Part 4 to be precise) and remixed it a bit. The version
 in this demo is technically bad performed, sounds more like chip than
 music and is not really worth hearing. The effects in the demo are a big
 blocky sinus-scroller (saying "HAPPY NEW YEAR!), a pretty nice HAM-plasma
 and a very low resolution zoom-rotator that is mirrored. Last one is
 displayed in a very small area of the screen with a scrolltext below it.
 Also there are some standard transitions here and there, the way they are
 used is not very well done, though. A plus is that you can click the
 mouse during most of the routines to proceed to the next one.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Avoid this, it isn't worth it

@EndNode


@Node "Pulstar" "Pulstar / Abyss"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Pulstar
@{B}Group:@{UB} Abyss

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995 (probably)
@{B}Event:@{UB} ? (maybe The Party 5)
@{B}Placing:@{UB} Probably did not compete

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.36 MB
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Moon
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Celtic
@{B}Music:@{UB} Substance

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice routines, trancing music
- Gets boring, few routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} This demo is very different from most other demos. It contains
 just about two different routines, a color zoomer and a distorted texture
 rotator (not to forget the nice and - in opposition to the other effects -
 1x1 resolution wave distortion of a nice logo picture in the beginning of
 the demo), and especially the first one, combined with the music, create
 a unique atmosphere. As the title suggest it's some music with pulse in
 it, and the pulstar sound is also what makes the music so special. It
 starts with these pulsating synth sound, and slowly more instruments and
 rhythm are added giving a trancing effect together with the spinning
 visuals. The variation is not big, on the contrary, but if you're captured
 by the trance mood this demo is a hit - if not it's dull...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Give it a try, it just might save your day!

@EndNode


@Node "Invasion" "Invasion / Ukonx"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Invasion
@{B}Group:@{UB} Ukonx

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} RTS
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1

@{B}Size:@{UB} 8.2 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} 1.7 MB chip-RAM, maybe more 
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030

@{B}Code:@{UB} Deemphasis
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Unison, Deemphasis
@{B}Music:@{UB} Unison

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Some kind of humor (?), two good pictures
- Most of it is pretty average or below average

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The Earth may be invaded by little green men someday, but it
 sure ain't gonna be the ones from Ukonx! They simply haven't got what it
 takes, they have no kind of appeal to draw attention. Well, maybe except
 for the short parts when they disquise as Lego®-figures, that is the
 resolution is very low, and dance (two ar three frames animation). One
 might think of Three little Elks' @{" The Tribe " link "TheTribe"} when watching
 these little ugly aliens, but 3le's elks are a lot more interesting!
 Luckily the aliens only take up a small amount of time in the demo, their
 spaceships are much worse. It's a 3D space scene where you see a simple
 flying saucer that lands on a planet, the aliens get out. Later a bomb is
 droppen on them... The part where the saucer flies are quite long, but it
 gives the time to present the credits. Also, the technical side of this
 part is not too good, luckily the routines in part two are better, but the
 resolution is a bit low. And there aren't many of them: Phong in space,
 plasma (the kind with two "centers" flying around) that changes its color
 constantly, and a hi-color transparent text greetings effect, just to
 mention most of them. Two good pictures are presented in the demo, the
 intro picture and one that has absolutely nothing to do with the theme
 (presenting a woman of course). However, they are both well drawn.
 The music in the first part are at first (in space) atmospheric tunes,
 more work on these would have created a more dense atmosphere, and later
 when the aliens dance it's an old radio hit that drives you nuts after a
 while. In the second part it's a piece of techno with an aggresion hidden
 somewhere in it. Sounds pretty good. The demo ends with a 3D-scene where
 you see a lot of saucers flying towards Earth. Time for the invasion.
 Finally, I'd like to add that by clicking the mouse you can actually skip
 the long 3D-sequence, but then there isn't much of the demo left.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not recommended, the humor fails - the show gets dull

@EndNode


@Node "ScreamThyLastScream" "Scream Thy Last Scream / Mankind"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Scream Thy Last Scream
@{B}Group:@{UB} Mankind

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1997
@{B}Event:@{UB} Saturne Party 5
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.77 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030

@{B}Code:@{UB} Krabob, Redshift
@{B}Music:@{UB} Tex

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Good code
- Bad music, strange design, too little variation, crashes if it runs out
  of memory

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Once again Krabob proves that he is one of the best coders
 around. Unfortunately this demo does not live up to Krabob's standards,
 thanks to the lack of design and the very strange music that is not timed
 with the rest of the show very well.
 There's a lot of 3D in this short demo, all of it (without exception) is
 texture mapped. Quite a task to make it all run quickly, but due to the
 resolution that is a bit low, and good code work, everything runs fine on
 a fast '030 I guess. What you find in the demo is lots of different plasma
 in different colors, zooming and transparent words and names in front of
 the effects (impressive!), water-like background with silly 2D-brushes
 in front of them being manipulated, and of course the small 3D-scenes with
 wallwrap background and flat, wrenching and twisting things splashing down
 on a plate below them. Cool code! However, the colors used look like a
 modern painting painted by a colorblind artist (at least they don't match
 each other well), and the techno-like music is not a pleasant surprise,
 not even for the trained ear. But at least it's different...
 
@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Turn down the volume and have a look. Once.

@EndNode


@Node "BoogienightsSpedes" "Boogienights / Spedes"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Boogienights
@{B}Group:@{UB} Spedes

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 6 of 7

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.97 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Don't know. Maybe no more than OCS chips?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} No

@{B}Code:@{UB} Nakathappura, Kortsu
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Spede, Kortsu
@{B}Music:@{UB} Kortsu

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ It was probably fun to create
- It surely isn't fun to watch!

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The crazy Spedes team was not succesful in reaching the bottom
 of the demo compo at Assembly this time, even though they were close (I've
 problems imagining the one that got placed at the last placing!).
 This disco "demo" contains very little code, lots of 32 color graphics and
 scans and disco music - a mix of the good old disco hits. The most
 interesting about it all is that many of the pictures used in the demo is
 not packed or decrypted, meaning that you can have a look at them with a
 standard IFF-viewer. The interesting part about this is that you can see
 how Spedes has created a very psychedelic background effects with just a
 couple of strange pictures. And that's not too interesting... This demo
 could easily have been made in a demomaker, and it probably is.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Avoid!

@EndNode


@Node "Wildlife" "Wildlife / Abyss"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Wildlife
@{B}Group:@{UB} Abyss

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 8
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.37 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020, AGA, 3 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz, and '040 for the last routine

@{B}Code:@{UB} Pink, Kustom
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cyclone, Judas, Pink
@{B}Music:@{UB} Moby & Pink

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ***-

+ Great design, original routines, well coded, nice graphics
- Lacks transitions, some (compared to the standard) simple routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} The best about this demo is that it is designed a way that
 have probably never been seen before. The routines are still tunnels, 3D
 stuff and zoom-rotators, but the way they are made, and the way the design
 around them is made makes a really big difference. Let's start at the
 beginning:
 Like in most movies the credits are presented as the first thing. Using a
 zoom-rotator. You may wonder how you are able to use a such things for
 presenting the author's names, the Abyss gives you the simple, but highly
 innovative answer: Slowly zoom and rotate the names into the matchbox
 shaped showfield. A good routine is required to make this look nice, and
 Abyss has got one that is close to be perfect. Also, the design in this
 first part is something extra ordinary. The style is class `A'! Especially
 the last part of this first part is good, that is when you zoom away from
 the picture and discover that it all together forms the Abyss name, with a
 little helped from letters that are faded on as the big final.
 The demo then continues with a nice piece of funk music, the explanation
 of what wildlife is (you know, trees and stuff), and, in the background,
 strings of strange twisting 3D objects. Looks weird, and very interesting.
 The next routine is cute, but far from impressive. You see a rectangular,
 texture mapped plate from above with 5-6 small balls jumping around on it.
 Everytime the a part of the plate is hit by a ball that part is pushed
 down a bit. Shortly after an exploding Abyss logo disappears, just to
 introducte to you a very interesting tunnel. First of all it's not just
 circular, secondly the view point is placed closed to the wall and floor
 giving it a new perspective, and thirdly the texture is different, made
 by squares in some special way. Also, they manage to have an Abyss logo
 made by small shining pixels flying towards you in this tunnel. To make it
 run smoothly the viewfield is made smaller, but as the borders are nicely
 painted it doesn't really matter. The next couple of routines aren't that
 interesting, but still they possess the high technical standards of the
 previous ones. And besides two nice pictures are shown in between (two of
 the The Party 8 pixel compo pictures, no. 3 by Cyclone and 13 by Judas).
 The routines are a 3D-scrolltext stating that scrollers are outdated (?),
 a strange "jelly" picture reacting according to the music, and a routine
 called unlimited playfields (a lot of small pictures are moving around
 in different planes). A scrolltext is running in the bottom of this
 routine telling that it is a shame that the Amiga has only to playfields,
 in the beginning at least.
 The short and final routine is a reversed pixelstorm drawing an Abyss
 logo, looks really cool if your processor is fast enough. An '040 would
 probably do it.
 The scrolltext in the end managed to keep the The Party visitors
 breathless for a couple of seconds as it stated something like: "This was
 the last Abyss demo". However, shortly after an "In 1998" was added and
 the excited crowd could breath again. Cruel joke, funny afterwards...!
 The end music is good by the way.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} An innovative and recommended demo!

   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Wildlife01.jpg"} Strange curling 3D objects. Great!
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Wildlife02.jpg"} The Abyss logo just before it explodes
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Wildlife03.jpg"} A shot from the excellent intro part
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Wildlife04.jpg"} A new (?) kind of tunnel with the Abyss logo zooming
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Wildlife05.jpg"} Unlimited playfields
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Wildlife06.jpg"} The graphics is nice
   @{"  " system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DemoGuidePics/Wildlife07.jpg"} Everytime a ball hit a plate it's pushed down. Cute!

@EndNode


@Node "Juusto2" "Juusto 2 - The Revenge / Artificial People"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Juusto 2 - The Revenge
@{B}Group:@{UB} Artificial People

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 8
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 8 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.25 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} ?

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Nice (but slow) routines
- Slow (but nice) routines, no design

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A demo that have probably been put together in very little
 time. Basically it's just a bunch of 3D routines, like morphing phong,
 texture mapped blobs and waving plains, shown one by one. The routines are
 nice, though, if you have a fast '060 or similar. Don't try it on less.
 After starting it a little requester pops up asking you to choose
 resolution, the better resolution you choose, the smaller is the display.
 The music is techno with a good beat in it, but like the rest of the demo
 it's somewhat unfinished. There's no graphics in the demo, except for a
 bit of text, including one stating something about the lack of design...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Would have been nice, if they'd put a couple of month of
 work into it. But they didn't.

@EndNode


@Node "DagePown" "Dage Pown / Da Jormas"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Dage Pown
@{B}Group:@{UB} Da Jormas

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.19 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Pekka Pos
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Purakkamunalla
@{B}Music:@{UB} Rekka Poo

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Funny, special Jormas design (but is that good?!)
- Few effects

@{B}Comment:@{UB} As always with Da Jormas demos it doesn't really look like
 anything else (maybe except for Speedes), and as always this one is no
 exception. However, it doesn't look like many of the other Jormas
 productions either, it got its own design and style. That is a '80s
 look-a-like style with clear colors, raster and girls dressed in fancy
 clothes used as decoration. The effects take up very little space on
 screen as they are placed in small fields, typically this is plasmas of
 some kind, texture mapped, twirling, rotating, lightsourced. Sounds pretty
 good, and it is, except for the low number of colors used, 32 that is.
 Another effect is the "morphing". A picture showing for example a face
 which is morphed according to the music (a bit like watching the bass
 moving in a loudspeaker). Quite fun! The music is in a way a disaster,
 in another way a little master piece. It sounds like someone being
 tortured, but fits the demo well. Maybe.
 This demo gets an extra star for its humour and different style!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Recommended for you who like weird, tasteless things!

@EndNode


@Node "Authentik" "Authentik / Skarla"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Authentik
@{B}Group:@{UB} Skarla

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Non
@{B}Placing:@{UB} -

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.89 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Jamie
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Norm
@{B}Music:@{UB} Marvin
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Horus

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Fast code, nice graphics and music, Skarla dance!
- Same texture is used a lot, many similar routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Skarla's first official demo release! And a great one too!
 Jamie (previously Fred) is showing of his coding abilities with some very
 fast routines, Norm has drawn some nice pictures (including a brilliant
 one presenting French actor Gerard Depardieu), Marvin with two quite good
 pieces of funky music, the first improved with a cool electric guitar
 (even though it tends to scream too much), the second with some brilliant
 triphop-like drums. The 3D objects aren't very advanced, it's cubes, balls
 and other simple shapes, but they move very fast, even though they are
 texture mapped most of the time.
 The show starts with a nice picture (some of it might be ripped!),
 followed by the credits with simple vector objects flying in the
 background. The title on afterwards, with another nice picture behind it.
 A red voxel landscape then appears. It's looks smooth and moves very
 smoothly, filled with small hills, but on the other hand the display area
 does not fill out the entire screen, it's square. Next routine demonstrate
 some texture mapped 3D objects, simple ones, but very fast! The texture is
 a teddy bear, which unfortunately is used a lot through the demo. A
 texture plasma that streches and rotates is on next, also fast. More 3D is
 presented next, but this one it's not the object itself, a head, that
 moves, but the colored lightsources around it. Simple, but nice. A big 3D
 ball is on for a short while afterwards (it's really big!), followed by
 the excellent Depardieu picture that introduces us to part 2. This part is
 actually not different from the first part, even though it's a new piece
 of music that is played. For instance a new cube is on, still with teddy
 bears on it, but this time they strech and rotate. Another example of the
 good coding is the 3D water routine afterwards. You see some blue water in
 the lower part of the screen from an oblique angle that waves up and down,
 write different things and so on. Looks really cool and has also been used
 in some of their later demos. A couple of gouraud shaded objects are
 presented next, nothing special today, but then it was something. The
 final effect is one of my all time favorites: The Skarla dance! No, you
 don't see the Skarla team dance, not the persons anyway, you see a
 3D-character build from boxes and triangles dance in a very realistic way.
 It looks really amazing! The only minor complain could be that there's a
 little bug in the Z-buffer, so that it's not always the right part of the
 well animated figure that is in front, but this is not very clear, and
 compared to how great the rest of this effect is it's easy to close your
 eyes for this. A scrolltext ends this Skarla demo.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A good demo. And you just have to see the Skarla dance!!!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} This demo is the first official Skarla demo release.
 However, it is said that they've made a demo before this one, called
 Obsession, that unfortunately is not released. I wonder why.

 Motion capture technique was used to create the Skarla dance (therefore
 the very realistic movement). Acti System is greeted for this in the
 endscroller.

@EndNode


@Node "Disco" "Disco / Drifters"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Disco
@{B}Group:@{UB} Drifters

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Mekka-Symposium
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.85 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} A dance floor

@{B}By:@{UB} ToF, Clary, Falcon, IO

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ It's funky, usual cool Crux/Drifters style
- Only last for one look

@{B}Comment:@{UB} If you know some of the other releases from Drifters, like
 @{" Paradisio " link "Paradisio"} and @{" Refuse " link "Refuse"}, you'll have a pretty good idea of what it is all
 about. Anyway, I'll tell: The "demo" is made of small animations, usually
 no more than 5 frames, that are drawn in a funky cartoon way. The most
 notable about it is the Calvin & Hobbes animation, where they dance.
 Orange is the most common color in the demo, and as the title suggests
 there's a disco party going on. You can both see and hear that!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Nice party, but it doesn't bear a repeatation

@EndNode


@Node "Paloo" "Paloo / Embora"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Paloo
@{B}Group:@{UB} Embora

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Satelite
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.25 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} 1.96 MB Chip-RAM, 8 MB fast-RAM

@{B}By:@{UB} Rakazi, Deixas, Denz

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Fast routines
- After a good start it tends to look old-fashioned

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A demo that could have been something, but instead just became
 another one in the huge pile of average or half-hearted demos. The case is
 that Embora actually starts as if something big is going to happen. At
 first a very fast phong routine is shown, followed by a nice 3D-tunnel
 with colors that slowly change. But after this good beginning the design
 is ruined by less impressive - still entertaining - routines. The first
 one is a vortex distortion routine. "Concentrate on the center" you are
 asked, and after a short while you are ready for an asylum (or at least an
 eye operation). This routine is followed by a picture, but it is not the
 picture itself that is interesting, it's the repercussions of the previous
 effect that is still interesting. It's a bit like being drunk!
 Anyway, next routine is utterly un-interesting, a 3D dot plain with text
 written on it, unreadable by the way, and with nasty colors. This is
 followed by an interesting phong object, still fast, and I think that the
 reason for the great speed must be the low amount of colors used. However,
 it still looks good, the shading is just a bit different. At this point in
 the demo it starts to go really downhill: A low-res texture zoomer is on
 followed by a sequence of fast changes of some of the previous effects,
 plus a couple of pictures. Gives nothing to the demo but confussion.
 The music is drum'n'bass, heard too many times before in too many demos,
 but technically it's fine.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a must see, but the phong (and partly the vortex)
 is worth having a look at.

@EndNode


@Node "Riot" "Riot / Appendix"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Riot
@{B}Group:@{UB} Appendix

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Gravity
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 5.28 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, '020, 8 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060

@{B}Code:@{UB} Informer
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Slayer, Cooper, Mag666
@{B}Music:@{UB} Pic Saint Loup
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Madbart

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice (but slow) routines, good techno music
- Needs lots of CPU power, quite short, too much 3D

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A demo that really prefers a fast processor to run smoothly,
 but if you got that it's quite nice. However, it contains a lot of 3D,
 which may be rather boring in the long run. Actually there's only two or
 three routines besides the different 3D-scenes. These are some nice
 plasma, a blur routine that are used to erase the intro-letters - it works
 on the x-axis only, and a colorful bumpmap routine that - except for the
 low resolution - is enjoyable. Oh yes, I forgot the cool free direction
 tunnel. That one is also a hit, but as most of the other routines CPU
 hungry. It's the kind of tunnel that bends it walls to become shaped as a
 flower, and with a couple of flares flying around in it. A few pictures
 are also in the demo, non of them anything special. The music, however, is
 a good piece of techno, and even though it isn't timed well to the demo it
 fits the show. What is "wrong" about this demo are the many and too long
 3D-scenes. They've been seen before, faster, more beautiful and with more
 effects in them. If they were cut out the demo would be real short, but,
 in my opinion, more entertaining. The design helps a little, but as an
 overall it doesn't really work.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Nothing special to come after here

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} This demo is the last production from Informer under
 the Appendix label (he, Superfml and Flapjack left Appendix due to lack of
 communication).
 The demo should have been released at Intel Outside 5 (but wasn't!).

@EndNode


@Node "Omnipotent" "Omnipotent / Tulou"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Omnipotent
@{B}Group:@{UB} Tulou

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Hackersnight
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.89 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030

@{B}Code:@{UB} Strangelove, Razorback
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Razorback
@{B}Music:@{UB} Temal

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some good pictures and routines, stylish theme
- Strange design, few routines, some of it looks unfinished

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I suppose that a deadline prevented this demo from being
 finished, or at least from being well timed. Some of the routines are on
 for just a short period of time, while others last for ages (almost).
 Also, the pictures in the demo (that are, as everything else in the demo,
 satanistic) is shown with only a short interval between them, that's the
 way to do it in a slideshow, not a demo. The satan-theme is presented
 mainly using the pictures (plus a little animation), but also the
 predominant color design leads your thoughts in that direction.
 The effects are a texture mapped cube that spells TULOU in the beginning.
 A 3D texture mapped tunnel. A lot of pierced 3D layers, also texture
 mapped (this effect looks really great, but is also CPU hungry). Something
 that looks like a walking person seen from above, but the colors are very
 dark in this part, so it is difficult to decide what exactly is going on.
 Some different zooming effects, including the credits part. A gouraud
 shaded morphing torus to ball object that moves incredibly slow across the
 screen (yawn). The longer you get through the demo, the less effects and
 the more pictures are there. Generally the speed drops in the end untill
 it stops completely with a picture and the greetings...
 The music is some kind of heavy rock that tries to underline the satan-
 theme, and even though it's partly succeeds the demo doesn't benefit much
 from it due to the lack of raw power and true aggressions.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Looks unfinished, but some of it is nice.

@EndNode


@Node "Enigma" "Enigma / Phenomena"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Enigma
@{B}Group:@{UB} Phenomena

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.9 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} OCS or better, to install on HD you need a fix
@{B}Note:@{UB} As the demo is developed for the 68000 only problems may occur
 if you run it on other MCs. Disabling the caches might help to solve the
 problem.

@{B}Code:@{UB} Azatoth
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Uno/Scoopex, Terminator
@{B}Music:@{UB} Firefox, Tip

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Nice design, smooth effects, nice graphics, great soundtrack
- Simple 3D scenes

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A true classic! One that even today is worth having a look at,
 even though it's old.
 Firefox and Tip's excellent soundtrack and a 3D starfield with credits in
 front of it introduces us to the show, followed by the unreadable title
 picture. First real effect is a smooth cube that is constantly commented
 on by the scrolltext below it. The cube after a while reveals different
 effects running on its sides, very nice, even though it's "just" simple
 line objects and filled vector. The "Trip to Mars" sequence is, I guess,
 one of the most well known 3D scenes in the Scene history. It's not
 advanced in any way, it's just plain vector graphics and 3D objects, but
 it was one of the first of it's kind. The scene that comes afterwards is
 not as big as the Mars scene, but on the other hand it's light sourced,
 looks nice. Phenomena then break the dot-ball record by presenting a ball
 consisting of 800 dots rotating on all three axis. After this two other
 balls are shown (do not misunderstand!), one made of lines and another one
 that is lightsourced filled vector. As the next effect the "impossible"
 Star Wars scroller is on (you know, text in space seen from an oblique
 angle flying away from you) is shown, followed by a very impressive
 raytraced animation featuring more raytracing effects than I'll mention
 here. Anyway, it's a long line of green balls that are reflected in a
 fractal beneath them. Looks great!
 In the end of the demo there's a some textscreens that sweeps away some
 rumours about Phenomena. If you have got a fixed version of the demo you
 can even quit it, and scroll faster through the different parts. If not
 the magic reset function is the only way back to reality!
 

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} A classic that should be in your collection for sure!

@EndNode


@Node "Foam" "Foam / Corrosion"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Foam
@{B}Group:@{UB} Corrosion

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Scene Strike 3
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1 of 3

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.19 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '060, fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Suffocator
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Marcus Garvey, Asarhad
@{B}Music:@{UB} Asarhad, Dominator

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ It has style to a certain extend
- Gets boring, needs lot of CPU power, few routines

@{B}Comment:@{UB} If this really is the winner of Scene Strike 3 I don't want
 to see the runner ups! And it is, even though it's not that good. Most of
 the time is spend watching morphing, blured grids or big, blured dots,
 which actually looks okay if you've got a fast machine ('060 should do
 it), but when more or less the same routines are used again they are
 unable to get your attension. The nice, "digital" atmosphere that is build
 up in the demo's beginning doesn't last either, partly because of the
 dullness, but also because of the few other effects uses a completely
 different set of colors. In the last minutes of the demo the pace drops
 even further when some average pictures are shown for a long time, and
 the dance techno music is far from able to get the demo alive. It sounds
 okay in the beginning (a silent part), but when the beat starts kicking
 you loose your interest quite fast.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} At first it's a positive surprise, but it doesn't last for
 long.

@EndNode


@Node "Kicker" "Kicker - Wannabe 2 / Nature"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Kicker - Wannabe 2
@{B}Group:@{UB} Nature

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Gathering
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 10 of 10 (probably)

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.83 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020>, AGA, 3.5 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030
@{B}Note:@{UB} Crashes after exit on my system. The 3D-scene is faster on an
 '030 than on an '060!

@{B}Code:@{UB} Pezac, Yomat, Pipe
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Yomat, Pipe
@{B}Music:@{UB} Pipe, C-Frog
@{B}Design:@{UB} Pezac

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ A few nice routines, a cute endscroller
- Seems unfinished, low resolution sometimes, changing style

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A gloomy basement. Grey walls, grey floor, grey ceiling. A
 Kinder egg. ... Nature's humor speaks for itself, the weird combination of
 an atmospheric (but technically bad) tune, a 3D-scene that is said to run
 slower on an '060 than on an '030, and a chocolate egg that should have
 been presented at a Kindergarten party! Anyway, the scene is okay coded,
 but not perfect, and even presents a rotating 3D-cube.
 After this first part the demo continues with the second part (!).
 Blur-blobs forms two words that together with an ugly titel picture starts
 the show for real. Next up is a nice, but low-res wire frame effect that
 simply shows a lightly blured 3D-landscape. The display is a bit weird,
 but besides that it actually looks really good. Then a beautiful bumpmap
 is presented, actually two of them. At the same time, meaning that they
 are partly transparent. This routine is really smooth, one of the best
 ever seen of its kind! After the presentation of a traced picture a set
 of light balls are shown (in low resolution), they suck pretty much and is
 kind of a contrast to the nice bumpmap. The greetings that follows this
 part is shown using a plasma/wave effect that is quite nice. Also, the
 next routine is nice, but low-res. It's no less than four 3D objects
 moving smoothly on an '030/50 MHz, very nice despite the 2x2 resolution.
 The credits part is just as cool as the bumpmap effect. It's a spotlight
 routine that light up the letters from behind, so that you're blinded by
 the light except for the places where the letters are. Unfortunately most
 of the names are unreadable, but who cares when they are presented later
 anyway? The music in the demo's main part is a combination of breakbeat
 techno and synthesizer melodies, and C-Frog is not very succesful with
 this combination. Nor is Pipe who've made the rest of the tunes.
 The endpart is really cute: Four smoking smileys, representing each of
 the authors, are talking to each other. Each of them are standing next to
 scrolltext-slider that show what they are saying. Cute.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Some good (certain effects), some bad (music).

@EndNode


@Node "PlanetA" "Planet A. / Drifters & Crux"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Planet A.
@{B}Group:@{UB} Drifters & Crux

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Belgian Scene Event
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.98 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Fast-RAM I guess

@{B}Code:@{UB} ?
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} T0F, Sweet, Clary, Grey, Gam, Overaga
@{B}Music:@{UB} Demon, BMP

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ Cute
- Technically not very good, bad sound quality

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Another party, another Strange Drifters release! This one is
 technically the worst so far. There's no real code in the "demo", all that
 happen is that some small animations and a piece of music that sounds like
 a French song for children is played. The sound quality is low, as it is a
 sample that is played, not a module or similar. The animations, however,
 are simple, but quite cute, and T0F has made a very fine picture that
 doesn't really fit into everything else in the "demo", but it's very nice.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For Drifters fans only!

@EndNode


@Node "Radiation" "Radiation / Vertical Syndicate"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Radiation
@{B}Group:@{UB} Vertical Syndicate

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} Votice Party
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 3 (unfinished version)

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.66 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020>, AGA, 4 or 8 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} Fast '030

@{B}Code:@{UB} Lazy Jones
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ID
@{B}Music:@{UB} Storm, Bomber
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Titt

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Highly energetic
- Messy design, generally average work

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A nice debut demo for Vertical Syndicate, who've chosen the
 "easy way" by creating a demo that runs at a tremendous speed, really
 showing a lot of not too advanced routines in a short period of times.
 However, non of them are ugly in any way. The hard techno music supports
 the impetuous visuals well, and the graphics (that originally are drawn in
 ECS mode, later converted to AGA) really looks radioactive. The display is
 quite buggy, though, as the hi-res lace pictures is quite "jumpy".
 The routines are, among others, some transparent, non-moving 3D-object
 with a moving background behind them, voxel, bumpmap, starfields and
 gouraud shading. It's all mixed together in this radioactive production
 giving a very mixed experience, some would say confusing. On the other
 hand you are not bored for a moment.
 The end part is a scrolltext with a picture and another 3D-starfield in
 the background.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not a must see, quite average with ups and downs.

@{B}Inside information:@{UB} The idea for this demo was developed in 1996.
 However, two years passed before it became a reality.
 Lazy Jones took the demo to a compo even though it wasn't finished, while
 the others was boozing... Later it was finished anyway.
 The graphics are AGA-nized, originally it was in ECS.
 It's Vertical Syndicates first demo.

@EndNode


@Node "Jul" "Jul / Latex"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Jul
@{B}Group:@{UB} Latex

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.47 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Omen
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Lunix
@{B}Music:@{UB} Omen

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ----

+ Not much, maybe the bumpmap-like routine
- Everything

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Another demo made in less than an hour, featuring bad effects,
 graphics and music, and generally sucks a lot. However, the intention with
 the "demo" is good: To wish you a merry Advent. It's all in Danish though,
 non-Scandinavians may have a hard time decoding the message.
 Anyway, I'll mention the effects just to please any curious readers: One
 lowres shadebob routine, one bumpmap-like routine using very few colors,
 and... That's that. The music is horrible, Christmas carols exposed to
 electric drumbeat.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} The X-mas is better without this!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB}
 "Jul" means "X-mas" in Danish.
 The demo was coded in about 35 minutes (they claim. I believe them).

@EndNode


@Node "Bath2" "Take a bath with Tulou 2 / Tulou"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Take a bath with Tulou 2
@{B}Group:@{UB} Tulou

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 8
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 9 of 13

@{B}Size:@{UB} 3.87 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} AGA, maybe more
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '040

@{B}Code:@{UB} Papa Todi
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} ?
@{B}Music:@{UB} Reflect

@{B}Rating:@{UB} *---

+ One nice, but slow plasma
- Slow code, more a slideshow than a demo, takes up a lot of HD space

@{B}Comment:@{UB} I suppose this production is about releasing something, rather
 than releasing something worth watching. Because it isn't worth watching.
 Actually it's more a slideshow than a demo. The pictures are photographs
 presenting the Tulou members (I presume) doing different things, for
 example bathing in a lake. There are two routines in the demo, both slow,
 but one of them nice anyway. That one is a double plasma, looks a bit like
 (but just a tiny bit) if you blend oil and water, except for the colors.
 The other routine is a very slow, simple, heavily blured wireframe object.
 Not exactly impressive.
 The music is funk, not bad, but nothing special either.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Don't take a bath with Tulou

@EndNode


@Node "JulemandensSidsteFerie" "Julemandens Sidste Ferie / Loonies"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Julemandens Sidste Ferie
@{B}Group:@{UB} Loonies

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1998
@{B}Event:@{UB} The Party 8
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 13 of 13...

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.06 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020>, AGA, 2 MB fast-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz

@{B}Code:@{UB} Psycho
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Laika, Bifrost, Blueberry
@{B}Music:@{UB} Puryx/Unique
@{B}Objects:@{UB} Laika

@{B}Rating:@{UB} ----

+ Nice phong, weird humour
- Terrible "music", bad graphics, Danish only

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A two hour production made just before the TP8-deadline. The
 result (13th place of 13) matches the effort put into it, but I guess it
 was fun to make. There's only one routine in it, a nice phong, everything
 else is cartoonish drawings and a terrible cover version of an X-mas
 carol. The most entertaining about the demo is a boy with a goat and Santa
 Claus talking nonsense. And if you like nonsense you should try to read
 the readme-file! Remember, though, that it is Danish, just like the rest
 of the show...

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} May be interesting for hardcore Loonies fans, else avoid!

@{B}Comment:@{UB} A two hour production. It says it all I guess? The only routine
 in this "demo" is a golden phong sleigh. The rest of the time is spend on
 cartoonish pictures of rather low quality and nonsense text in Danish.
 Anyway, it may be quite amusing if you understand Danish (but I think most
 people don't). The music is a horrible remix of a Christmas song.
 Fortunately it's a rather short production. The readme-file tells the
 story of what's happened before we see the demo. Also in Danish of course,
 and also completely nonsense!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Made just before deadline at TP8. It shows! Avoid!

@{B}Inside information:@{UB}
 Made two hours before deadline at The Party 8.
 "Julemandens sidste ferie" means "Santa Claus' last vacation".

@EndNode


@Node "Spectral" "Spectral / The Black Lotus"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Spectral
@{B}Group:@{UB} The Black Lotus

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1996
@{B}Event:@{UB} Creutz
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 1

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.46 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} '020>, AGA, PAL, 2 MB chip-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz, 2 MB fast-RAM

@{B}Code:@{UB} Equalizer, Offa, Noy, Rubberduck
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Cypher, Igloo, Tudor
@{B}Music:@{UB} Azazel

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Some nice and fast routines, catchy tune
- Lacks design, average graphics

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Fascinating how big the difference in quality there are on this
 demo and @{" Tint " link "Tint"} that was released the same year. Spectral is a quite good
 demo, except for the design which is pretty messed up, it's bad!
 The show starts with some lensflare pictures presenting the demos title,
 followed by the credits with giant, green phong objects flying in the
 background in 2x2 resolution. Their speed is amazing, and the resolution
 is not a big problem, it still looks nice. Afterwards a pretty average
 fantasy picture is presenting, and shortly after the very same picture is
 used in a stretching rotator routine. Here the resolution should be better
 as it tends to mess up the picture too much. The next routine is just as
 interesting as it is ugly: A 3D-box with shadebobs on its sides. Also this
 routine wouldn't mind a better resolution, the box looks like a
 flowerpower party place after a while, and that's not a pretty sight.
 Another picture is presented afterwards, and once again the picture is
 used in the following effect: A tunnel routine. Not the traditional
 circular once, a square one with textures on both walls, floor and
 ceiling. It even waves up and down, but not side to side. A similar (and
 more beautiful) can be found in Sanity's Arte. Still, it's nice. A third
 pixelated piece of graphics is showm afterwards (a cute alien), then
 another kind of plasma is presented. It's the kind with its holding point
 in the middle. The waves caused by the plasma goes from the centre, the
 holding point, of the screen to the edges. This routine also features a
 rotater hidden below the plasma. A flatscape with a very ugly texture is
 on as the next effect, then a weird colored torus that causes a stream of
 colors that are zoomed towards you while the torus moves around. The last
 effect is a voxel twister, that is a lump of voxel-like material rising
 from (in this case) the floor of the background picture, spinning around,
 twirls, changes it shape. It's seen from an oblique angle and looks okay.
 The demo ends with a short scrolltext.
 The music is a catchy, funky tune with demo tune elements in it, however,
 I guess it could be catagorized as "demo rock".

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Far from the best TBL demo ever, still it's okay

@EndNode


@Node "BoogieNightsSubspace" "Boogie Nights / Subspace"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Boogie Nights
@{B}Group:@{UB} Subspace

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1976 (!?!)
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 2.62 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} Lots of chip-RAM
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} '030/50 MHz

@{B}By:@{UB} Spite, Desoto, Origo, Zalo

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Disco style!
- Short, the music could be technically better

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Disco demos has been seen before, but I believe Subspace must
 have been the first group to make one, at least if you are to believe the
 year mentioned in the demo: 1976. I'm not sure about the credibility of
 this fact, but the demo's style could convince me (almost). The short show
 starts with a colorcycling, circular background with pulsating letters in
 front of it presenting title and names. Then the first dance sequence is
 on: You see a dancing person in filled 2D vector graphics with big disco
 lights in the background. The movement is realistic (some kind of video
 technique has most likely been used), however, it's not as good as for
 example the ones in @{" Symbolia " link "Symbolia"} by Access or the almightly @{" State of the Art " link "StateOfTheArt"}
 by Spaceballs. Afterwards a phong blob is presented, 1x1 resolution, and
 still pretty fast, and another disco sequence is on afterwards. That's it!
 The backgrounds are stylish, helps creating the right atmosphere, the
 music is mostly a mix of "real life" disco songs, unfortunately the
 technical side of it is poor.
 A shame the demo is so short.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} For disco freaks

@EndNode


@Node "FruitKitchen" "Fruit Kitchen / Silents"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Fruit Kitchen
@{B}Group:@{UB} Silents

@{B}Year:@{UB} 1995
@{B}Event:@{UB} Assembly
@{B}Placing:@{UB} 4 of 15

@{B}Size:@{UB} 1.28 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Crush, Ricky
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Dize, John Doe
@{B}Music:@{UB} Scortia
@{B}Design:@{UB} Crush, Ricky, Martin Groftenhauge

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ All in all a fine demo
- Much 3D, low resolution here and there, not all graphics are good

@{B}Comment:@{UB} One of the "Kitchen" demos, a good one two. The Danish division
 of Silents almost reached a third place at the Assembly party, but was
 short of about 140 points to get it. The demo features a bunch of nice
 effects, much of it vector and 3D stuff, and a good piece of music that is
 hard to put into a category, maybe demo music will do?
 After starting the demo the title is presented with a fruitful Fruit
 Kitchen logo, and the show is continuing with the credits presented in
 front of a pretty fast voxel landscape. The first really impressive
 routine is a disco light ball, normally one of those round, twisting
 spheres with spotlights all over, but this one is a cube with rotating
 eyes on its sides that work as spotlights. Everytime the spot points
 directly towards you, you are blinded. Like all of the other routines this
 one runs smoothly on my '030/40 MHz. Next up is a quite simple 3D scene
 where you fly above a street in a city. What makes this interesting are
 the lamp posts that creates lensflares all over the place, looks nice.
 More 3D is on next, one of the coolest Descent routines at that time to be
 precise, and even today it's quite good except for the low resolution.
 The framerate is high, the camera direction good, the textures maybe a bit
 monotone. After exiting this maze an routine with exploding vector objects
 is on. All of the exploding vectors reveals a new object inside of it, the
 torus in the end doesn't though... All this 3D is interrupted for a short
 while by a low-res plasma, but the resolution somewhat ruins it. Much more
 exciting is the following routine: Small gouraud shaded 3D objects are
 flying around a stillstandin, texture mapped sphere that reflects them.
 Simple, but nice. Bigger objects would be nice though, but on the other
 hand both the resolution and the speed is good. The demo continues with
 flatshaded vector objects casting their shadows on a square plate. The
 demo ends with a scrolltext and the inside of a torus as background (not
 very pretty). Finally there's a commercial for the next Kitchen-demo,
 Blood Kitchen.
 The demo is timed so that you're not bored for a second before a new
 effect takes over. However, you might find all that vector and 3D stuff
 dull in the long run.

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} Not bad, have a look!

@EndNode


@Node "FridayAtEight" "Friday at Eight / Polka Brothers"

@{B}Name:@{UB} Friday at Eight
@{B}Group:@{UB} Polka Brothers

@{B}Year:@{UB} ?
@{B}Event:@{UB} ?
@{B}Placing:@{UB} ?

@{B}Size:@{UB} 0.4 MB
@{B}Requirements:@{UB} ?
@{B}Recommended:@{UB} ?

@{B}Code:@{UB} Airwalk
@{B}Graphics:@{UB} Mount, Colin
@{B}Music:@{UB} Dice, Slide

@{B}Rating:@{UB} **--

+ Great speed, good design, many simple, but interesting effects
- Many of the effects are too similar

@{B}Comment:@{UB} Even if you missed the nicely traced intro picture you wouldn't
 have any doubts about who the authors of this demo are, at least not if
 you have just a little experienced watching demos. The simple, but
 effective Polka design shines right through, the humour too. The credits
 are shown in a hurry, and that's about how the rest of the demo goes, in a
 hurry. There are many effects in it, but non of them are on for more than
 about ten seconds, meaning that you do not get bored watching it. Many of
 the effects are similar, though, as they are often made with wireframe and
 vector graphics (not mapped in any way), which means that you may not want
 to see it again right away. The effects are, among others: Various 3D
 boxes, tunnels made of simple, motion blured wires and vector plates,
 wire pattern routines, an interference effect, etc. No smart transitions
 or bumpmapped, lightsourced, colorcycling, env-mapped, twisting 3D
 objects. Just pure simplicity, elegantly performed with a good sense of
 timing. Also, the system requirements are lowered in this way.
 There are two pieces of music in the demo, and the good timing goes for
 these as well. At first a piece of techno is played, then a funky ballad.
 A strange combination I think, one genre would have been more appropriate.
 As individual pieces of music they are quite okay without impressing. They
 fit well into the demo (it's a matter of taste which one of them should
 have been playing through the entire demo).
 It all ends with a stretching scrolltext, most of the jokes are in
 Danish...!

@{B}Conclusion:@{UB} It's Polka Brothers, it has style, it is recommended!

@EndNode


